<FIRST>r a AM-TeachersStrikes 1stLd-Writethru a0600 09-05 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teachers Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sacramento Teachers Go Out and Idaho Teachers Reach Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Controlled Choice Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: RECASTS lead. SUBS grafs 7-9, `An all-day ...,' with 10 grafs
to UPDATE with events in Pennsylvania, Massachusetts, Montana; picks up
10th graf, `In Michigan ...' ^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers in Sacramento, Calif., went on strike Tuesday after
contract talks broke down, raising the number of students without
classes to more than 110,000.
   In Coeur D'Alene, Idaho, teachers overwhelmingly ratified a new
two-year contract with the school board, ending the threat of a
strike set for Tuesday.
   Walkouts in 12 districts in Illinois, Michigan, Montana, Ohio and
Pennsylvania affected about 66,000 students as of Labor Day.
   Negotiators worked through the holiday to try to head off a
strike in Sacramento, with 48,000 students the biggest district in
the nation to have a walkout.
   Talks broke down about 3 a.m., and teachers were on strike by 7
a.m., officials said. The teachers want a 12.7 percent raise this
year and are seeking class-size limitations and hiring deadlines for
new teachers.
   Elsewhere in California, teachers without a contract for 14
months embraced a last-minute deal so schools could open Tuesday in
San Jose, the state's third-largest city. Details of the agreement
were not released.
   In Pennsylvania, 378 teachers were on strike in three districts
with 5,700 students.
   Strikes began Tuesday in two of those districts. But a walkout
that began in a fourth district, Perkiomen Valley near Philadelphia
with 2,300 students and 159 teachers, ended in a settlement later in
the day.
   In the Upper St. Clair School District in suburban Pittsburgh, an
all-day negotiating session Monday settled a strike by 225 teachers,
and 3,700 students went back to school Tuesday. Teachers in the
Union School District in western Pennsylvania returned to work on a
daily basis.
   In Massachusetts, the 317 teachers in the Boston suburb of
Everett voted unanimously to go on strike in the second walkout in
three years.
   ``We've never had that anywhere in Massachusetts,'' said
Massachusetts Teachers Association spokesman Stephen Wollmer.
   The district, which has 3,900 students, had been scheduled to
reopen Wednesday.
   Teachers in nearby Chelsea agreed to an unusual six-month
contract with Boston University, which is administering the
3,500-pupil school system in an experiment aimed at improving the
troubled schools. The teachers union said it agreed to the short
contract to give the university time to raise money.
   With school scheduled to start over the next 10 days, talks
continued with 28 other locals across the state.
   Schools in the Great Falls district in Montana reopened Tuesday
with 540 substitute teachers for 12,500 students. Only 45 of 723
teachers showed up for work there last week. Salaries top the list
of contract issues.
   Laurel, Mont., teachers voted Saturday to accept a contract
giving them a 2.5 percent raise and returned to work Tuesday.
   In Michigan, teachers in the Jackson and Saginaw Township school
districts were on strike Tuesday.
   In Ohio, no negotiations were held in the Indian Creek and Warren
school districts. In Illinois, pay negotiations continued as a
strike in Quincy entered a second week.
</TEXT>
