<FIRST>r w AM-AideCleared     09-05 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aide Cleared,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Counsel Decides Against Prosecuting Bush Aide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent counsel decided not to prosecute
one of President Bush's aides, who was investigated for a $5,000
loan from a Baltimore brokerage company that required no repayment,
according to a report published Wednesday.
   Former U.S. Attorney Dan K. Webb of Chicago, who served as the
independent counsel in the case, determined there was no evidence to
support prosecuting James W. Cicconi under the Ethics in Government
Act, The Washington Post reported.
   Cicconi is in charge of the White House appointment office.
   Cicconi, reached at home Tuesday night, said he had no comment on
the report.
   Cicconi received the loan in 1984 from First American Mortgage
Co. to cover moving expenses to Austin, Texas, where he planned to
enter private law practice after leaving the Reagan White House.
   Michael Clott, chairman of First American, told invstigators that
the loan was to be a ``sham loan'' and probably would not be repaid.
Clott is serving a 12{ year prison term for fraud and racketeering.
   Cicconi repaid the loan with interest, according to unnamed
sources cited by the Post.
</TEXT>
