<FIRST>r i PM-Kabul-Rockets Bjt   09-05 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kabul-Rockets, Bjt,0857</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Terrorize Kabul At All Hours</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The whoosh and boom of exploding
rockets terrorizes Kabul at all hours of the day and night, creating
a climate of fear not known before in the 11-year-old Afghan civil
war.
   Periods of intense rocketing occurred in the past, especially
last fall, but longtime observers say the barrage that began in June
has been more deadly.
   Between June 25 and Aug. 26, United Nations sources said 577
rockets pounded Kabul, killing 366 people and injuring 999. Nearly
all were civilians, struck at random in homes or offices, at bus
stops, bazaars, movie houses.
   ``We are very, very afraid that rockets will kill all the
people,'' said Mohammad Aqbar, who gave up teaching to earn more
money selling potatoes and onions in the bazaar. ``When we hear the
rockets, we try to hide with our families, but sometimes there is no
place to go.''
   U.N. sources say many Kabul residents in recent weeks have
migrated north, where fewer rockets and cheaper and more plentiful
food await them.
   Most of the rockets hitting Kabul have been Egyptian or
Chinese-made SAKR-20s or SAKR-30s, with a range of about 12{ or 20
miles, though U.S.-backed guerrillas fighting to overthrow the
Soviet-backed government of President Najib say they have SAKR's
with a range up to 38 miles.
   In mid-August, Afghanistan accused the United States and Pakistan
of supplying the guerrillas with new, more lethal long-distance
rockets armed with cluster-bomb warheads.
   The rebels deny firing them, Pakistan calls the allegations
unfounded and the United States refuses to comment.
   The new rockets remain unidentified. Reporters were first taken
to see two rockets bearing the numbers E320-MII@1344 and
E320-MII@138 and no other markings except a tag saying in Arabic
and English, ``Before loading take out safety plug.'' Days later,
they were taken to see the contents of the warhead _98 bombs that
stack into each other.
   Late last month, Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil wrote U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar saying these long-range
missiles scattered cluster bombs with delayed time fuses and
anti-personnel mines which were ``aimed at mass murder and wreaking
havoc and terror in the cities.''
   The first cluster rocket hit Kabul Aug. 15, killing five
civilians and wounding 23 in the former Soviet-occupied Mikrorayan
housing complex near Kabul Airport, now home to many government
workers, the government said. A second struck a dozen children
playing in the Cala-i-Shada district Aug. 19, killing seven and
wounding five.
   ``They are shaped like light-bulb sockets,'' said Asmatullah, an
18-year-old student who lives in the Mikrorayan complex. ``One small
boy took one home and it exploded. He lost his arm.''
   Military experts say the government can defend this mile-high
capital ringed by parched, treeless hills that are a great strategic
advantage. Experts say a conventional guerrilla assault would be
suicidal, given the government's powerful air and land defenses.
   While insignificant in military terms, the rocketing has been a
major psychological weapon.
   Many Kabul residents blame the rocketing on the guerrillas, who
call themselves mujahedeen or Islamic holy warriors, and their
American backers.
   ``Every time there's a rocket, my cook watches and says, `That's
America','' said one foreign relief worker, speaking anonymously.
   ``The American government shouldn't help the mujahedeen with
these rockets. Our people don't want war,'' said Noor Karga, a
cleaner at Avecinna Chest Hospital. He had just watched 22 victims
of rocket attacks being brought in and eight die.
   But more and more, Kabulis blame the government and their Soviet
suppliers as well.
   ``Please tell the Russians and the Americans, don't help with
such sort of weapons,'' said Mohammad Hussein, 32, who was
hospitalized with shrapnel wounds from a rocket attack.
   ``Both sides buy rockets and we hate both of them, the Soviet
Union and the United States,'' said Sayed Salahuddin, an 18-year-old
student, as he walked through the rubble of a neighbor's house that
took a direct hit.
   Before Soviet troops withdrew on Feb. 15, Soviet and Afghan
forces would retaliate immediately against rocket attacks on Kabul
with heavy artillery fire and helicopter gunships hitting suspected
rocket-launching positions. Now, very little counteraction by the
Afghan air force is seen, military observers said.
   The government announced in mid-August it was extending the
security belt around Kabul from 30 kilometers (19 miles) to between
40 and 60 kilometers (25 and 38 miles) to prevent long-range rockets
from hitting the city.
   Abdul Kabir of Younis Khalis' fundamentalist Hezb-i-Islami
guerrilla group told The Associated Press in Pakistan that
Soviet-supplied government rockets, not rebel ones, were hitting
civilian targets in Kabul.
   ``We know that the Kabul government is firing from their own
positions to Kabul city for propaganda purposes,'' to turn civilians
against the guerrillas, he said. ``The enemy (government) is hitting
the hospitals, and bazaars and even the mosques. After this they
show it on TV and blame the mujahedeen.''
   The government strongly denied firing any rockets at Kabul.
</TEXT>
