<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Population     09-05 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Population,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Koreans Live Longer Lives, Have Fewer Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Koreans are living longer and
having fewer children than ever before and by the year 2020 the
country's population growth will be zero, officials said today.
   The average life expectancy for a South Korean child born this
year is 70.1 years, the Korea Institute for Population and Health
said in a report. Women can expect to live 73.3 years and men 66.9
years.
   Life expectancy for American newborns is about 75 years.
   The institute estimated that population will increase 0.97
percent in 1989, with growth slowing to zero in the year 2020 at a
peak of 52 million people. South Korea now has a population of 42
million.
   The average Korean woman now is expected to give birth to 1.6
children, compared with six children in 1960.
   The report said that 77 percent of married women between the ages
of 15 and 44 use some form of birth control, up from 20 percent in
1966.
</TEXT>
