<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-05 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the neighbor's lawnmower is sitting in
your garage because you haven't gotten around to returning it, the
Procrastinators Club of America wants to honor you.
   Today is ``National Be Late for Something Day,'' said Les Waas,
spokesman for the group, and late returners will be honored.
   ``We usually honor somebody, this year we're honoring all
`procrastineighbors' _ the people who borrow the lawnmower and
ladder and tools and those sort of things,'' Waas said Monday.
   ``They procrastinate returning them, thereby preventing us from
doing our chores and giving us time to take naps and have some fun
and enjoy doing other things.''
   Waas said the neighbors have been granted amnesty. ``They don't
have to get them back tomorrow, either,'' he said.
   He said the procrastinators have been celebrating ``Be Late for
Something Day'' for 15 years. About 6,800 people have joined the
group.
   ``We have a half a million members who haven't gotten around to
joining yet,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mattie Juanita Brown's doctor didn't tell her
an apple a day would keep him away, but recommended a substitute
instead: a shot of bourbon and a soda.
   At a celebration for her upcoming 104th birthday, Mrs. Brown said
she's been following the advice faithfully for 51 years.
   ``He told me it couldn't hurt,'' Mrs. Brown said Saturday as
about 30 friends and relatives gathered at her home. ``If it's 4
o'clock, it's highball time.''
   ``I eat what I want when I want, and I've never been on a diet,''
she added.
   Mrs. Brown said she relishes her independence. She has lived
alone since her husband, Leroy, died in 1971. Although she suffers
from cataracts and depends upon hearing aids, she said a nursing
home is out of the question.
   ``I can still take care of myself,'' she said. ``I feel like I do
every day, perfect.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RANGER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Posses are largely a thing of the past in
west Texas, but the Ranger police chief and a justice of the peace
rounded up about 50 men on Labor Day weekend to help corral an
unusual escapee.
   It took a while, but posse members finally surrounded and lassoed
their prey _ a 4-foot-long caiman.
   The alligator-like reptile had broken out of a fenced-in pond and
was spotted Sunday night crawling toward a football field in the
town of about 3,400.
   Justice of the Peace Alford Bush not only led the caiman's
capture, but persuaded his wife, Jackie, to let him keep it
overnight until its owner showed up.
   ``Alford used my extension cord to corral the critter,'' Mrs.
Bush said.
   Ranger Junior College biology professor Jerry Glidewell claimed
the caiman on Monday. He usually keeps the reptile in an aquarium in
his classroom but was keeping it at his home for treatment of a skin
disorder.
</TEXT>
