<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     09-05 0887</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Everyone Who's Anyone is on Yeutter's First-Name List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter is a
breezy, friendly sort. Informality is his style, and that includes
letters to Tom, Dick and Connie on Capitol Hill.
   Just so letter writers in the Agriculture Department's vast
bureaucracy get it straight, they have been issued a manual called,
``Secretary Yeutter's First-Name List for Priority Correspondence.''
   Specifically, it's for letters written in USDA's agencies that
are forwarded to Yeutter for his signature.
   For example, a congressman might complain about USDA meat
inspection, so the department's Food Safety and Inspection Service
is asked to respond with a letter for Yeutter to sign.
   The list is broken down in alphabetical order into House and
Senate segments. There are others for state governors, state
commissioners of agriculture, and cabinet members.
   Each line bears the person's title _ ``Honorable'' for both the
House and Senate _ first name, middle initial, last name, subtitle
such as Jr. or II or III, position such as congressman or senator,
and the diminutives of first names, or nicknames if used. There is
nothing to show the person's political party or state.
   Not every entry has a middle initial, subtitle or diminutive,
such as Bob for Robert or Don for Donald. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., for example, may be Ted to buddies, but he's Edward in
Yeutter's book.
   About half the members of the House and three-fourths of the
Senate are cited for first-name treatment under the heading for
diminutives or nicknames.
   Sen. Charles S. Robb, D-Va., popularly called Chuck by friends
and colleagues, is Charles, while Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa,
is Chuck.
   Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va., is shown as Jay. Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., is listed as Pat, and Sen. Ernest
F. Hollings, D-S.C., is Fritz.
   Sen. Robert Dole, R-Kan., rates Bob in Yeutter's list; Sen.
Christopher S. Bond, R-Mo., is Kit; and Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato,
R-N.Y., is Al.
   In the House, other examples of Yeutter's first-name list include
Rep. Thomas J. Downey, D-N.Y., as Tom, while Rep. Thomas S. Foley,
D-Wash., rates a double listing _ as Tom and as Mr. Speaker.
   Rep. Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., is Dick; Rep. Robert H. Michel,
R-Ill., is Bob; Rep. G.V. Montgomery, D-Miss., is Sonny; Rep.
Charles Pashayan Jr., R-Calif., is Chip; and Rep. Constance A.
Morella, R-Md., is Connie.
   In the cabinet, Secretary of State James A. Baker III is Jim;
Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady is Nick, and Defense Secretary
Richard Cheney is Dick. But Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole, whose
husband rated a Bob, is Elizabeth, not Liddy.
   The first-name list, which is dated Aug. 1, follows a memo
circulated back in March to all undersecretaries, assistant
secretaries and agency heads, informing them that Yeutter ``has
asked several changes be made'' in the preparation of letters for
his signature.
   ``All correspondence should be on a first name basis when
appropriate,'' the memo said.
   If the incoming correspondence to Yeutter says, ``Dear Clayton,''
that is a hint on how to respond, the memo added. But if it says
``Dear Mr. Secretary,'' letter writers should call the office of
Yeutter's executive secretariat for guidance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smaller cotton crop this year is boosting
prices and signaling a reduction in U.S. inventories, according to
Agriculture Department analysts.
   The department's monthly report last week on farm prices in
August showed upland cotton at an average of 64.3 cents per pound,
up from 60.6 cents in July and 53.9 cents in August 1988.
   A report by the department's Economic Research Service said U.S.
cotton production, based on Aug. 1 indications, is forecast at 11.8
million bales, down from 15.4 million last year.
   The cotton acreage planted for 1989 harvest dropped 16 percent to
10.5 million acres, reflecting a larger acreage reduction required
under USDA's price support program.
   Average cotton yields are forecast at 595 pounds per acre, on the
average, down 4 percent from last year. Yields in the Delta and
Southwest are expected to be down 14 percent and 19 percent,
respectively, because of bad weather.
   The total 1989-90 cotton supply is forecast at 19 million bales
for the marketing year that began Aug. 1.
   Allowing for domestic use and exports, the U.S. cotton inventory
by Aug. 1, 1990, could be pulled down to around 3.9 million bales
from an Aug. 1 carryover this year of 7.5 million bales, the report
said.
   ``Although U.S. cotton textile imports are expected to reach
near-record levels and manmade fiber prices have become more
competitive with cotton, domestic mills will likely use 7.7 million
bales during 1989-90,'' the report said. ``Lower textile inventories
and larger denim production should keep domestic mill consumption
strong this season.''
   Domestic cotton use may rise to and average of 23 pounds per
capita, up two pounds from last year, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who take out government crop price
support loans this month will pay a bit less in interest, says the
Agriculture Department.
   Keith Bjerke, executive vice president of the department's
Commodity Credit Corp., said the September rate is 8 percent, down
from 8[ percent for loans made in August.
   The reduction by the CCC reflects the rate charged by the U.S.
Treasury in September, he said.
</TEXT>
