<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cuba-Crash     09-05 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Crash,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Continues For Bodies After Crash Kills At Least 150</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers in Cuba searched for more bodies in
the wreckage of a Cuban jetliner and the homes destroyed when the
plane crashed just after taking off in a thunderstorm, killing at
least 150 people, news reports said.
   Most of the dead were Italians on their way home from a Cuban
vacation.
   At least 600 people continued searching for bodies through pieces
of the chartered Cubana de Aviacion jet and what was left of 33
homes in a Havana suburb, Cuba's official news agency Prensa Latina
reported Monday night.
   The Soviet-made Ilyushin 62, bound for Milan, Italy, exploded
Sunday evening shortly after taking off in a heavy thunderstorm from
Havana's Jose Marti airport, Prensa Latina reported.
   The news agency said flaming debris from the jet plummeted into
neighborhoods on the capital's southern outskirts. It quoted the
Municipal People's Committee in Boyeros, the suburb where the crash
occurred, as saying at least 150 people were killed _ 125 on the
plane and 25 on the ground.
   Only one person, an Italian, survived the crash, officials said.
The neighborhood group said 26 people on the ground were hurt, most
of them seriously.
   A taxi driver and his three passengers riding near the airport
were among the injured, Prensa Latina said.
   ``The explosion lit up the sky,'' one injured person told Cuban
television. ``We thought it was all over,'' said another.
   Cuban and Italian authorities had identified 22 bodies by Monday
evening, including four crewmembers and nine people on the ground,
Prensa Latina reported. It did not release names of victims except
44-year-old Cuban film critic Jose Antonio Gonzalez.
   The news agency reported that 104 bodies had been taken to the
medical examiner's office by Monday night.
   The jetliner was carrying 113 Italian tourists, two Cuban
passengers and a crew of 11, said the Cuban Ambassador Javier
Ardizones in Rome. He confirmed there was one survivor, an Italian.
   The survivor was not identified, nor was the survivor's condition
released.
   The cause of the crash was not determined, but a Foreign Ministry
employee in Rome said the weather appeared to be a factor.
   ``It was very bad, a storm, with rain and lightning,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   A government commission headed by Rogelio Acevedo, president of
the Civil Aeronautics Institute, was investigating, Prensa Latina
said.
   President Fidel Castro visited the crash site and then went to
hospitals where the injured were taken, suffering extensive burns
and multiple fractures, Prensa Latina said.
   Pope John Paul II sent condolences Monday to the families of
victims.
   Prensa Latina described the accident as the worst in the history
of Cubana de Aviacion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0142EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneBaby     09-05 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Baby,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emergency Dispatcher Talks Couple Through Delivery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For David and Sharon Bachman, the
Labor Day weekend was just that. The couple delivered their third
child, this time with the help of a 911 emergency dispatcher.
   Fire Department dispatcher Nancy Fuhrmann was on duty before dawn
Sunday when the frantic Bachman called, saying his wife was having
their third child upstairs, unable to move.
   ``A lot of the effort was in calming him down and telling him
that what he was seeing was normal,'' Ms. Fuhrmann said Monday.
   Ms. Fuhrmann told him how to hold the child's head as it comes
out.
   ``The baby is coming out now ... I see it,'' Bachman said at one
point, as his wife's cries were heard in the background. ``She's
pushing! ... Oh! ... There's the baby's head! Oh my God!''
   ``OK, the baby's out!'' he said, breathlessly.
   ``OK, that's great! Congratulations,'' the dispatcher replied.
   Paramedics arrived at the three-story condominium as the child's
head was appearing, but couldn't get inside the security gate,
Bachman said. After the child was delivered, he rushed down to let
the paramedics in and shouted ``It's a boy!''
   Mrs. Bachman, 24, and little Bryan Allen Bachman returned home
from the hospital late Monday and were doing fine, according to the
25-year-old father, who runs a car lubrication service called
``Greased Lightning.''
</TEXT>
