<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brewery Said to Drop TV Series Tie After Threats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stroh Brewing Co. withdrew $600,000 in
financing for National Audubon Society television specials to save
money and not because of a threatened boycott by loggers unhappy
about an upcoming program on Northwestern forests, the company says.
   ``I want to stress any consideration or thought of canceling
future contributions to the Audubon Society's program productions is
completely independent from concerns related to the upcoming program
``Ancient Forests: Rage Over Trees,''' said Lacey Logan, a
spokeswoman for the Detroit-based brewery.
   But environmental sources, who spoke on the condition they remain
anonymous, said the company had suggested to the Audubon Society
that changes be made in the program to ``make it more favorable to
the loggers'' and that the money was withdrawn when the society
refused to change the program.
   The timber industry and environmentalists have been fighting for
months over the future of logging in the Northwest's old growth
forests, which provide prime habitat for the northern spotted owl.
