<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Chasing Tax Evaders Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department has a new method to try
to find Americans living overseas who cheat on their taxes.
   Hundreds of thousands of Americans living in other countries are
not filing the required tax returns, according to a study by Bryan
L. Musselman of the Internal Revenue Service. In 1986, the General
Accounting Office the losses at between $620 million to $2 billion a
year.
   In 1988, a new law covered Americans who apply for new passports
from U.S. consulates in other countries. American adults who go
abroad need new passports every 10 years; those under 18 need one
every five years.
   Revenue officials are matching the names from the State
Department against their master file to see who is filing tax
returns and who is not.
