<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0444EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-05 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets ,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite repeated interventions by the central bank,
the U.S. dollar rose to a 2{-month high against the Japanese yen
today, while stock prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined
slightly.
   The dollar closed at 146.65 yen, up 0.52 yen from Monday's close.
The currency opened at 145.85 yen and moved in a range between
145.80 yen and 146.65 yen.
   It was the highest close since June 15, when the U.S. unit
finished at 150.30 yen.
   Currency dealers said the Bank of Japan continued to intervene at
levels above 146 yen as Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto indicated
in a Tuesday morning press conference that the central bank would
continue to invervene in the currency market.
   The central bank does not confirm or deny its intervention
activities.
   ``We have no intention of approving a situation that includes
violent exchange rate swings,'' Hashimoto said in a press conference
following a regular Cabinet meeting.
   The dollar's recent rise, which makes Japanese products easier to
sell in the United States, raises fears that improvements in Japan's
trade surplus may be slowed.
   ``The general sentiment of the market is still toward the bullish
dollar, but the anxiety about the central bank's intervention is
keeping the currency from moving up as high as it wants to go,''
said a dealer at Daiichi Kangyo Bank, speaking anonymously.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which gained 135.56 points Monday, fell 41.83 points, or
0.12 percent, to finish at 34,441.95.
   The main barometer of the market started the day in a bullish
mood as exchange rates showed signs of stability. It declined
moderately in afternoon trading as the Japanese yen lost ground
against the U.S. dollar.
   Securities dealer said the relative stability in the currency
market encouraged the investors to buy new stocks in the morning.
   ``The market participants seem to share the feeling it is about
time that the market turn bullish,'' said a dealer at Nikko
Securities Co. ``But trading was still relatively light Tuesday.''
   But dealers said a September rally cannot be expected until
exchange rates settle down.
</TEXT>
