<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0507EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-US     09-05 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-US,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Official Urges U.S. Free Iranian Assets To Help Hostages'
Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western hostages in Lebanon could be
released if the United States shows its good will by freeing
billions of dollars in Iranian assets, a senior Iranian official
says.
   The call was echoed in an interview published today of a Shiite
Moslem cleric in Lebanon who is believed to be a spiritual leader of
the kidnappers.
   Iranian media on Monday quoted Ali Mohammed Besharati, Iran's
deputy foreign minister, as saying that as ``a sign of good will,
the United States should denounce the interference in Iranian
affairs by previous administrations and release the Iranian assets
with no conditions attached.''
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, also quoted Besharati as saying President Bush sent several
letters, the latest three weeks ago, to the Iranian government.
   ``In these letters, the U.S. mentioned issues including Iran-U.S.
relations and the Lebanese situation,'' he said.
   Iran did not reply in writing, he said, but an oral response
``was definitely given through messengers.'' Besharati did not
identify the messengers.
   In Kennebunkport, Maine, where Bush has been vacationing, White
House spokesman Roman Popadiuk responded: ``There has been no
message sent by the president to the Iranian leadership.''
   Besharati said the hostages ``may be released'' if the United
States turns loose the billions of dollars worth of assets,
including military hardware, frozen after the storming of the U.S.
Embassy in Tehran in 1979.
   Iranian officials and news media have in recent months sent
conflicting signals to the United States about whether unfreezing
the assets would help secure freedom for the hostages.
   Sixteen Western hostages are held in Lebanon, most by radical
Shiite Moslems loyal to Iran. Eight are Americans and the one held
longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for
The Associated Press. He was abducted March 16, 1985.
   In its report on an interview with Besharati by the
English-language Tehran Times, IRNA said he believed Bush was making
greater efforts toward conciliation than did Ronald Reagan.
   ``We see the Bush administration has tried to undo many things of
the past,'' Besharati said.
   Hopes for a more moderate attitude toward the West have been
raised by the death June 3 of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's
revolutionary patriarch, and the election to the presidency July 28
of Hashemi Rafsanjani, leader of the ``pragmatist'' faction that
supports closer ties with the West.
   Because of the closed nature of Iranian politics, it is difficult
to assess whether the Besharati comments signaled a new willingness
to negotiate freedom for the hostages.
   Last month, Rafsanjani offered to help work for their release if
the United States adopted a friendlier policy toward Iran, and he
cited frozen Iranian assets as one sore point.
   In an apparent struggle between radical and pragmatist factions
within the Iranian government, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Iran's
spiritual leader, said Aug. 14 that there would be no dealings with
the United States. But Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati on the
same day left open the possibility.
   The day before, IRNA outlined conditions for release of the
hostages, citing the assets.
   An Iranian newspaper, Kayhan International, said Aug. 15 that
unfreezing the assets would not guarantee Iranian help in freeing
the hostages.
   The next day it said the United States can only improve its ties
with Iran by releasing the assets.
   Besharati has made several trips to Lebanon in recent years and
is believed to have influence with Hezbollah, or Party of God, the
pro-Iranian group believed to sponsor Shiite kidnap gangs.
   In an interview published today in the Washington Post, Sheik
Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, believed to be Hezbollah's spiritual
leader, said the Bush administration should stop seeing moves for
unfreezing U.S.-held Iranian financial assets as a potential ransom.
   ``Iran sees that its relations with America do not revolve around
assets and hostages, but around what it considers hostile American
policies against Iran,'' he was quoted as saying in an interview
Saturday at his villa in southern Beirut.
   ``The release of the assets would be an indication of America's
distancing itself from hostile policies,'' he said.
   Fadlallah also called on the United States to look for
``opportunities to improve the conditions and suffering in the cirle
of (Arab) detainees or hostages'' held by Israel or Lebanese
factions, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0526EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PragueRefugees     09-05 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prague Refugees,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 300 East Germans Flood Prague Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 East Germans hoping
to flee to the West have taken refuge in Bonn's embassy in Prague,
creating a ``critical'' situation inside the mission, a diplomat was
quoted as saying today.
   Michael Steiner of the West German Embassy told the Communist
party daily Rude Pravo of a ``continuous influx'' of East Germans
who have camped out on the mission's grounds.
   The mission, housed in the Baroque Lobkowicz palace in Prague's
Mala Strana district, was closed to the public Aug. 23 after about
140 East Germans were reported to have taken refuge there seeking
safe passage to West Germany.
   Scores more have since arrived, apparently climbing over an
unguarded seven-foot fence that surrounds the well-tended embassy
park. Giant tents have been erected in the grounds to house the
refugees.
   Prague government officials have not said if whether they will
follow Hungary's more reform-minded leadership in allowing the East
Germans to go to West Germany.
   Czechoslovakia's entrenched Communist leadership is close to East
German leader Erich Honecker, and seems unlikely to offend him by
allowing the East Germans to flee to the West.
   Bonn was forced to shut its Prague embassy in October 1984, when
about 160 East Germans sought refuge there. They returned home to
East Germany in January 1985 after a hunger strike failed to win
them exit visas, and it is not known if they ever were allowed to
leave later for West Germany.
   Rude Pravo said the embassy compound is currently only ``a
distant reminder of a diplomatic mission.''
   Steiner was said to have praised the ``attitude of Czechoslovakia
as a host country as entirely correct in the solution of technical
matters connected with this extraordinary situation.''
   Several temporary West German visa offices have been opened at
different points around Prague to cope with the task of issuing up
to 6,000 visas a day requested by Czechoslovaks, who are enjoying
new freedom to travel to the West.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
