<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Interview     09-05 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Interview,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Can't Guarantee Taxes Won't Go Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he has to harness his
tendency to sometimes get emotional.
   ``We Bushes cry easily,'' he told British journalist David Frost
in an interview on the lawn of his home in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   The interview was taped Aug. 29 and is scheduled for television
broadcast tonight on Public Broadcasting System.
   Already, Bush has had to contend with the July 31 claim by
terrorists that they had hanged Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins, and
the deaths of 47 USS Iowa crewmen during the April 19 explosion
aboard the ship.
   ``And those get me,'' he said. ``I'm not good at expressing the
concerns of a nation, in matters of national concern like that. I'm
just not very good at it, and so you try not to choke up.
   ``You try to say what you really think, but I feel very moved
when I see those kinds of tragedies. You feel a certain
responsibility, you feel a certain frustration, particularly in
terms of these hostages,'' he said.
   Bush said he recalls turning down several drafts of a speech
about the Iowa because he thought he would become too emotional.
   On July 31, a videotape of Higgins hanging from a noose was
released in Lebanon, and a pro-Iranian Shiite faction claimed
responsibility for the death of the U.S. hostage.
   ``When I saw Colonel Higgins' body displayed in that brutal,
cruel fashion, I had this visceral reaction of wanting to do
something. I still want to do something,'' Bush said.
   ``If I could find a way to surgically go in and free those
American hostages, I would do it.''
   Asked if he expects to renew diplomatic ties with Iran, Bush
replied, ``I'd like to think we could see that day, and I'd welcome
it.
   ``But there has to be a certain modicum of international
decency,'' Bush said, referring to the reported link between Iran
and terrorist groups holding U.S. hostages in Lebanon.
   ``From time to time their officials make statements indicating
they have some control over that situation,'' he said. ``That's got
to change dramatically, before there can be the kind of relations
that I personally would like to see with Iran.''
   Bush also said he will fulfill his campaign pledge to fight for
``no more taxes,'' but added that he can't guarantee Congress won't
act ``in strange and mysterious'' fiscal ways.
   ``What I'm trying to do is fulfill that pledge by going forward
step by step on the budget without raising taxes,'' he said.
   When asked whether he is committed to the tax pledge for his full
four-year term, the president said, ``We're going to succeed this
first year ... and then we've gotta see what happens, but it is my
intention to fight every inch of the way for no more taxes.''
</TEXT>
