<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Guns     09-05 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Guns,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Lawmaker Tried To Smuggle In Hundreds of Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs officials seized more than 300
rifles and handguns from a Philippine congressman and his companion
today after they arrived from the United States, authorities said.
   Zafiro Respicio, chief customs collector at Ninoy Aquino
International Airport, said 314 guns were found in nine bags
identified as belonging to Rep. Nicanor de Guzman and Ponciano Dato.
   The two arrived today on a Philippine Airlines flight from San
Francisco. The guns included .25-caliber and .45-caliber pistols,
.38-caliber revolvers and several assault rifles, Respicio said.
   Respicio said the shipment was discovered when the baggage passed
through the airport's X-ray machines. He also said de Guzman did not
have necessary documents for importing the weapons.
   He said smuggling charges were being prepared against de Guzman
and Dato. The weapons were estimated to be worth $139,000, Respicio
said.
   De Guzman is a member of the Struggle of the Democratic Filipino,
a political party that supports President Corazon Aquino.
   Officials said the bags were being carried by Dato and that the
congressman had left the airport before the shipment was discovered.
   In a radio interview, de Guzman denied the bags containing the
weapons were his and claimed he did not know Dato. De Guzman said he
had been in the United States for about two weeks and that he would
not have had enough time to buy so many weapons under U.S. law.
   De Guzman said he would resign if officials could prove the
weapons were his. House Speaker Ramon Mitra said he was forming a
three-member panel to investigate.
   Mrs. Aquino said she would order Philippine Airlines offices in
the United States to tighten procedures for inspecting baggage
destined for Manila.
   Weapons smuggling is widespread in the Philippines, and officials
estimate there are more than 180,000 unregistered firearms in the
country.
   Also today, customs chief Salvador Mison said inspectors at the
port of Manila found 23 handguns in six boxes sent by a Filipino
living in the United States.
   Officials say the proliferation of unlicensed weapons is a major
cause of the rise of street killings here.
   The incident occurred amid a widely publicized dispute between
Mrs. Aquino and the House of Representatives, the more
pro-administration of the two chambers of Congress.
   Last year, the House tried to import hundreds of pistols, Uzi
submachine guns and Galil assault rifles because members said they
needed additional protection.
   But the guns were turned over to the military and customs
officials after Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos ruled the weapons were
illegally imported. That led to a public outcry over the deal.
   Last week, Mrs. Aquino ordered the confiscated weapons to be
burned to show her ``strong commitment'' to fighting crime.
   But the plan was aborted after Mitra and other congressmen
complained that they had not exhausted all legal appeals for release
of the weapons.
</TEXT>
