<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-05 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in moderately active European
trading today despite repeated intervention by the Bank of Japan in
earlier Asian trading.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Traders said repeated dollar sales by the Japanese central bank
had raised fears of concerted central bank action in Europe, but
that no other major central banks had been sighted in the open
market by midmorning.
   Market participants said the central banks' actions would be
crucial to a market that has little else to trade on. No major U.S.
economic indicators are scheduled for release this week.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.52 yen to a closing 146.65 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 147.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _1.9891 West German marks, up from 1.9780
   _1.7180 Swiss francs, up from 1.7085
   _6.7073 French francs, up from 6.6725
   _2.2383 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2282
   _1,425.50 Italian lire, up from 1,417.50
   _1.1828 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1815
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.5403 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5532 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $358.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $359.00. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $358.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $358.20 compared with $359.00 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 22 cents to close at a bid
359.28.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of 5.06 dollars a troy
ounce, barely changed from Monday's 5.05.
</TEXT>
