<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0637EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-Heroin     09-05 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-Heroin,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 900 Pounds of Heroin Seized, Biggest Ever In Colony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided a house in this British colony and
seized $420 million worth of ``China white'' heroin in what is
believed to be the third largest seizure of the drug, authorities
said today.
   Officers grabbed 924 pounds of more than 90 percent pure heroin
along with two automatic pistols and radio scanners used to monitor
police activity during their raid on the house Monday afternoon.
   Police officials said the drugs were probably bound for the
United States and Australia and were an indication of Hong Kong's
growing role as a conduit of heroin from the Southeast Asia's
``Golden Triangle''.
   Two men, a lifeguard and a driver, and two women, both
homemakers, were arrested at four different locations after the
raid, said Tsang Yam-pui, chief staff officer of the Narcotics
Bureau.
   He told a news conference that the unidentified men and women
were not married and that they would be charged with drug-related
offenses later this week. Police were still looking for three other
men.
   Tsang estimated the street value of the drugs at $420 million.
According to U.S. statistics, it would be enough to supply one out
of every five U.S. addicts for a year.
   Tsang said the seizure capped a 6-month probe of the drug ring.
He said the drugs, which were wrapped in brown paper and displayed
at the news conference, had been smuggled through Thailand and
arrived in Hong Kong by boat after passing through both
international and Chinese waters.
   The drugs arrived in Hong Kong several days ago and more than 100
police officers had been hot on the trail since, he said.
   The drug raid apparently was the second biggest seizure of
``China white'' heroin and the third biggest seizure of heroin ever.
   In January 1988, authorities seized 1.1 tons of ``China white''
packed into bales of rubber on a U.S.-bound ship in the Gulf of
Thailand. In January 1982, authorities in Iran grabbed 1,411 pounds
of ``brown sugar'' heroin, the drug's Middle Eastern variety.
   Tsang said the seizure, which comes at a time of falling heroin
use in Hong Kong, was an indication that gangs here are looking for
international markets for heroin.
   The Hong Kong government today released a report that said new
reports of drug addiction fell in 1988 by about 11 percent when
compared to 1987.
   For several years, U.S. authorities have said Chinese gangs,
based in Hong Kong and Thailand with connections in America, were
moving into the heroin racket in the United States.
   The most recent case illustrating this trend was the FBI's
``Operation White Mare,'' which resulted in the seizure of 828
pounds of ``China white'' in three locations in New York City in
February.
   Arrests were made in the United States, Singapore and Hong Kong.
   The drugs in both the ``White Mare'' case and today's case came
from the ``Golden Triangle,'' which comrpises the border areas of
Thailand, Burma and Laos.
   Tsang said Burma's production of opium, which is the raw material
of heroin, has apparently doubled this year to 2,400 tons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
