<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0825EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SharkAttack     09-05 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shark Attack,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shark Bite Victim Videotaped His Attacker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORRANCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scuba diver said he videotaped a shark
attacking him and used the camera to beat the animal back until he
could swim to safety.
   ``All I could see was its snout,'' Larry Stroup said Monday. ``It
was butting its head against my camera. What surprised me was when
he reached out and grabbed my arm.''
   The camera captured the entire incident, Stroup said. He said
another diver who viewed the tape said it showed the shark
``waggling back and forth, like they do in the movies'' as it clung
to his arm.
   The 46-year-old real estate developer from Albuquerque, N.M.,
displayed his bandaged limbs during a news conference at Harbor-UCLA
Medical Center.
   Dr. Annie Hollister, an orthopedic surgeon, said Stroup would
remain at the facility for four or five days so he could be watched
for signs of infection. She said there a possibility of nerve damage
affecting movement of his thumb.
   Stroup said he was filming a school of about 10 blue sharks,
which were between seven and 10 feet long, about 15 miles off Santa
Barbara Island on Sunday when he swam out of a protective shark cage
to get a better shot.
   ``If as long as there is no erratic behavior it's OK to get out
of the cage,'' he said. Her added that the blue shark ``is not
terribly aggressive.''
   But this particular blue shark bumped his camera about four
times, he said. ``I didn't feel him bite. I just looked over and his
mouth was around my arm,'' he said.
   Using his camera and helped by a fellow diver, he warded off the
shark, and Stroup swam about 35 feet to their boat. A Coast Guard
helicopter flew him to the hospital, where he underwent surgery to
repair torn ligaments and muscle.
   Santa Barbara Island is about 40 miles southwest of Los Angeles.
   Stroup, a diver for five years, said it was his first expedition
to observe sharks.
   ``I'm sure I'll go diving again. Right now I'm not so sure I'll
go shark diving,'' he said. ``I would say that I have a little more
respect for sharks.''
</TEXT>
