<FIRST>r a PM-Prisoner'sPrize     09-05 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prisoner's Prize,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Wins $1,000 in McDonald's Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONWAY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate who was brought a jailhouse meal
from McDonald's peeled an ``instant winner'' game piece from a
medium Coke and won $1,000.
   ``Too bad I won't get it in time for my lawyer,'' said Charles E.
Wilson, after being told it would take up to two months to collect
the prize.
   Wilson, 33, of Brooksville, Fla., was in jail Sunday night
awaiting extradition in a few days to Carthage, Mo., to face a drug
charge when he was brought a fish sandwich, french fries and a Coke.
   ``I thought maybe I'd win a hamburger and they'd pick me up an
extra one,'' said Wilson, who was arrested Thursday night. ``I
pulled it off and said, `Do what?'''
   ``It's pretty good to be sitting in jail and win $1,000,'' he
said.
   City officials said Wilson is apparently the only inmate in the
jail to win a fast-food promotion.
   His chances of winning were 476,000-to-1, said Bob Kennedy,
assistant manager of the Conway restaurant. Kennedy said it might
take up to eight weeks to process the claim.
   Patrolman Lynn Carter said Wilson ``had a real big grin on his
face. He was just elated to say the least. He was just short of
jumping up and down.''
   Several other officers were summoned to look at the game piece.
   ``I just got sick,'' said Patrolman Bill Thessing.
</TEXT>
