<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0462 09-05 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0462,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast In Christian District Kills Two; Demonstrators Surround U.S.
Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with second death, police now saying
blast caused by car bomb, demonstration at U.S. Embassy; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful car bomb jolted a bustling
Christian neighborhood today during a lull in fighting between
Christian and Syrian forces, killing two people and wounding seven,
police said.
   Also today, hundreds of Christians demonstrated at the U.S.
Embassy to protest Washington's policy in Lebanon. Organizers said
the protesters would remain there until U.S. Ambassador John
McCarthy presents his credentials to the Christian government.
   Police said a Mercedes sedan rigged with 88 pounds of explosives
blew up at 9:20 a.m. near a vegetable market in the Mokalles
district in northeast Beirut.
   A police spokesman said experts were puzzled by the blast. He
said a fuse and two anti-tank missiles in the car did not explode,
saving the area from a catastrophe. But other explosive material in
the vehicle apparently went off.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
regulations, said a pedestrian and a man in a sedan parked near the
Mercedes were killed. All the wounded also were civilians.
   The explosion set ablaze seven vehicles, including a Lebanese
army jeep, knocked down power poles and shattered windows.
   Voice of Lebanon, the main radio station in Christian east
Beirut, at first said the blast was caused by a car bomb, then
reported that an anti-tank mine went off under a civilian car.
   By police count, 28 people were killed and 218 wounded in five
previous car bombings in Lebanon this year.
   Police said 15 people were killed, and 150 wounded when a car
bomb exploded in Beirut's Christian district of Jal el-Deeb on March
17.
   Syrian and Christian gunners skirmished with mortars across
Beirut's dividing Green Line and in mountain towns east and
northeast of the capital. Police said one person was killed and
three were wounded.
   But the exchanges were limited to the frontlines, allowing
Beirut's shrunken population to venture out to shop for food or
check on property. The Mokalles market was packed with shoppers at
the time of the blast.
   By police count, the 6-month-old confrontation betwen Gen. Michel
Aoun's 20,000 troops and Syria's 40,000-strong force has killed 827
people and wounded 2,452.
   About 1,000 Christian youths gathered along a barbed-wire
barricade at the entrance of the U.S. Embassy compound and demanded
that Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun be recognized the
country's legitimate prime minister.
   Sources at the embassy, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
McCarthy was not at the compound today.
   ``We declare the beginning of the peaceful siege of the U.S.
Embassy,'' Jubran Tueini, one of the organizers of the march, said.
   ``McCarthy go home, McCarthy go home,'' the crowd chanted.
   The latest round of fighting began March 8, two days after Aoun
imposed a blockade on illegal ports run by Syria's militia allies in
south Beirut.
   The Syrians and allied Moslem forces retaliated by shelling and
besieging the 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of Beirut.
Aoun then declared a ``war of liberation'' against the Syrian army
in Lebanon.
   Damascus moved troops into Lebanon in 1976 under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, is competing
for legitimacy with Aoun's three-man Christian cabinet. McCarthy,
who took up his post in Septembar 1988, has not submitted his
credentials to either cabinet.
   Tueini said the siege would continue until McCarthy ``submits his
credentials to the legitimate Lebanese authorities represented by
Gen. Aoun.''
   Tueini, publisher of the weekly An-Nahar Arab Internationa, said
initially that U.S. Embassy staff will be allowed to move in an out
of the compound. But if the demands of his group were not met
``we'll increase the dose'' of the siege.
   Aoun has complained about what he said was U.S. ``indifference''
and ``tacit support'' of Syria in its war against his army.
   The United States, a traditional backer of the pro-Western
Christians, has avoided taking sides in the latest confrontation,
calling repeatedly for a cease-fire but making no accusations.
   Tueini called on Washington to dispatch an official envoy to
Lebanon ``like the Soviets and French.'' French and Soviet envoys
visited Lebanon, Syria and other Arab countries last week to discuss
proposals for a settlement of Lebanon's 14-year civil war.
</TEXT>
