<FIRST>r a PM-Miami-Haiti     09-05 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miami-Haiti,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Aided Haiti Even During U.S. Cut-off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city of Miami donated 22 surplus vehicles to
Haiti's military government after U.S. aid was suspended,
infuriating some Haitian exiles.
   ``For us, that was a slap in the face,'' said Jacques Despinosse,
president of the Haitian American Democratic Club.
   Late last year the city sent vehicles that included a front-end
loader with backhoe, five dump trucks and 10 garbage packers to
Haiti. The equipment was worth $114,800 used but would cost more
than $1 million new, officials said.
   The shipment went unnoticed by Haitian exile leaders until they
heard government officials had fought over the equipment in
Port-au-Prince.
   Mayor Xavier Suarez said in retrospect, city officials should
have consulted with Haitian exile leaders.
   The Miami Herald reported on Monday that a Haitian exile
businessman had suggested to City Commissioner Miller Dawkins that
officials do something to clean up Haiti's streets. Dawkins brought
up the idea in November. After visiting Haiti, he proposed shipping
the equipment to Haiti and won approval.
   Haiti changed military leaders when Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril
overthrew Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy in September. U.S. direct aid to the
Haitian government was suspended after November 1987 elections were
canceled by violence.
   Haiti's consul general in Miami, Antonio Jean-Poix, defended the
shipment as a humanitarian gesture.
</TEXT>
