<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0911EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugLaw     09-05 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Law,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Canton Drug Law Sparks Criticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union says it
will watch closely when the city make any arrests under a new
ordinance that, among other things, makes it illegal to be in a park
where drugs are sold.
   ``It's just too broad,'' said Elinor Alger, legal director of the
Ohio ACLU. ``I know it's getting after crack houses. But I think it
puts enormous responsibility on individuals who may be engaged in
innocent activity.''
   Last week the City Council approved the ordinance after Mayor Sam
Purses called for police to ``bump right up against the line''
between legal and illegal methods in the pursuit of drug dealers.
   The ordinance forbids people to ``enter, visit or remain in or
about any place or premises ... including but not limited to rooms,
apartments, buildings, motor vehicles, yards or parks where (illegal
drugs) are manufactured, sold, dispensed, furnished, given away,
stored or used with knowledge that such activity is occurring or
being reckless in that regard.''
   ``They might as well shut the parks down,'' said Harvey Gittler,
executive director of the ACLU's Ohio chapter.
   ``Theoretically, I couldn't go into a public park if I knew
another person in the park because that person might be selling
drugs and that would make me subject to arrest.''
   Ms. Alger said the ACLU will investigate any arrest that seems to
violate constitutional rights. As of Monday, there had been no
arrests under the law, police said.
   City Law Director Tom Bernabei said the city is re-examining the
ordinance's language. ``If it needs to be tightened up we will do
so. We don't want to pass an unconstitutional law, '' he said.
   ``But we have a problem in Canton with drugs,'' Bernabei said.
``We also want to be creative in the laws that we adopt in pushing
the edge of what is or what may be constitutionally prohibited.''
   In June, several gunshots were fired into the house of a city
councilman who has campaigned against drugs and gangs, which he and
others say have moved into Canton from Los Angeles, Detroit,
Baltimore and Jamaica.
   No one was injured.
</TEXT>
