<FIRST>r a PM-KalamazooDrugs 1stLd-Writethru a0422 09-05 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kalamazoo Drugs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0422,0839</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kalamazoo Fights Big-City Drug Problem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 16th graf pvs, `The assets ...' with four grafs to ADD
Ohio ordinance.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sadie Miles looked through her living
room window and pointed out the boarded-up crack house across the
street and the blatant drug deals occurring outside in the afternoon.
   ``This isn't supposed to happen in Kalamazoo,'' she said with a
sigh as she reminisced about life when she moved to the northside
neighborhood with her parents in 1962.
   But residents of this southwestern Michigan city are learning
firsthand that no place is immune to the drug epidemic.
   Six drug-related homicides since April are among dozens of
shootings in Miles' neighborhood this year. On Aug. 23, a masked
gunman demanding cash and crack fired randomly into two separate
crowds, wounding six, including an 18-year-old pregnant woman whose
fetus did not survive.
   ``It's like someone took the worst place in Detroit and dropped
it here. The only difference is that this place is so small, the
problem affects everybody,'' said one former crack addict at Safe
House, a neighborhood recovery center.
   Authorities believe Kalamazoo's location between Detroit and
Chicago on Interstate 94 has played a large role in the escalating
problem. Because Detroit is saturated with crack, a dealer in
Kalamazoo can charge three or four times as much for that highly
addictive form of cocaine.
   Police are fighting back with some get-tough approaches that many
residents applaud but civil libertarians find troublesome.
   A new law that has resulted in about 50 arrests since May makes
it illegal to loiter in any house, vacant lot, or other place where
drugs or drug paraphernalia are sold, used or stashed.
   About 85 percent of those arrested under the ordinance have been
charged with more serious drug offenses.
   The law, adopted in various forms in several other cities, has
been criticized by the American Civil Liberties Union on grounds
that it violates the right to freedom of association. A Kalamazoo
judge upheld the law in July.
   ``People here are so fed up with the shootings, the deaths, they
are willing to accept almost anything _ constitutional or
unconstitutional _ to bring about relief,'' said Tilman Cothran,
president of the local chapter of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
   Many residents want even tougher enforcement of the law by police.
   ``The ones who are calling all of this unconstitutional don't
live here,'' said the Rev. Otha Gilyard, pastor of Mount Zion
Baptist Church and president of the Northside Association for
Community Development. ``This is a crisis situation. This is war.''
   Police also plan to target the assets of suspected drug dealers _
even if they don't have enough evidence for criminal charges.
   ``If we believe you're involved in drug trafficking, ... and we
see you're living a lifestyle that would be higher than what you'd
have legitimate income for, we're going to seize your assets and
you'll have to prove how you came across them legally,'' said Capt.
Scott Dolfman, who heads the Public Saftey Department's Special
Investigations Unit.
   In Canton, Ohio, the American Civil Liberties Union has said it
will watch closely when the city make any arrests under a new
ordinance that, among other things, makes it illegal to be in a park
where drugs are sold.
   ``I know it's getting after crack houses. But I think it puts
enormous responsibility on individuals who may be engaged in
innocent activity,'' said Elinor Alger, legal director of the Ohio
ACLU.
   Canton's City Council approved the ordinance last week after
Mayor Sam Purses called for police to ``bump right up against the
line'' between legal and illegal methods in the pursuit of drug
dealers.
   In Kalamazoo, assets seized from suspected pushers will go
directly into the 3-month-old Drug Asset Seizures and Forfeiture
Unit.
   Civil libertarians object to the plan.
   ``Assuming someone is guilty and taking their property until they
are proven innocent sure doesn't sound like the United States,''
said John Powell, ACLU national legal director.
   ``This shows the community _ like the rest of the country _ is
frustrated with drugs and is desperate. But it's important that the
first casualty of this fight against drugs not be the Bill of
Rights, the Constitution, our democratic society.''
   Despite these efforts, the police seem to be losing the war.
   ``Drug trafficking is worse now than it's ever been, and it's
going to get worse,'' said Dolfman, who added that the problem is
caused in part by a lack of space in county jails.
   Some residents refuse to accept such dismal predictions.
   ``I've seen plenty of people move away, but I've made up my mind
to stay,'' said Miles, whose well-maintained home stands in contrast
with the weed-choked lots and dilapidated houses on her street.
``Why should I leave? I want the problem to leave.''
</TEXT>
