<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     09-05 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Lawmaker, Nine Killed In Sinhalese Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman walked into the office of a
former lawmaker today and fatally shot him while four accomplices
stood guard outside, military officials said.
   The killing of Merril Wijeyesena Kariyawasam, chairman of the
state-owned Rubber Research Institute, was blamed on anti-government
radicals of the People's Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese
group trying to overthrow the government.
   Kariyawasam's bodyguard was injured in the attack in Ratmalana
town, 10 miles south of Colombo, said the officials, who cannot be
indentified under briefing rules.
   Kariyawasam was a senior official of the governing United
National Party's trade union, the National Workers Union. He had
represented the Agalawatte constituency in southern Sri Lanka in
Parliament.
   The military officials said nine more deaths were reported during
a 24-hour period ending today in ethnic violence inspired by the
militants. The victims included three radicals who were shot and
killed by security forces, the officials said. They gave no details.
   Six bodies were found today in different parts of the country,
the official said. He accused Sinhalese militants of the killings.
   The government says more than 5,000 people have died in the
front's 2-year-old campaign to topple the government.
   The radicals are protesting concessions made in a July 1987
accord with the minority Tamils, who are demanding a separate nation
in the northeast.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
the Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the population.
   A senior military official said today that the Sinhalese front
had built up an army of about 7,500 men and armed them with
sophisticated weapons. The militia is supported by 2,000 activists,
said the official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Defense officials had earlier estimated that the front had 2,500
hard-line members.
   Sri Lanka's security forces comprises about 103,000 members,
including 50,000 in the army, 7,000 in the navy, 4,000 in the air
force and 42,000 policemen.
</TEXT>
