<FIRST>r p PM-Coelho'sSeat 1stLd-Writethru a0456 09-05 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho's Seat, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0456,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coelho's Downfall Not Big Issue In Race To Succeed Him</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to raise election rules, restore dropped
words to 7th graf pvs, `The race ...'; PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, `In the ...';
DELETES 17th graf pvs, `Under California's ...' to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MODESTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Democratic Whip Tony Coelho left
Congress under a cloud of ethical questions, but no candidate in the
campaign for his seat has bad words about him.
   Abortion, highway congestion, agriculture problems, Middle East
hostages and the candidates' experience seem to be getting more
attention than congressional ethics and Coelho's departure from the
House.
   Instead of keeping his distance, the lone Democrat in the race,
Assemblyman Gary Condit, has used TV ads and mailings that stress
his ties to Coelho.
   ``What's happened is that both sides have done polling. I am very
positive in the district. They decided it would backfire if they
took me on,'' said Coelho, who had held the seat since 1978.
   The special election is on Sept. 12. Under California's rules,
all candidates will appear on the same ballot. If no one gets more
than 50 percent, the top finisher of each party will take part in a
runoff Nov. 7.
   Coelho resigned on June 15, his 47th birthday, after failing to
report a $50,000 loan from a savings and loan. The money was used
for a junk bond deal set up by the firm's chief executive officer.
   The race to succeed Coelho is the fourth congressional contest
this year. Democrats have won two. Republican Ileana Ros-Lehtinen
last week won the Florida seat held for 27 years by Democrat Claude
Pepper, who died May 30.
   Elections will also be held to fill House seats that belonged to
Speaker Jim Wright, who resigned while under an ethics
investigation, and Mickey Leland, D-Texas, and Larkin Smith,
R-Miss., who died in plane crashes.
   In the California race, a couple of GOP candidates say
congressional ethics is an issue. But the leading Republican, former
state agriculture director Clare Berryhill, says the subject hasn't
caught on with voters.
   ``You'd think it would be an issue ... (but) the local people
don't seem to be that upset,'' Berryhill said. ``When he came back,
they almost welcomed him like a hero. That's why I am saying,
people, they talk about ethics ... but do they really care?''
   Coelho said there was nothing improper about the $50,000 loan and
that it wasn't disclosed because of a clerical error.
   His political problems coincided with the Wright's downfall,
magnifying them and for a time giving Republicans two prominent
targets, something Coelho said he wanted to avoid.
   Coelho's former district and its predecessors have been in
Democratic hands since B.F. Sisk, Coelho's former boss, won the seat
in 1954. Coelho captured the district in 1978 when Sisk retired, and
rose through the ranks to become whip, the No. 3 post in the House
Democratic hierarchy.
   The district stretches through the heart of the San Joaquin
Valley farm belt, then juts east into the Sierra Nevada to take in a
portion of Yosemite National Park.
   Democrats make up about 55 percent of the district's voters. But
the area tends to be conservative on many issues and Berryhill sees
a tight race.
   ``I think it's going to be like every race I have been in. I
think it's going to go down to the wire,'' Berryhill said.
   Condit, a moderate-to-conservative Democrat who has spent 6{
years in the state Assembly, probably is best known in California as
a member of the Gang of Five _ rebel Democrats who tried
unsuccessfully to topple Speaker Willie Brown last year.
   Eight candidates will be on the ballot: Condit, six Republicans
and Roy Shimp, a Libertarian. Two Republicans discontinued
campaigning after Berryhill was endorsed by state and local party
leaders.
   The other GOP candidates are Cliff Burris, a contractor who
stresses ``family values;'' Robert Weimer, a farmer and farm
equipment manufacturer; and Dave Williams, a food packaging engineer.
</TEXT>
