<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Walesa 1stLd-Writethru a0492 09-05 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Walesa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Calls for European Unity on West German Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with Walesa's quotes; picks
up graf 5th graf pvs: During his ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa
arrived in West Germany today and called for East and West to
overcome economic and political barriers, creating a Europe ``where
everyone feels that they are free.''
   Walesa spoke upon arrival at Duesseldorf airport at the start of
a five-day visit to West Germany.
   He is expected to lobby for Western aid to help promote Polish
reform under the new government of Solidarity activist Tadeusz
Mazowiecki, who was named last month as the East bloc's first
non-Communist government leader.
   In his remarks today, Walesa called for a strong and united
Europe, ``a Europe in which there is a place for everybody and where
everyone feels that they are free.
   ``We have the chance to work together fruitfully. From the
airplane, I saw that we are indeed a united Europe, but it is hilly
here and there, and there are also other obstacles,'' Walesa told
reporters through an interpreter.
   ``I believe that these hills, obstacles and walls can be
removed,'' he said. ``We must above all think about humanity. We
must above all consider that no one can be allowed to dominate
another. We must think about the past when many people suffered
losses _ we too.''
   ``We have thought about many of these losses for 50 long years
now. That cannot be repeated,'' Walesa said.
   Poland and West Germany are still struggling for reconciliation
50 years after World War II began with Nazi Germany's attack on
Poland.
   Since the war, however, West Germany has built strong business
ties with Eastern Europe. The United States has suggested Bonn take
the lead in the West's efforts to support East bloc reform.
   During his West German stay, Walesa is to meet with high-ranking
government officials including Chancellor Helmut Kohl; the
Duesseldorf-based German Labor Federation; and Ruhr Valley steel
workers and industrialists.
   ``The chancellor and Lech Walesa on Thursday will be discussing
the situation in Poland following the government changeover,
economic conditions there, international aid measures for Poland,
and the future cooperation between our two countries,'' Kohl's chief
spokesman, Hans Klein, told reporters Monday.
   Kohl has pledged West German aid for Poland, but the two sides
have been unable to agree on how much.
   Differences between the two countries spoiled Kohl's hopes of
traveling to Poland as a symbolic gesture of goodwill marking the
50th anniversary of the start of the war.
   Relations between Europe's two largest countries have also been
strained by recent suggestions of West Germany's conservative
finance minister, Theo Waigel, that Polish lands once part of the
German empire technically still belong to Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
