<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Brewer-SADD     09-05 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Brewer-SADD,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anheuser-Busch to Donate Money to Alcohol Awareness Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stung by allegations that concerts sponsored by
beer companies encourage minors to drink, the nation's biggest
brewer said it will donate $250,000 to Students Against Driving
Drunk in Texas.
   The money will help provide SADD chapter start-up kits to all
Texas junior and senior high schools, Stephen J. Burrows,
Anheuser-Busch vice president for consumer awareness and education,
said Monday.
   Anheuser-Busch and Miller Brewing Co. were criticized for
sponsoring large outdoor music festivals in seven Texas cities over
Labor Day weekend.
   Both brewers took precautions to prevent underage drinking and
the events, which drew 500,000 people, were without major problems,
police said.
   SADD, founded in 1981, is a student-run organization that uses
peer pressure to discourage alcohol and drug use. It has 4 million
members nationwide.
</TEXT>
