<FIRST>u i PM-Demjanjuk 1stLd-Writethru a0505 09-05 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Demjanjuk, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0505,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Asks Appeal Delay, Citing New Evidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th pvs, `He was...,' to ADD dropped reference to Nazi-occupied
Poland. Pick up 5th pvs, `The Ukrainian...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for John Demjanjuk said he had new
evidence to show his client is not a Nazi war criminal and asked the
Supreme Court today to postpone an appeal hearing on his conviction
and death sentence.
   The evidence includes at least four documents recovered from a
garbage pail at the Justice Department in Washington that contradict
key testimony given against Demjanjuk at his trial, laywer Yoram
Sheftel said in a telephone interview.
   Demjanjuk, 69, a retired Ohio autoworker, was found guilty by an
Israeli court in April 1988 of crimes against humanity and crimes
against the Jewish people. He was sentenced to death.
   He was identified by witnesses as a sadistic guard known as
``Ivan the Terrible'' at the Treblinka death camp in Nazi-occupied
Poland, where 850,000 Jews perished in 1942-1943.
   The Ukrainian-born Demjanjuk has claimed to be a victim of
mistaken identity. He appealed the verdict on June 30, 1988, and
after several postponements the appeal was scheduled to be heard
starting Nov. 1.
   In two petitions filed today, Sheftel asked for a delay of
Demjanjuk's appeal hearing for at least six months, citing documents
found several weeks ago at the Justice Department's Office of
Special Investigations, which probes suspected Nazi war criminals.
   Sheftel said that in one document, a key witness against
Demjanjuk, former Nazi prison guard Otto Horn, is said to have
failed to identify him in a photo line-up, contradicting claims in
court that Horn recognized Demjanjuk.
   He accused the Justice Department of ``concealing important
evidence on the one hand and falsifying other evidence'' in
proceedings which stripped his client of U.S. citizenship in 1981,
paving the war for his extradition to Israel five years later.
   ``We have reports there are other (Justice Department) documents
like these, which they have hidden until now,'' Sheftel said, adding
that the case was already under investigation in Washington.
   Among the witnesses who identified Demjanjuk as the notorious
guard Ivan were several Treblinka survivors who gave emotional
testimony at his trial.
   Demjanjuk's attorneys failed in their attempts to persuade the
court that too much time had elapsed since the war for positive
identification and that their client was a prisoner of war during
the period in question.
</TEXT>
