<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-US     09-05 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US,0180</SECOND>
<UNK>Aquino Names Council Members to Draft Alternative Uses of U.S. Bases</UNK>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino on Tuesday
appointed a council to propose alternative uses for U.S. military
bases in case Manila and Washington do not renew the agreement under
which they operate in the Philippines.
   The 17 members of the Executive-Legislative Bases Council include
provincial governors, Cabinet undersecretaries, business leaders and
congressional members. The council is to convene next week.
   Congress created the council in July to study proposals on the
uses of U.S. bases in case Americans vacate them. The agreement on
the six installations, including Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay
naval base, expires in 1991, and many Filipino politicians have
called for the installations to be closed.
   U.S. and Filipino officials are expected to begin talks on a new
agreement late this year.
   Congressional leaders have proposed moving the airport and other
government buildings to Clark Air Base, 50 miles north of Manila.
They have suggested converting the Subic Bay base into a repair
facility for commercial vessels.
