<DOCNO> AP890905-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Venezuela     09-05 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Venezuela,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Drug Barons Moving to Brazil, Venezuela, Envoy Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Drug Plan Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's war on drugs in alliance with the
United States will move drug kingpins to neighboring Brazil and
Venezuela, Venezuelan Ambassador Alberto Consalvi said today.
   ``Brazil and Venezuela, among Colombia's most sensitive
neighbors, are in the midst of election campaigns and the extreme
divisions of the political leadership do not permit them to ...
agree on questions of vital importance such as defense against the
drug cartels,'' Consalvi said in an interview.
   Consalvi is a close ally of Venezuelan President Carlos Andres
Perez. Perez took office in February and his position was shaken
almost at once by bloody rioting over price rises. State and local
elections are to be held in Venezuela in December.
   Brazilians will vote in November to replace President Jose Sarney.
   ``Big areas in Colombia's neighbors that are not adequately
policed will be irresistible to the drug barons,'' Consalvi said.
   He said that in Venezuela, politicians seem to be losing
perspective on the risks in the drug war.
   ``In some countries and in important parts of their economy, the
presence of drug money has already been seen, and it stimulates the
economy mysteriously at a time of crisis,'' he said. ``The
penetration of drug money is one of the most insidious problems in
Latin America.''
   Consalvi added that the message being sent from this country is
that Latin Americans should limit their conflicts in view of the
common danger, not only of losing control of their economies to the
drug traffickers but also of interference in politics.
   ``What is happening in Colombia can happen in any other
country,'' he said.
   ``Political leaders can only avoid it by acting in time. It's a
race against the clock.''
</TEXT>
