<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea-US     09-05 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea-US,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Protest U.S. Food Imports</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of South Korean farmers marched
outside a Seoul hotel Tuesday to demand cancellation of an American
food fair they say signals a U.S. invasion of the Korean
agricultural market.
   Two small groups of farmers shouted ``Stop the food fair'' as
they tried to march into the Hilton Hotel complex downtown, where a
U.S. Embassy-sponsored food fair is to be held Wednesday through
Saturday.
   Police said they arrested about 30 farmers but released all of
them a few hours later.
   About a dozen protesters, identifying themselves as members of
the National Council of Farmers, appeared just before a reception
honoring the U.S. food exposition was held in the hotel's grand
ballroom.
   ``Stop the food fair!'' farmers shouted as they unfurled a large
banner reading ``We oppose food imports which kill 10 million
farmers.''
   Police grabbed placards reading ``Yankee go home'' and chased
protesters around the hotel parking area.
   Ninty minutes later, another group of 40 farmers began a march
along a road leading to the hotel but were stopped by about 100
police officers. Several protesters were arrested.
   The National Council of Farmers, which claims to represent 11
nationwide groups, said it would hold protests until it halted the
food fair, which it said ``signals a U.S. invasion.''
   Lee Kyong-hae, chairman of the National Council of Young Farmers
and Fishermen, issued a statement saying his 45,000-member
organization ``cannot just idly watch the American attempt to invade
our market, shaking our agricultural industry to its roots.''
   South Korean farmers have staged violent protests demanding a
halt to imports of U.S. agricultural products. They say the imports
threaten their livelihood by destroying the domestic market.
   Washington has pressured Seoul to open its markets to help
decrease South Korea's $8.5 billion trade surplus with the United
States.
   South Korea purchased $2.25 billion worth of American farm
products last year, becoming Washington's second-largest
agricultural customer after Japan. The volume is expected to
increase 15 percent to 20 percent this year, government officials
say.
   The 63 companies represented in the food fair have products that
all have been approved for export to South Korea, the embassy said.
They include everything from jelly, wine and prunes to microwave
popcorn.
   Marilyn Bonin of the California Department of Agriculture said
about half the products in the show are from California. Asked if
protests concerned her, she said ``Not at all. Change is hard, and
we've had farmers protests in the States also.''
   Frank Morrison of Clearwater, Neb., was in Seoul to market his
microwave popcorn.
   ``We were told protests would be peaceful,'' he said. ``They have
to know that as a country, they can't continue to just export, but
will have to import also. It will take time to change.''
   The protesters Tuesday issued a statement that included a large
cartoon of Uncle Sam, dressed as Batman with fangs, arriving in
Seoul, and Korean farmers dying in their fields.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
