<FIRST>u a PM-CouncilTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0474 09-05 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Council Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0474,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Voting Rights Trial in Dallas Gets Under Way</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with trial under way. PICKS UP
5th graf pvs, `It is ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The way Dallas elects its City Council _ an issue
voters supposedly decided only weeks ago _ went before a federal
judge today, who could order changes if he finds minorities aren't
getting a fair shake.
   A lawyer for two blacks who ran unsuccesfully for City Council
opened the trial by saying blacks have trouble getting elected
because of Dallas' system, under which some candidates are elected
from districts and some from the city as a whole.
   ``Subtle or not so subtle, racial discrimination has occurred in
past City Council elections,'' said Betsy Julian, attorney for Roy
Williams and Marvin Crenshaw. They sued in 1988 and were joined by a
Hispanic group, alleging that the set-up dilutes minority voting
power.
   But Paul Pearce, an attorney for the city of Dallas, said no
pattern can be established that shows the apportionment
discriminates against minorities.
   ``In the last 14 elections, since 1983, the black preferred
candidate has been successful in nine races,'' he said.
   Williams and Crenshaw are asking U.S. District Judge Jerry
Buchmeyer to order the city to restructure the council into 15
districts.
   On Aug. 12, voters approved a plan under which the mayor would be
elected at large and other council members would be elected from
``super districts,'' but that plan does not go into effect for two
years.
   ``It is about self-determination and an end to apartheid in this
city,'' said Crenshaw. ``Dallas is one of the few cities that didn't
receive a challenge from the African-American community during the
civil rights movement of the 1960s. Now, it's Dallas' time.''
   The city denies that the current apportionment discriminates
against minorities. The city claims that the voters' right to pick
their system of government is at stake and it denies that the
current system is discriminatory.
   Both sides say the outcome will shape the Dallas city government
for years. Any judicial precedents that are set could affect local,
state and federal voting districts throughout the nation.
   Minority leaders long have said the city is dominated by its
business community and predominantly white north Dallas
neighborhoods.
   The current council, governing a population estimated to be 51
percent minority, consists of nine non-Hispanic whites, two blacks
and no Hispanics.
   Under Dallas' 8-3 council system, eight members are elected in
single-member districts, and three, including the mayor, are elected
at-large.
   The new 10-4-1 system, scheduled to go into effect in 1991, would
include 10 council members from single districts, four from
quadrants or ``super districts,'' and only the mayor would be
elected at-large.
   Betsy Julian, attorney for the plaintiffs, called the plan ``too
little, too late,'' and said it was a ``last-minute, peace-keeping
concession to maintain the status quo.''
   ``We will show there is a long history of racially polarized
voting in the city of Dallas,'' Ms. Julian said.
   Some say the case will influence realignments on all levels of
government after the 1990 census.
   ``The Dallas hearing is the first of many related cases,'' said
Sonya Jarvis, executive director of the Washington-based National
Coalition of Black Voter Participation. ``It will be a microcosm of
what's going to happen around the nation following the 1990 census.''
   Dallas' 10-4-1 plan emerged after Mayor Annette Strauss appointed
a multiethnic business and civic group to find solutions to racial
tension in the city following a series of deadly confrontations
between minority citizens and police.
   Black and Hispanic leaders opposed the 10-4-1 plan, which was
approved 41,456 to 20,823 in a turnout of less than 14 percent of
registered voters. Analyses by precinct showed whites voted for the
plan and blacks and Hispanics against it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
