<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0481,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Season's Strongest Hurricane Gets Stronger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with latest position; PICKS UP
7th graf pvs, `The storm ...'; SUBS next-to-last graf to UPDATE with Felix's
position.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Caribbean's easternmost islands reported large
swells and heavy surf as Gabrielle, the most powerful hurricane of
the Atlantic season, tossed gale-force winds today in a
400-mile-wide spiral.
   Meanwhile, Tropical Storm Felix was upgraded to a hurricane early
today after its sustained winds topped 74 mph, but was in the middle
of the northern Atlantic and posed no threat to land, the National
Hurricane Center reported.
   With top winds of 130 mph, Gabrielle's center was expected to
pass north of Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands today.
   ``It's a very large storm,'' hurricane specialist Jim Gross said
today. ``We don't have anything that looks like it would deflect it
right now.''
   As of noon EDT, Gabrielle was centered near 21.1 north latitude
and 57.9 west longitude, 550 miles east-northeast of San Juan,
Puerto Rico. It was moving northwest at 12 mph.
   Forecasters expected the season's fourth hurricane to strengthen
and hold its course through Wednesday morning but said they wouldn't
know until it nears the Bahamas on Friday whether it will hit the
U.S. mainland or veer north.
   ``The storm is actually a long way away from any potential
impact,'' said Bob Sheets, director of the National Hurricane
Center, who nevertheless warned people in U.S. coastal areas to
follow its progress closely.
   Tropical-storm force winds of at least 39 mph were spotted 250
miles northeast of Gabrielle's center on Monday and 150 miles in the
opposite direction.
   Gabrielle formed Thursday near the Cape Verde Islands off Africa.
Its growth has been typical of some of the most destructive
hurricanes, forecasters said.
   Little additional strengthening was expected for Hurricane Felix,
which barely crossed the 74 mph threshold for hurricanes at 6 a.m.
and had 80 mph winds at noon.
   Its center was near 36.7 north latitude and 49.0 west longitude,
or 975 miles west of the Azores. It was drifting north-northwest at
5 mph.
   The Atlantic hurricane season runs from June to November.
</TEXT>
