<HEAD>At Least 400 Die During Holiday Weekend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with late totals.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 400 people died in accidents on the
nation's roads during the Labor Day weekend.
   As of 1 p.m. EDT today, law enforcement and other authorities had
reported 431 fatalities.
   The National Safety Council projected last week that there could
be between 420 and 520 traffic deaths over the three-day holiday,
which traditionally marks the end of summer.
   For counting purposes, the weekend began at 6 p.m. local time
Friday and ended at 11:59 p.m. Monday.
   Council spokeswoman Gail Mansfield said 422 traffic fatalities
were recorded in 1988. The highest toll for the holiday weekend was
in 1968, when 688 people died.
