<HEAD>LaserPhoto XACC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss New Hampshire, Jennifer Ann
Landry, had to wake up at 3:45 a.m. and endure a bumpy flight to be
the first candidate to arrive Tuesday for the Miss America Pageant.
   ``I'm honored to be the first one,'' Ms. Landry, 22, said about
9:30 a.m. after descending the steps from a small commuter plane at
Bader Field.
   As her 10 pieces of luggage were packed into a car trunk, Ms.
Landry pulled out a small, white teddy bear which she said was a
good-luck charm given to her by the daughter of the New Hampshire
pageant director.
   The 5-foot-6 blonde, blue-eyed contestant also received what she
considered an unsolicited boost from the pilot of her plane.
   ``He mistook me for Miss America,'' Ms. Landry said. But she
added that her real talisman will be the 100 friends and relatives
she expects to come to watch her compete.
   All 51 contestants arriving Tuesday will rehearse and make a
series of public appearances. Beginning Sept. 12, they compete in
preliminary competition leading to the 69-year-old pageant's
nationally televised finals Sept. 16.
   ``Greeters'' from the pageant limited reporters' questions
because ``sometimes the girls will run off at the mouth a little,''
said Millie Frambes, one of the four greeters for Ms. Landry.
   However, Ms. Landry seemed eager to answer questions, saying her
plane ride was a ``little bumpy,'' and telling reporters of her
pre-dawn rise.
   Ms. Landry is a University of New Hampshire student majoring in
child care-special education.
   In a new twist this year, each contestant has submitted an essay
on an issue of her choice, Horn said. If she wins the crown, she
will be able to promote that issue during her reign, he said.
   The new Miss America will succeed Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson of
Minnesota.
