<HEAD>Pentagon To Release Iowa Report Thursday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with plans to release report; picks up at pvs
2nd graf, In an</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy on Thursday will release the findings
of its months-long investigation into the explosion aboard the USS
Iowa that claimed the lives of 47 crewmen, it was announced today.
   Navy investigators have searched to find the cause of the April
19 tragedy, when powder exploded in the battleship's No. 2 gun
turret during open-seas gunnery practice near Puerto Rico.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said the report is 1,100 pages
in length, and will be discussed at a briefing by the vice chief of
naval operations, Adm. Leon Edney and the investigating officer,
Rear Adm. Richard Milligan.
   Williams said the two intended to offer a ``very thorough''
briefing on the accident. He declined to discuss the details of the
report in advance.
   Meanwhile, a sailor from the battleship says Navy investigators
browbeat him into implicating shipmate Clayton Hartwig in the
explosion.
   In an interview with ABC News broadcast on Monday, Seaman David
Smith said he believed that Hartwig, a gunner's mate, was innocent
of causing the explosion that destroyed one of the battleship's gun
turrets.
   According to reports earlier this summer, Smith told naval
investigators that Hartwig had made sexual advances to him the night
before the explosion and that on other occasions Hartwig had talked
about how to set off explosions and showed him a timer device.
   ``Part of me can see him doing it,'' Smith was quoted as saying.
   Hartwig died in the explosion with the other sailors.
   In his ABC News interview, Smith said the investigators
questioned him in sessions lasting up to 12 hours and threatened to
charge him with 47 counts of murder and accessory to murder if he
did not cooperate.
   Smith said investigators put words into his mouth and distorted
his testimony, ABC said. Smith said he did not receive a homosexual
proposition from Hartwig and never heard of any timing device owned
by Hartwig, ABC said.
   Navy spokesman Kendall Pease said he was unaware of the ABC
report and had no comment.
   In Cleveland, Hartwig's sister, Kathy Kubicina, said her campaign
to clear her brother of suspicion in the case has been given a boost
by the news report.
   ``This only adds credence to what I've been saying,'' she said.
   She said of Smith, ``It doesn't surprise me a bit that he is now
recanting his story. I knew somebody would get to this kid and make
him tell the truth.''
   Ms. Kubicina said her own efforts to meet with Smith have been
unsuccessful.
   She said she went to Norfolk to try to meet with him face to
face. ``He refused to see me,'' she said, ``but I've talked to a
couple of the guys who survived and they assured me this kid never
had any contact with my brother.
   ``The guys aboard the ship didn't know the reason why he would
say these things,'' she added.
   Ms. Kubicina also said she was dismayed by questions she was
asked by two Navy investigators who were in Cleveland to meet with
her.
   ``The gay angle was it for them,'' she said. ``They didn't want
to talk about anything else.''
</TEXT>
