<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Uranium     09-05 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Uranium,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Japanese Accused of Trying to Sell Uranium to U.S. Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Japanese were arrested for trying to sell
nearly nine pounds of refined uranium to the U.S. Embassy for $83
million, police said Tuesday.
   In concentrated form, the radioactive chemical element can be
used for nuclear power generation and nuclear bombs. However,
nuclear experts said the substance offered by the suspects was
nearly in its natural state and would require more processing for
almost any use.
   City police said the four men and a woman were arrested Friday
after offering to sell the uranium to the Embassy in Tokyo at about
2,000 times its market value.
   Police said they were tipped off about the case by the U.S.
Embassy and secretly took pictures of the suspects in cooperation
with the Embassy before making the arrests.
   Police said they seized photographs from the suspects showing
about 40 metal capsules that appeared to contain uranium. They said
the suspects offered to sell a total of 8.8 pounds of the substance.
   Authorities said Tuesday the five were arrested for illegal
possession of nuclear substances but had not been formally charged.
   Police said the suspects brought a capsule with 3.5 ounces of
uranium to the Embassy in early August and offered the rest for sale
later.
   Police said they sent the substance in the capsule to the Science
and Technology Agency, which found it was refined natural uranium of
70.7 percent purity.
   The analysis showed only 0.71 percent was uranium-235, the kind
used for power generation and bombs. Experts say nuclear power
generation requires more than 3 percent uranium-235, and an atomic
bomb needs more than 90 percent of that same type.
   Nuclear experts, including Prof. Kyoji Naito of Nagoya
Univerisity, said the uranium was almost in its natural state and
thus had little use without further processing.
   They said it could be harmful if the human body were exposed to
it for an extended time.
   The American Embassy said laboratory analysis showed the
substance had posed no danger to Embassy personnel or the public.
   Naito and the police said the price the suspects demanded shows
they did not know the uranium's value. The same type is being sold
at about $275 per ounce, making the price the group demanded more
than 2,000 times greater than its market value.
   Takaharu Ushikoshi, head of the police department's public
security, said police do not believe the groups had terrorist or
political motives. ``It looks like the group's intent was purely
money,'' he said.
   Ushikoshi said one suspect said the group bought the uranium from
an unidentified person for $35 million.
   He suggested the suspects tried to sell the material to the
Embassy because ``they probably thought ordinary people or companies
wouldn't buy such an outrageous thing.''
   Police identified the alleged ringleader as a 43-year-old woman,
Toshiko Nishijima, who owns several small companies.
   The others were identified as Koichi Tsuru, 33, owner of a
securities firm in Hong Kong; Toshitada Mizuno, 44, a real estate
firm owner; Kasutoshi Okazaki, 44, a master of the traditional
Japanese tea ceremony; and Tomoyuki Nishida, 39, owner of a trading
company.
</TEXT>
