<FIRST>r a AM-Branstad-Drugs     09-05 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Branstad-Drugs,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov Calls for New Prosecutors, Agents in Drug Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Drugs Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Terry Branstad on Tuesday announced
a program to hire more drug-fighting prosecutors and narcotics
agents.
   Many details of the package will depend on how much President
Bush proposes for aid programs to states in a $7.8 billion federal
program he was to announce Tuesday night.
   The cost of the governor's proposals was put at $10 million, plus
a 30 percent increase in prevention and treatment programs, which
now cost $13.5 million.
   Branstad said the focus of the effort would be on hard drugs such
as cocaine and heroin, but treatment and education also are
important components.
   ``We're not going to win this drug war simply with additional
cops,'' Branstad said.
   ``We are beginning to see a reduction in casual use of drugs,''
Branstad said. But he said reports of violent, drug-related crime
are increasing.
   The Iowa National Guard, however, plans to continue its aerial
searches which so far have located 80 marijuana patches, leading to
the seizure of drugs with a street value of $4 million, spokesman
Warren Lawson said.
   The governor's proposal includes:
   _Hiring of eight new prosecutors to work for the attorney general
and help local prosecutors in drug cases.
   _Hiring 10 new drug enforcement agents.
   _Providing a ``hard suspension'' of driving privileges for those
caught driving while using alcohol or drugs. Aides said that meant
the elimination of probation and other options that allow continued
driving.
   _Beefing up treatment programs targeted at women, the unemployed
and youngsters.
   _Providing funding to allow state troopers to train local police
in drug education programs.
</TEXT>
