<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Earthquake     09-05 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Earthquake,0147</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake in Northern Aegean; No Damages or Casualties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake struck the northern
Aegean on Tuesday but caused no damages or injuries, the Athens
Geodynamic Institute said.
   A spokesman for the institute said the quake registered 5.4 on
the Richter scale and hit at 9:52 a.m., 161 miles northeast of
Athens. Its epicenter was in the Aegean Sea, northwest of the island
of Limnos, he said.
   A number of quakes have hit Greece in the past month. A quake
measuring 4.8 on the Richter scale rolled through the western part
of the country Friday, damaging 22 buildings but causing no injuries.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
   A magnitude 5 quake can cause considerable damage in a populated
area.
</TEXT>
