<FIRST>u a PM-DoubleKilling     09-05 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Double Killing,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Children Killed in Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two young brothers who went out to pick
up golf balls for pocket change were stabbed to death in a park,
police said today.
   Acting Police Chief Bob King said William James Neer, 10, and
Cole Laverne Neer, 11, were stabbed repeatedly in the chest a
half-mile from home. He said there was no evidence they were
tortured or otherwise molested.
   Police said they had no motive and no suspects in the slayings.
   Investigators searched the scene ``on their hands and knees''
this morning for clues, King said.
   The boys left home about 4 p.m. Monday, telling their father they
were going to a driving range to pick up golf balls, police said.
King said the boys earned money by turning in balls that were hit
over the fence.
   The boys' father reported them missing about 10 p.m. King said
it's not known whether the youngsters reached the area where they
collected balls.
   A passerby found the younger boy dead in a ditch in a wooded
section of Vancouver's David Douglas Park shortly before 7 p.m.
Monday. The other body was found off a trail 110 yards away just
after 2 a.m., police said.
   King said the younger boy apparently was dead when he was found,
but his body was warm enough that officers decided to call for
emergency medical treatment.
</TEXT>
