<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--HidingPlace     09-05 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hiding Place,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Stuck Briefly in Washing Machine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old boy's game of hide-and-seek
turned into hide-and-stuck when he climbed into a washing machine
that kicked on when he closed the lid.
   It took two men 15 minutes to extract the 35-pound Donovan Redden
from the machine in the laundry room at an apartment complex where
he and his sister and three cousins were playing Monday.
   ``It scared me,'' Donovan said later at Florida Hospital, where
he was examined and released after complaining his head hurt. ``I
was stuck.''
   He said he dove head-first into the machine to hide from his
playmates. The machine apparently had not completed its last cycle
and started up when Donovan pulled the door down. It did not fill
with water.
   He was ``wrapped like a sheet around the pole,'' said one of the
men who heard Donovan and the other children yelling and then helped
pull him out.
   ``He was crying and hollering and sweating,'' said his mother,
Dorothy Orr. Besides the headache and a little soreness, Donovan was
not seriously hurt.
