<FIRST>r a AM-NewtonKilled     09-05 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newton Killed,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plea Delayed A Week In Newton Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who faces murder charges in the
slaying of Black Panther co-founder Huey P. Newton was granted a
six-day delay for entering a plea Tuesday so his lawyer can review
the case.
   Police say Tyrone Robinson, 25, confessed to the pre-dawn
shooting and hoped the killing would advance his standing in a
prison-based street gang. He appeared briefly in court with his
hands shackled at his waist.
   Municipal Court Judge Horace Wheatley granted the extension until
Monday to allow attorney Alfons Wagner time to prepare his case.
   Wagner, appointed by the court, has interviewed Robinson but said
after the hearing that he does not really know enough about the case
to comment. He described Robinson as ``calm, responsive to my
questions. He knows he's in trouble.''
   Deputy Alameda County District Attorney Terese Drabec said
witnesses ``sharply contrast'' Robinson's version of the incident.
   Police say Robinson has admitted shooting Newton three times in
the head early on Aug. 22. Robinson, described by police as a
low-level crack dealer and member of the prison gang known as the
Black Guerrilla Family, claimed he shot Newton in self-defense after
Newton pulled a gun and demanded drugs. Newton was 47.
   Robinson told officers Newton robbed him of 14 crack rocks and
$160 earlier this year and also had ripped off other BGF members.
   Homicide investigator Sgt. Robert Chenault has said there is no
evidence to support Robinson's claim of self-defense. Drabec said
Robinson may not actually be a member of the BGF; she said she heard
he was trying to join.
   Newton formed the Black Panthers in the 1960s with Bobby Seale
and served as its defense minister. Newton's position with the
Panthers led him into frequent confrontations with police.
