<HEAD>Medical Teams Practice for Terror Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army and civil defense medical teams rushed to
treat 150 people posing as victims of a car bomb attack Tuesday in
an exercise aimed at testing readiness to handle a terrorist attack.
   ``We've got 30 wounded in this area and others around here!''
shouted an army physician identified only as Dr. Haim, as ambulance
sirens wailed in the background. ``We're evacuating them to the
hospitals.''
   Israel radio broadcast from the scene, and the radio accounts
were so vivid that worried listeners phoned in, the radio said,
despite repeated broadcast warnings the reporters were describing an
exercise.
   According to the scenario, the car bomb exploded outside a Jewish
convention. The actual site was a supermarket parking lot.
   About 150 army recruits pretended to be victims, and another 50
people posed as doctors, who arrived at the scene in ambulances.
