<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Regains Power in Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELIZE CITY, Belize (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The centrists of George Price, who led
Belize to self-government 25 years ago, defeated Prime Minister
Manuel Esquivel's conservative party, according to election results
announced Tuesday.
   Official results of Sunday's vote gave Price's Peoples United
Party 15 seats in the lower house of the bicameral legislature to 13
for the United Democratic Party led by Esquivel.
   Both men won reelection. Price is expected to lead the new
government, to be announced Wednesday.
   Price led the Central American nation of 160,000 people from
self-rule in 1964 through independence from Britain in 1981, until
Esquivel defeated him in the 1984 election.
   Esquivel campaigned on his record of economic recovery. Price
accused him of allowing foreigners too much influence in programs
for increasing investment and tourism.
