<FIRST>r a AM-People     09-05 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once wasn't enough for former Swedish tennis
star Bjorn Borg and Italian pop singer Loredana Berte, who had two
weddings within 24 hours.
   First it was city hall. Then the two got to church on time for a
pastor, brought in from Switzerland to perform a Lutheran ceremony
Tuesday in a tiny downtown church.
   About 20 guests attended, church officials said, including Borg's
parents, his son Robin, and Adriano Panatta, the captain of the
Italian Davis Cup team.
   Borg, 32, a five-time Wimbledon champion, and the dark-haired
38-year-old singer arrived in separate automobiles. A party in a
downtown hotel completed the two-day wedding ceremonies.
   Borg was married previously to Romanian-born tennis player
Mariana Simionescu. The mother of his son is Janike Bjorling.
   Berte was previously married to Italian industrialist Roberto
Berger.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gregory Harrison went through more than
$700,000 worth of cocaine before he realized he was ``sitting in the
back seat of my addiction and the devil was driving.''
   Harrison, who played Dr. Gonzo Gates on the early 1980s
television show ``Trapper John, M.D.,'' has a new role as celebrity
spokesman for the Entertainment Industry Referral &amp; Assistance
Center. The 5-year-old center has helped about 3,000 industry
workers seeking treatment for substance abuse.
   ``For four or five years it didn't harm me,'' Harrison said of
his early occasional drug use. ``But it's very insidious. It lets
you get away with it just enough time to be convinced you will
always get away with it.
   ``I felt more intelligent, more handsome, more creative, witty
and charming,'' Harrison, 39, said during a recent interview at his
home. ``My acting didn't suffer for a long time. It's that
convincing an illusion.''
   In August 1987, Harrison got into the car and drove from Los
Angeles to the Betty Ford Center in Rancho Mirage for treatment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floyd Jackson has spent almost 50 years
shining the shoes of the stars. Now his ``Floyd's Place'' stand is a
regular stop on the NBC studios tour in Burbank.
   ``Floyd Jackson is the only person who knows what it's like to be
in my shoes,'' Brandon Tartikoff, president of NBC, once joked.
   Since opening his business at NBC studios in 1951, Jackson has
worked on a lot of big shoes. ``I used to shine Bob Hope, Flip
Wilson and Dinah Shore,'' he said.
   Now 80, Jackson started shining shoes in the early 1930s at the
swank Rice Hotel in Houston. He moved to Hollywood in 1947.
   His regular clientele includes most of the guests who appear on
``The Tonight Show,'' as well as show host Johnny Carson.
   ``It's become a good luck gesture for guests to have their shoes
shined by Floyd before appearing on the show,'' said NBC spokeswoman
Pat Schultz.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marilyn Quayle plans to attend a luncheon here next
month sponsored by the Susan G. Komen Foundation for breast cancer
research.
   Mrs. Quayle's mother suffered from breast cancer, said Komen
foundation founder Nancy Brinker.
   ``And I think her visit underscores how the problem of breast
cancer is viewed at the highest level,'' Mrs. Brinker said.
   First lady Barbara Bush is doing a video for the foundation that
will be played at the Oct. 11 event.
   The foundation last year presented its national Betty Ford Award
to Nancy Reagan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Waikiki entertainer Charo is being investigated
by the Immigration and Naturalization Service for allegedly
importing illegal aliens to work at her restaurant.
   Charo, the Spanish singer best known for her ``cuchi-cuchi''
routine, called the allegations ``ridiculous.''
   ``I think the immigration department is using my name just for
publicity,'' she said.
   INS agents executed a search warrant last Thursday to look for
evidence at ``Charo's Restaurant'' on the island of Kauai.
   Arrangements for two Mexican aliens to come to Hawaii were made
in December in Charo's Beverly Hills, Calif., home, according to an
affidavit by Immigration Agent Dennis Smith.
   The two workers lived in a house adjacent to the restaurant, in a
remote area of the island, the affidavit said. It said another
illegal alien, a woman, worked at both the restaurant and in Charo's
home, about a mile from the restaurant.
   ``To the best of our knowledge, we were not hiring any illegal
aliens,'' said Bruce Lesher, her brother-in-law, who manages the
restaurant. ``Further than that, I have no comment.''
</TEXT>
