<DOCNO> AP890905-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1536EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Asbestos     09-05 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asbestos,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subway Train Strays Into Contaminated Tunnel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subway train was mistakenly routed Tuesday
through an off-limits zone contaminated with asbestos, but
authorities said the 1,000 passengers were not endangered by the
hazardous substance.
   Up above on midtown Manhattan's Eighth Avenue, meanwhile, some
automobile traffic resumed Tuesday morning while workmen continued
repairing the broken water main that caused the weekend asbestos
emergency.
   Water from the break, which occurred early Sunday, had flushed
through the subway tunnels and carried with it asbestos insulation
from nearby Consolidated Edison steam pipes.
   The northbound avenue had been closed from 44th to 52nd streets
while contractors and city employees purged it of asbestos.
   The subway misadventure occurred at 7 a.m. Tuesday, the start of
the morning rush hour, when a Transit Authority tower operator
failed to switch a southbound train from its normal route under
Eighth Avenue over to the tracks of the Sixth Avenue line after it
passed 59th Street.
   The motorman found himself on tracks without power but, because
the tunnel south of 59th Street is downhill, was able to coast to
42nd Street, said TA spokesman Bob Slovak.
   The riders were evacuated at the closed 42nd Street station. That
station had not yet been cleaned up, Slovak said, but it was safe
because ``the asbestos is still on the track, still wet, so there
are no airborne particles yet.''
   Inhaled particles of asbestos may cause cancer.
   It took two days of intensive cleaning to clear asbestos from a
half-mile of the surface of Eighth Avenue. It could take that much
time or longer just to get bids and plans from contractors to clean
the train tunnel and stations, said Deputy Mayor Robert Esnard.
   Con Edison, which had to turn off steam service because of the
flooding, said eight of 20 steam customers in the area got their
power back at 3 a.m. Tuesday. One of the restored customers was St.
Clare's Hospital, which had lost its hot water.
   It is not yet possible to estimate the cleanup cost, city and Con
Ed spokesmen have said.
   A Con Edison steam line on East 20th Street in southern Manhattan
ruptured Aug. 19, killing three people and contaminating Gramercy
Park apartment buildings with a mud-and-asbestos bath.
   With no probable completion date in sight, the cleanup bill for
Gramercy Park already has risen into the millions of dollars for Con
Edison, spokesman Martin Gitten said. The utility faces claims for
damage and temporary housing from some 500 area residents who had to
leave their homes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
