<DOCNO> AP890905-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1540EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Norway-Crash     09-05 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Crash,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aircraft Mechanic Steals Jet, Crashes Into Farm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aircraft mechanic Tuesday stole an F-16
jet fighter he was untrained to fly and crashed it into a vacant
farm minutes after taking off from an air base, the military said.
He was missing and believed dead.
   The aircraft exploded in the crash, engulfing a farm building in
a fireball, said Lt. Col. Svein Fredriksen of Norway's Oerland Air
Force Base, from where the plane was taken. There was no reports of
injuries to anyone on the ground.
   Rescue helicopters found no sign the Belgian mechanic ejected,
but search crews found no trace of him at the crash site, Fredriksen
said. The identity of the mechanic was being withheld until his
remains were found and his family notified, the officer said.
   It was not clear if the mechanic accidentally or intentionally
crashed.
   Fredriksen said the jet motor specialist plunged to the ground in
the single-seat Belgian plane nine miles from the coastal Oerland
base, west of the city of Trondheim.
   ``The impact point is nothing but a hole in the ground. We are
looking for physical evidence that he was actually in the plane ....
There is nothing left,'' said air force Major Amund Sveen.
   The mechanic was taking a training course for NATO F-16 crews
from Norway, Denmark, Belgium and the Netherlands, Fredriksen said.
   ``The technician did not have permission or training to fly the
F-16. You could say he stole it. We don't know if he had any other
kind of flight training,'' said Fredriksen.
   ``We have no idea what he was up to. An aircraft mechanic is not
trained as a pilot and can't control one of these fighters. They
know how to start the motors to check them and can maybe even taxi,
but they don't have a chance after takeoff,'' said Fredriksen.
   Sveen said the mechanic had taxied the jet onto the runway, taken
off, and managed to reach about 2,000 feet of elevation before
crashing.
   He said fighter pilot training lasts more than two years and that
it ``is madness'' for untrained personnel to try flying an F-16.
   The technician had no contact with the control tower and was
wearing improper equipment, a defense spokesman told the Norwegian
news agency NTB.
   A team of 10 Belgian military investigators were on their way to
the accident site. They were to investigate with Norwegian
officials, Sveen said.
</TEXT>
