<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     09-05 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses Mistrial As Jury Deliberates For 13th Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge rejected a mistrial motion by Richard
Ramirez's lawyers Tuesday while the jury in his ``Night Stalker''
murder trial began its 13th day of deliberations on 43 charges.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan also denied a motion to
disqualify jurors for allegedly disobeying court instructions.
   Attorneys for Ramirez claimed the panelists were obviously
watching TV or reading news accounts when one juror was murdered
last month. Several arrived at the courthouse in tears. The defense
said this showed they had disobeyed an order to avoid exposure to
publicity.
   Attorneys also claimed that the murder prejudiced jurors and made
their deliberations unfair to the defendant.
   Tynan ruled on the written motions without hearing arguments.
   Ramirez, 29, a drifter from El Paso, Texas, who is accused of
being the devil-worshiping ``Night Stalker,'' made a brief court
appearance to acknowledge he did not want to attend the court
session. He answered ``yes,'' when asked whether he understood his
right to be there, then signed a waiver of his presence.
   Tynan said the jury, which began its deliberations anew after the
panel member died, has asked to review videotape evidence in the
case on Wednesday. He said he would send a video player into their
jury room.
   The tapes in evidence show a police lineup in which victims
identified Ramirez as the attacker who murdered, raped and robbed
victims in a string of nighttime attacks during the summer of 1985.
   Defense attorneys have claimed that witnesses were coached to
pick Ramirez out. They contend he is a victim of mistaken
identifications.
   The prosecution has said the evidence linking Ramirez to the
terrifying attacks is overwhelming.
   The jury had already deliberated 13 days when it was required to
restart its talks on Aug. 11 because one juror had been sleeping and
was dismissed.
   They had barely begun when word came on Aug. 14 that juror
Phyllis Singletary was found beaten and shot to death. Her boyfriend
later took his own life. He left a note saying he killed her in a
domestic argument.
   After a recess for jurors to recover from the shock, an alternate
was sent in and the panel began talking again Aug. 16.
</TEXT>
