<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1720EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mauritania-Senegal     09-05 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mauritania-Senegal,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>West African Dispute Stirs Talk of War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ethnic and racial dispute with
neighboring Senegal that left hundreds dead last spring is flaring
up again with threats of open warfare between the two nations.
   Officials in both West African capitals have invited Egypt's
President Hosni Mubarak, president of the Organization of African
Unity, to mediate the conflict. He will visit both countries
beginning Wednesday with a stop in Nouakchott, Mauritania's capital.
   Mubarak has his hands full. When Senegal and Mauritania broke
diplomatic relations Aug. 22, Foreign Minister Ibrahim Fall of
Senegal said the situation ``constitutes a threat to peace in the
entire region.''
   Fall said Senegal was ready ``to use all means to defend its
territorial integrity, its sovereignty and its independence.'' But
Senegal has denied Mauritanian charges that it was massing troops at
the border for a military offensive.
   Information Minister Mohamed Lemine Ould Ahmed of Mauritania said
in a recent interview that the dispute stems from ``a Senegalese
plot to dominate Mauritania.'' However, he did not provide proof.
   Farmers from Senegal and nomadic herdsmen from Mauritania have
clashed for centuries.
   The latest trouble began in April, when a herd of goats strayed
across the ill-defined border. Farmers and herdsmen fought over the
goats, and two Senegalese were killed.
   Tempers exploded in both countries. In the snowballing conflict,
hundreds of people were murdered in riots in Nouakchott, Senegal's
capital of Dakar, and other cities.
   In addition, thousands of Mauritanian and Senegalese expatriates
were forced to flee. About 200,000 refugees are now living in camps
on both sides of the border.
   Blaise Cherif, of the office of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees, said it was the first time his office has had to cope with
such a massive influx of refugees anywhere in West Africa.
   The conflict has pitted mainly Arabic-speaking Mauritanian Moors
against largely French-speaking Senegalese blacks. About a third of
Mauritania's 1.7 million people are black, but not all the blacks
attacked by mobs in this country have been of Senegalese origin.
   President Abdou Diouf of Senegal has said the cause of the
trouble is the determination of Mauritania's Moorish majority to
``Arabize'' their country. Most blacks in Mauritania do not speak
Arabic, and many blacks accuse the government of racism.
   The dispute is complicated by the changing course of the Senegal
River, has divided the two lands since France ruled them both.
   Mauritania says the border lies in the middle of the river.
   However, when the river floods, its shore moves north by 20 to 30
miles over a 580-mile stretch. About 18,000 square miles of fertile
land thus remain in dispute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
