<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--CrocodilesHatch     09-05 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Crocodiles Hatch,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Endangered Philippine Crocodiles Hatched at Zoo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five endangered Philippine crocodiles
that hatched Tuesday at the Gladys Porter Zoo are believed to be the
first to hatch away from the Philippines, a scientist said.
   Two more were trying to break out of their shells Tuesday
afternoon, said Pat Burchfield, a herpetologist and deputy director
of the zoo.
   There are only 400 to 500 Philippine crocodiles in the wild. The
species, known scientifically as Crocodylus mindorensis, has
declined because of human encroachment on their habitat, Burchfield
said.
   The olive green, 8}-inch-long babies hatched from 13 eggs laid at
the zoo 73 days before, he said.
   The zoo had only two males until last year, Burchfield said, when
it acquired two females with the help of Charles Ross of the
Smithsonian Institution and A.C. Alcala of Silliman University in
the Philippines.
   Some of the baby crocodiles probably will be sent back to a
breeding program at Silliman University, Burchfield said.
</TEXT>
