<FIRST>r w AM-Poindexter-Webb     09-05 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poindexter-Webb,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Lawyer to Prosecute Poindexter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former U.S. attorney from Chicago will
prosecute former national security adviser John Poindexter in the
Iran-Contra case, independent counsel Lawrence Walsh announced
Tuesday.
   No trial date has been set.
   Dan K. Webb, Walsh's choice to be chief trial counsel against
Poindexter, oversaw the federal corruption investigation of the Cook
County, Ill., judicial system known as Operation Greylord.
   As a U.S. attorney from 1981 to 1985, Webb also won convictions
in the Tylenol extortion case and the case in which 10 Chicago
police officers were convicted of taking payoffs from heroin dealers.
   Webb, 43, is a partner in the Chicago law firm of Winston &amp;
Strawn specializing in commercial litigation and white-collar
criminal defense.
   On another matter Tuesday, Walsh's office disclosed that it had
spent $15.9 million through the end of July to investigate and
prosecute the Iran-Contra affair.
   There have been three guilty pleas as well as the conviction of
Oliver North in the case since Walsh was appointed in December 1986.
   Poindexter is charged with conspiracy and two counts of
obstructing Congress and two counts of making false statements. He
is accused of telling Congress that no one in the U.S. government
knew until 1986 that a 1985 shipment to Iran contained Hawk
missiles. He also is accused of conspiring to cover up North's
assistance to the Contras during a a congressional ban on military
aid to the Nicaraguan rebel force.
   North, a former National Security Council aide, was convicted in
May of aiding and abetting an obstruction of Congress, destroying
NSC documents and accepting an illegal gratuity from Richard Secord.
North, who was sentenced to 1,200 hours of community service, is
appealing his convictions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
