<DOCNO> AP890905-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1757EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     09-05 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mazowiecki Finishing Cabinet Picks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leaders said the foreign and
transport ministeries, both sought by the Communists, remained under
discussion but that Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki's Cabinet list
should be complete Wednesday.
   As the makeup is described by various sources, Solidarity would
hold the most portfolios, followed by the Communists and the United
Peasant Party and Democratic Party.
   Bronislaw Geremek, Solidarity leader in Parliament, said the
Solidarity caucus would meet with Mazowiecki on Thursday and the
final list of Cabinet nominees would be presented to Mikolaj
Kozakiewicz, speaker of the parliament, or Sejm.
   In an interview with the state news agency PAP, Kozakiewicz said
the Sejm was scheduled to meet Sept. 12 to vote on the Cabinet.
   Kozakiewicz said hearings by parliamentary commissions on the
nominees would start Friday and last three days. ``I hope that no
complications will surface,'' he said.
   Sixteen government ministries are to be filled, but the number
could change if Mazowiecki decides to combine or split up
departments.
   Mazowiecki, a Solidarity newspaper editor elected prime minister
Aug. 24, met with leaders of the Peasant Party Democratic Party on
Tuesday.
   Jerzy Jozwiak, leader of the Democratic Party, told PAP after the
meeting that his party would receive four posts: a deputy prime
minister, domestic trade, the office for scientific-technological
progress and a ministry yet to be decided.
   Asked if his party was satisfied, Jozwiak replied: ``The number,
yes; the arrangement, not much.'' He did not elaborate.
   Peasant Party leader Roman Malinowski and the party's
parliamentary leader, Aleksander Bentkowski, met with Mazowiecki.
Bentkowski said later the party would receive five posts to be held
by four people: a deputy prime minister and the ministries of
agriculture, environment, health and justice. The deputy prime
minister also would be the agriculture minister, he said.
   Bentkowski said he was satisfied ``because we received what the
prime minister promised to us earlier.''
   Geremek said not only ministries are being balanced by
negotiations, but in some cases subordinate positions in ministries.
   For instance, Geremek said, if the Communists get the foreign
minister, the undersecretary of the ministry would be someone from
Solidarity.
   The Communists have pressed for Foreign Minister Tadeusz
Olechowski, the incumbent, to be retained.
   Geremek said the ministry overseeing state broadcasting probably
would be controlled by Solidarity.
   ``Radio and television should not be a party man, and he probably
will have a staff composed of representatives of different political
orientations,'' Geremek said. ``We want the television to be
pluralistic.''
   The pro-Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza quoted Communist
Central Committee secretary Slawomir Wiatr on Tuesday as saying the
party expects five ministries.
   In addition to the defense and interior ministries, originally
promised the Communists, Wiatr said the party expected foreign
affairs, culture and transportation. The Communists have threatened
to oppose Mazowiecki if they are not satisfied with the makeup of
his government.
   Solidarity activists believe an aggressive stance by the party
would hurt Mazowiecki's government as it seeks to carry out painful
economic reforms.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said Monday: ``Poland belongs to
everybody. ... If Poland is to be reformed, then (Communists) have
to enter the government as reformers, and not as party members. They
should think about Poland and reform, and not about the number of
seats that fall to them.''
</TEXT>
