<FIRST>u i AM-SovietUnrest 1stLd-Writethru a0594 09-05 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijan Party Leader Opposes Kremlin on Disputed Territory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with declaration by Azerbaijan party
leader, strike updates, other dvpts. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party chief of Azerbaijan has called
for an end to direct rule from Moscow in the republic's troubled
Nagorno-Karabakh region, which neighboring Armenia also claims, an
activist said Tuesday.
   Sources in Azerbaijan and Moldavia said strikes spawned by
disputes between rival ethnic groups in the two southern republics
spread to more factories and businesses.
   Aiden Amirbekov, the Azerbaijani activist, quoted party leader
Abdul-Rakhman Vezirov as saying in the television interview at
midnight Monday: ``We must liquidate the special form of
administration.''
   Taking that position would align the Communist leader of the
Caucasus republic against the Kremlin on the issue and with the
People's Front political movement, which organized the general
strike that began Monday.
   Vezirov and other Azerbaijani leaders refuse to recognize the
People's Front, which called the strike to demand that the
republic's national legislators be recalled and that it reassert
control over Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Amirbekov quoted Vezirov as saying nothing had been accomplished
by the direct rule of Kremlin representative Arkady Volsky, imposed
Jan. 12 in an effort to stop violence between ethnic Azerbaijanis
and Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Krasnaya Zvezda, the Defense Ministry newspaper, said Sunday the
disputed territory was on the verge of civil war and tensions
between Azerbaijanis and Armenians ``are like gunpowder.''
   In a 20-minute television interview, Vezirov also criticized the
strike as damaging to Azerbaijan and its relationship with other
republics, Amirbekov said.
   Amirbekov said Vezirov's comments would be discussed at a
People's Front rally Wednesday evening.
   Javad Salamov, a strike committee member, claimed Tuesday that 95
percent of Baku's factories were closed, but a journalist at the
republic's official news agency said the number was far lower.
   Salamov claimed public transport was halted in Baku, the
provincial capital, and newspapers were not delivered.
   ``Strikers are demanding full political sovereignty for
Azerbaijan, which means they don't want to secede from the Soviet
Union but ought to have the right to make political decisions about
its territory,'' he said.
   An editor at the official news agency Azerinform, who would not
give his name, said 95 percent ``is a big overstatement.''
   Some factories were closed and others partially shut, he said,
while ``some shops are closed, but not ones selling food.'' He
described public transport as ``unreliable,'' but said the subway
was operating; oil refineries and power plants were functioning, and
the railroad was running.
   Tass, the official national news agency, said a strike by
transport workers in Baku was slowing travelers going to work and
shipment of finished oil products.
   About 100 people have been reported killed in a the dispute that
began 18 months ago over Nagorno-Karabakh, a mountain enclave whose
population is 75 percent ethnic Armenian but was assigned to
Azerbaijan in 1923.
   Hundreds of thousands fled their homes, and the Kremlin assumed
direct rule in January.
   ``Most Azerbaijanis have left Armenian-populated areas'' in
Nagorno-Karabakh, the Azerinform editor said in a telephone
interview. ``More and more Armenians are leaving their homes in the
rest of the republic, especially Baku.''
   In Moldavia, strike committee member Pyotr Denisenko said workers
had struck 16 more factories, bringing to 218 the number shut in
protest of a new law making Moldavian the official language. Soviet
television said a national commission formed on Saturday met with
strikers for the first time.
   Labor unrest in the republic, which borders Romania, began two
weeks ago while the language law was being debated.
   On Thursday, the legislature declared Moldavian the official
language, which appeased many nationalists but angered ethnic
Russians and other groups who make up more than one-third of the 4.2
million population.
   Denisenko said in a telephone intervew the strikers want both
Russian and Moldavian to be official languages.
   The Central Committee, the 251-member policy-making body of the
national Communist Party, is to meet in Moscow later this month on
relations among the Soviet Union's more than 100 ethnic groups. The
meeting has been delayed several times and no specific date has been
set.
</TEXT>
