<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-Crash     09-05 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Crash,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Only Survivor of Crash That Killed 150 Fights for Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only survivor of an airliner crash that
killed at least 150 people fought for his life in a hospital on
Tuesday with burns over 70 percent of his body, the Cuban news
agency Prensa Latina said.
   It quoted a doctor at Calixto Garcia Hospital in Havana as
reporting Luigi Capalbo, 22, of Parma, Italy, in extremely critical
condition with burns, head injuries and a broken left leg.
   Capalbo was a passenger on a Cubana de Aviacion plane that
crashed right after takeoff from Havana in a thunderstorm Sunday
night, destroying two square blocks of homes in a suburb a half-mile
from Jose Marti airport.
   Investigators searched the wreckage for clues to the cause of the
crash and Italian reports said Tuesday three of the four ``black
box'' flight recorders aboard the Soviet-made Ilyushin 62 were found.
   The airliner was carrying 113 Italians returning home from
vacation, said Prensa Latina in a dispatch monitored in Mexico City.
The flight was bound for Milan, Italy, with a stop in Cologne, West
Germany.
   By Tuesday, forensic experts had identified the bodies of 14
Italians and 26 Cubans, the agency said.
   The plane was carrying 115 passengers and 11 crew. All were
killed except Capalbo. An estimated 25 people on the ground in the
Boyeros suburb also were killed and dozens were injured.
   The Communist Party newspaper Granma quoted unidentified sources
Tuesday as saying up to 50 people on the ground may have died, the
Mexican news agency Notimex said.
   Capalbo played on an Italian baseball team and left for Cuba Aug.
21 with three teammates, all killed in the crash, Italian reports
said.
   A government commission headed by Rogelio Acevedo, president of
the Civil Aeronautics Institute, was investigating the crash, Prensa
Latina said.
   Italian government officials and a judge flew to Havana to help
in the investigation and coordinate return of the bodies, the
Italian state television network RAI said.
   It said families of the passengers flew to Rome to board a Cubana
flight to Havana.
   RAI said three of the plane's four black boxes, which record
flight data, were found.
   Prensa Latina said bodies, wrecked cars and downed trees lay
scattered where the plane crashed.
   ``It was something terrible. I've never seen anything like it, it
was a ball of fire,'' it quoted one of the injured as saying over
local TV. ``The explosion lit up the sky. We thought it was all
over.''
   One man of about 30, who lost five relatives when the plane
crashed in front of his house, walked through the blood-splattered
mud, still littered with tourism magazines, a camera, sunglasses and
a toy, Prensa Latina said.
   Jose Antonio Gonzalez, 44, a leading Cuban film critic and film
industry promoter who was one of two Cuban passengers aboard, was
buried Tuesday.
   He held several government cultural jobs, including director of
international relations of the Cuban Art and Film Industry Institute.
</TEXT>
