<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Glance     09-05 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Glance,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Drug War At-a-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the latest developments in Colombia's war with drug
traffickers:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. HELICOPTERS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The United States delivered five UH-1H ``Huey'' transport
helicopters, modified versions of the combat choppers that gained
prominence during the Vietnam war.
   They arrived in a huge C-5 transport plane at Bogota's El Dorado
airport, the last of the big-ticket items in President Bush's $65
million package to help the government fight its drug war.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>VIOLENCE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen killed Angela de Guerrero, wife of Army Col. Carlos
Guerrerro, as she sat in car outside a supermarket just north of
Bogota. Police said they have no motive for the shooting.
Authorities have blamed past random acts of violence on drug
traffickers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. DRUG PLAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The White House released President Bush's national antidrug
strategy, disclosing plans to crack down on illegal drug users and
declare a $7.9 billion war on drugs. The plan would authorize $1.6
billion for corrections; $449 million for interdiction on the
international level, including some $260 million for military aid to
the drug-production countries of Peru, Bolivia and Colombia; $350
million for state and local law enforcement; $250 million for
expanding the court system; $3.1 billion for other law enforcement;
$1.2 billion for prevention and education; and $925 million for
treatment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>COCAINE PRODUCTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A police source said the government's 2-week-old crackdown on
traffickers has virtually paralyzed the nation's cocaine-producing
laboratories. The Colombian newspaper El Tiempo predicted there
would be a shortage of the coveted drug in the United States and
prices for it would rise.
</TEXT>
