<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Phoenix-BushPlan     09-05 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phoenix-Bush Plan,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phoenix House Head Gives Bush Plan Thumbs Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Drugs Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's new $7.8 billion drug plan is a
courageous combination of law enforcement and treatment, the head of
the nation's largest private, non-profit drug treatment center said
Tuesday.
   The founder and president of Phoenix House, Dr. Mitchell S.
Rosenthal, who has seen a draft copy of President Bush's plan, said
the program could have an even higher success rate than the
president is projecting.
   ``I think the goals of a 50 percent reduction are probably too
modest,'' Rosenthal said before leaving for a White House meeting
with Bush and federal drug czar William Bennett.
   ``I think if the American public can get behind this plan, we can
see a 75 to 80 percent reduction in drug use over the next 10
years.''
   Rosenthal, who brought Bennett to a Phoenix House facility in the
borough of Queens three months ago, said the best aspect of the Bush
proposal was its acknowledgement of jail as the start of a road to
rehabilitation. Funds for the program will be divided 70 percent for
law enforcement, 30 percent for treatment, the doctor said.
   ``I'm very encouraged with the plan. It's a gutsy, comprehensive
plan which addresses a coming together of treatment and law
enforcement concerns,'' Rosenthal said at a news conference.
   ``It recognizes most users are not motivated for treatment, and
includes sanctions to push them toward treatment. ... Jails are an
opportunity to begin treatment.''
   Rosenthal said one key to Bush's plan is convincing Americans
that casual drug use is an evil that must be stopped. In 1962, 2
percent of Americans said they had used illicit drugs; in 1982, it
was 38 percent, he said.
   ``It's essential to target casual users. This plan is trying to
make casual use by mainstream Americans something to think long and
hard about,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
