<FIRST>r i AM-GraceJones     09-05 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grace Jones,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grace Jones Fails to Appear at Cocaine-Possession Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jamaican singer and actress Grace Jones
failed to show up Tuesday for her trial on cocaine possession
charges, and a court said it will order her arrest if she doesn't
appear at the rescheduled trial.
   Ms. Jones' attorney, Tom Tavares-Simson, told St. Andrew Criminal
Court Magistrate Owen Parkin that her ``absence was due to
contractual bligations in Italy which she was unable to break, and
should not be taken as any form of disrespect for the court.''
   Parkin issued an arrest warrant but immediately suspended it,
making it effective Oct. 3 if she fails to show up for a new trial
on that date.
   The trial had already been postponed three times since it was
originally scheduled in June, either because prosecutors were not
familiar with the case, witnesses were missing or judges failed to
show up.
   Ms. Jones, 37, returned to the Caribbean island for the last
three trial dates after flying from Paris, Italy and Spain. Each
time she complained of the high cost of flying back to Jamaica, only
to learn in court that the trial had been suspended.
   Ms. Jones was arrested in April while vacationing in Kingston and
charged with possession of .006 ounces of cocaine that police found
in her handbag. Police said the street value of the cocaine was less
than $18.
   She was freed on $2,500 bail.
</TEXT>
