<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2021EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Auschwitz-Wiesel     09-05 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz-Wiesel,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wiesel Asks Pope to Declare Himself in Auschwitz Convent Furor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elie Wiesel, an Auschwitz survivor and Nobel Peace
laureate, said Tuesday only Pope John Paul II can end the conflict
over whether to move a Roman Catholic convent away from the
Auschwitz death camp in Poland.
   The American writer asked the pope to take a clear position on
the issue.
   Both Wiesel, a Jew, and the pope were born in Poland.
   John Paul has made no public comment on the controversy over the
Carmelite convent, which was to be moved to an interfaith prayer
center under an agreement between Jewish and Catholic leaders signed
in Geneva in 1987.
   A deadline for the transfer passed last Feb. 22, leading to
protests at the site by Jewish activists. Polish church leaders then
said the agreement was suspended because of the protests and what
they called ``aggressive'' demands. Cardinal Josef Glemp, the
primate of Poland, was quoted last week as calling for the agreement
to be renegotiated.
   Vatican officials have said, on condition of anonymity, that the
pope believes the problem should be worked out by the Poles without
his intervention.
   ``The pope's silence will be judged by history,'' Wiesel said
during a visit to Paris. ``How could the pope who, in his crusades
around the world, speaks of the problems of the countries he passes
through, sometimes with courage, fail to take a position on an
affair concerning his own country?''
   Wiesel has campaigned tirelessly for human rights and has
stressed the need to remember the horrors of the Nazi Holocaust.
   Cardinal Albert Decourtray, the primate of France who headed the
Roman Catholic delegation at the 1987 negotiations, has called for
the agreement to be carried out, but said on Sunday he hoped it
could be done without involving the pope.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
