<DOCNO> AP890905-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2022EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     09-05 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Austerity Measures Will Help Obtain Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The government said Tuesday if
recently decreed austerity measures succeed they will help this
impoverished Caribbean nation receive up to $340 million in aid.
   Finance Minister Leonce Thelusma told a press conference that
once Haiti has ``cleaned up its house'' it will receive the funds
from the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank and the
International Monetary Fund.
   He said when ``we have put our public finances in order, we will
obtain an Enlarged Structural Adjustment Loan of about $50 million''
from the IMF.
   An additional $170 million would come from the World Bank and
$100 million from the Inter-American Development Bank, according to
Thelusma.
   That amounts to $320 million and the finance minister did not say
where the additional $20 million would come from, nor did he say
when Haiti expected to receive the aid.
   Haiti's annual budget is under $300 million.
   In a series of weekend decrees, the government of Lt. Gen.
Prosper Avril raised tariffs on imports, changed tax deductions for
home loans, increased the number of merchants required to pay the 10
percent value-added tax on their sales by including smaller
businesses and raised taxes on basic foodstuffs.
   The moves are designed to help the government balance its budget
and are ``a pill we have to take now, but in the long run the
results will be positive,'' Thelusma said.
   The Chamber of Commerce and many businessmen and politicians
criticized the austerity measures, saying they would hurt the poor
and provoke social unrest.
   Thelusma confirmed unofficial reports that Haiti is negotiating
with the IMF. He said the economic measures were not demanded by the
IMF and were initiated by the government.
   Haiti, which shares the island of Hispaniola with the Dominican
Republic, is one of the world's poorest nations. It has a foreign
debt of $800 million and the annual per capita income is less than
$300.
   Declining farm production has been aggravated by cheap products
smuggled into the country, mainly from Florida, and political
instability has dissuaded foreign and local businessmen from
investing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
