<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DrugCosts     09-05 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Costs,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Losers: Housing, Immigration, Etc.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Drugs Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday proposed cuts in
juvenile justice, housing, immigration and economic development
programs to help defray some of the costs of his new anti-drug
program.
   But the size of the cuts, less than $800 million, was relatively
small compared with the overall $7.9 billion price tag of the
program Bush outlined in his first nationally televised addres to
the nation.
   White House Budget Director Richard Darman said that most of the
funds for the president's new program already had been earmarked or
proposed previously by the president.
   Overall, the package represents a $2.2 billion spending increase
over the current anti-drug effort.
   But of that, just $716 million would represent a budgetary
increase over funds Bush already requested of Congress in his
February budget message and his May anti-crime package.
   Ending weeks of silence on how Bush would pay for the package,
Darman was ready with a series of reductions that he said would
cover the increases.
   ``This isn't a come-later approach,'' Darman told a briefing.
   However the $751 million list of program reductions _ a juvenile
justice program, funds for housing, immigration and rural economic
development, a postal program and a Pentagon communications project
_ drew immediate skepticism from Capitol Hill.
   ``To say we've declared war and developed a domestic policy and a
foreign policy and then we have to go back and nickel-and-dime from
the different committees to raise $700 million, to me it just
doesn't seem as though we're sincere,'' said Rep. Charles Rangle,
D-N.Y., chairman of the select House Committee on Narcotics Abuse
and Control.
   In addition, House Democrats suggested that Bush still has not
said how he would pay for all of his earlier anti-crime proposals.
   The White House announced the overall program in terms of budget
authority _ which includes some spending on projects in future years
and thus tends to exaggerate the price tag, some critics contend.
   In terms of budget outlays, money that will be actually shelled
out in the fiscal yera beginning Oct. 1, the program's first-year
price tag comes to $6.4 billion, rather than the $7.9 billion in
budget authority.
   One reason for the disparity in the two figures is that a
fair-sized chunk of the program involves spending on new prisons,
and most of those costs would not be paid until later years, budget
officials said.
   Darman gave his list of the $716 million in ``new spending''
proposals, along with his $751 million in offsetting costs, in a
letter to the chairmen and senior Republicans on the House and
Senate approprations committees.
   The proposed cuts:
   _$320 million from a Human and Health Services program to help
states bear the costs of immigration legalization services. The
White House cited a slow start-up for the program as rationale, and
said states will still have sufficient funds available.
   _$194 million from the Economic Development Administration of the
Commerce Department, a program that former President Reagan long
sought to kill.
   _$40 million from a grant program for the Justice Department's
juvenile justice program. Budget officials claimed claimed the
orignial purpose of the program _ separation of junveile from adult
offenders _ had already been accomplished.
   _$15 million from a fund set up to reclaim lost postal revenue
through curbing past abuses of federal subsidies to non-profit
mailers.
   _$50 million from public housing operating subsidies by the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, funds that essentially
would be redirected to a HUD program to rid public housing of drug
dealers and to increase security.
   _$132 million from the Defense Department's Single Channel Ground
and Airborne Radio System, which the White House said needs more
testing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
