<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2028EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     09-05 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader Among Latest Killed in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent politician and union leader
shot to death in his office Tuesday was among at least 25 people
reported killed in Sri Lanka's ethnic violence, officials reported.
   Military officials said an unidentified man walked into the
office of Merril Wijeyesena Kariyawasam in Ratmalana, a town 10
miles south of Colombo, and opened fire.
   Kariyawasam, 52, was a senior official of the National Workers
Union, affiliated with the governing United National Party. He
formerly represented the southern Agalawatte constituency in
Parliament and was chairman of the state-owned Rubber Research
Institute.
   A bodyguard was wounded in the attack, during which four
accomplices of the gunman stood watch outside, said the officials,
who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   They said the raiders were believed to be from the People's
Liberation Front, a group of Sinhalese extremists trying to
overthrow the government.
   Earlier Tuesday, President Ranasinghe Premadasa told the
governing party's Parliament delegation the crisis had ``shaken the
very foundations of democracy and human rights.'' He urged all
parties to work for an end to ethnic violence.
   The government says more than 5,000 people have been killed in
two years of violence by the Sinhalese radicals.
   Premadasa plans an all-party meeting Sept. 13 to seek solutions
to ethnic problems. He invited the People's Liberation Front, which
has rejected other peace offers, but it has not responded.
   ``What is essential is the bringing in of all groups that still
remain outside the democratic process within its fold,'' he told the
United National Party lawmakers.
   Officials have reported at least 20 deaths a day in the past
week, the bloodiest of the Sinhalese extremist campaign. At least
237 people were killed in the Aug. 28-Sept. 4 period, according to
military reports.
   A senior military official said Tuesday the radical Sinhalese had
built an army of about 7,500 men with sophisticated weapons,
supported by 2,000 people who can use ``a shotgun, or maybe a
single-shot rifle.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Earlier estimates by defense officials have said the extremists
had a fighting force of about 2,500.
   Sri Lanka's security force number 103,000 _ a 42,000-member
police force, 50,000 soldiers, 7,000 men in the navy and an air
force of 4,000.
   Sinhalese radicals protest autonomy concessions made in a July
1987 peace agreement to Tamils militants, who seek an independent
nation in the north and east. They also demand withdrawal of Indian
peacekeeping troops deployed in the Tamil area.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese majority.
   The 6-year-old Tamil war has killed 11,000 people, including
1,000 Indian soldiers.
   India became involved because it is the regional power and its
own population includes 60 million Tamils, most of whom live in
southern India, just across the Palk Strait from Sri Lanka.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
