<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-05 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain, Flooding, Heat and Predictions of Snow</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains drenched South Carolina on Tuesday, and snow was
predicted in Montana, while the heat index in Texas reached 108
degrees.
   More than 1\ inches of rain fell at Charleston, S.C., in one hour
and 2{ inches had fallen in a six-hour period Tuesday morning.
   Three days of heavy rain in northeast Florida had rivers
approaching flood levels. Showers and thunderstorms moved across
central Kansas leaving many creeks flooded and roads under water
from flash floods. Two and a half feet of water came into some homes
at Hackberry Hollow near Arkansas City. Minor flooding continued
along the Wabash River in central Indiana.
   Showers and thunderstorms were reported across much of Florida
and from the central Gulf Coast region to the coastal waters of
Texas, across western Missouri and northeast Oklahoma. Light rain
fell th Carolinas and Georgia.
   Rough sea conditions prevailed along portions of the East Coast.
A heavy surf advisory was in effect on the North Carolina coast.
   Sunshine prevailed Tuesday afternoon from the upper Great Lakes
across the Dakotas, Wyoming and the Great Basin area to California.
Skies were also sunny over the Tennessee Valley and in much of
Texas. Partly sunny skies were the rule in the northeast.
   Afternoon temperatures were in the 70s and 80s across most of the
nation. Readings were in the 60s over western portions of the
Carolinas and southwest Virginia and much of the north Atlantic
Coast.
   An excessive heat advisory was in effect Tuesday for parts of
central Texas. Waco had a temperature of 98 degrees and a heat index
of about 108 at 3 p.m. EDT.
   Southerly winds gusted to over 30 mph from the Great Basin area
across Wyoming to South Dakota. Aberdeen, S.D., reported a wind gust
to 37 mph.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Great Falls, Mont., to 110 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstorms
scattered along coastal sections of the south Atlantic and Gulf
states and from the northern Rockies across the Dakotas and the
upper half of the Mississippi Valley to much of Michigan. Snow was
expected in the higher elevations of western Montana with gusty
winds over portions of Montana and Wyoming.
   High temperatures were expected in the 80s and 90s across most of
the nation. Highs in the 70s were forecast over the North Atlantic
Coast, portions of the Great Lakes region, the Pacific Northwest,
along the California coast and over the northern intermountain
region. Highs in Montana and northwest Wyoming were expected to be
in the 50s and 60s. Temperatures near 100 degrees were expected in
central and southwest Texas and between 100 and 110 in the Southwest.
</TEXT>
