<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-Plane 2ndLd-Writethru a0632 09-05 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Plane, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0632,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Found that Crash-Landed in Amazon; 46 of 54 Aboard Survive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with four survivors walked to ranch,
air force reporting helicopter at scene, rescue effort cut short by darkness,
details. Picks up graf 5 pvs, `Borges said ...' ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD LEWAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Brazilian jetliner that vanished
two days ago crash-landed in the Amazon jungle, and 46 of the 54
people aboard survived, an air force spokesman said Tuesday.
   Authorities found the plane Tuesday afternoon about 1,300 miles
northwest of Rio de Janeiro after four survivors walked about two
hours through the rain forest to a ranch in Alto Xingu region of the
eastern Amazon, Col. Ronaldo Borges of the Air Force Ministry said.
   From the ranch, the survivors contacted the ministry by ham
radio, and a C-130 transport plane dropped emergency kits with food,
water and medicine by parachute over the downed plane, where the
remaining 42 survivors are camped out, the air force spokesman said.
   An air force helicopter with a medical crew arrived at the crash
area about 6 p.m., but darkness forced authorities to cut short
rescue efforts and tending to the injured until dawn Wednesday,
Borges said.
   ``The rescue team will attend to the injured and stay with the
survivors through the night,'' the spokesman said.
   The survivors included the pilot and five other crew members, who
Borges pronounced ``in good condition.''
   A twin-engine Bandeirante plane and two helicopters had arrived
at Sao Jose do Xingu, about 35 miles away, and would begin ferrying
victims from the crash site to the town at first light, he said.
   Borges said the Boeing 737-200, which was en route from Maraba to
Belem at the mouth of the Amazon River, crash-landed Sunday near Sao
Jose do Xingu but cause of the accident remained unclear.
   Joao Luis de Sousa, a spokesman for Varig, said visibility was
poor because of brush fires and thick fog, making landing difficult.
   The plane disappeared on the last leg of a regularly scheduled
flight between the southeastern city of Sao Paulo and Belem, 2,140
miles northwest of Rio. The plane had made scheduled stops in
Uberaba, Uberlandia, Goiania, Brasilia, Imperatriz and Maraba.
   According to Borges, the pilot reported problems in his
navigational system and strayed far off route. Two hours after his
scheduled arrival in Belem, the pilot radioed the airport at
Carajas, 600 miles from Belem, asking for permission to make an
emergency landing.
   Ten minutes later, a Cruzeiro airline plane received the pilot's
final message, saying he was running out of fuel, had only one
engine working and would try to make an emergency landing in the
jungle, Borges said.
   Helio Smidt, the president of Varig, who was directing the
company's rescue operations in Belem, confirmed radio contact from
the survivor.
   Varig officials said all 48 passengers and six crew were
Brazilian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
