<HEAD>`Uncle Buck' Atop Box-Office Charts Again; `Casualties' Disappears</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summer Box Office, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ed: sex, lies and videotape in 6th graf is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the third week in a row, the babysitting
comedy ``Uncle Buck'' was No. 1 at the nation's theaters while the
Vietnam drama ``Casualties of War'' dropped off the charts
completely.
   According to Labor Day weekend figures released Tuesday by
Exhibitor Relations Co., ``Uncle Buck,'' starring John Candy as an
obnoxious relative taking care of his two nieces and a nephew,
grossed $7.8 million.
   In second place was director Ron Howard's ``Parenthood,'' a
comedy featuring Steve Martin, Jason Robards, Mary Steenburgen and
Rick Moranis. ``Parenthood'' collected $7.5 million. It was followed
in third by the underwater action film ``The Abyss,'' with receipts
of $5.5 million.
   ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' the action sequel reuniting Mel Gibson and
Danny Glover, was fourth with ticket sales of $4.7 million. In fifth
was the romantic comedy ``When Harry Met Sally...,'' with Billy
Crystal and Meg Ryan, which had revenues of $4 million.
   In sixth was the drooling police comedy ``Turner &amp; Hooch,''
pairing Tom Hanks with a salivating canine, which grossed $3.8
million. ``Batman'' finished in seventh with a gate of $3.5 million.
   ``sex, lies and videotape,'' the acclaimed character study that
has been playing in limited release, expanded to 347 screens over
the weekend and boosted its income to $3.4 million for eighth place.
   Rounding out the Top 10 were ``Relentless,'' the new Judd Nelson
movie in ninth on 42.8 million, and ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids'' in
10th with $2.7 million.
   ``Casualties of War,'' the story of a group of U.S. soldiers who
rape and murder a South Vietnamese girl during the war, has proved
to be a flop. In just its third week of release, ``Casualties of
War,'' starring Michael J. Fox and Sean Penn, took in $1.9 million.
It has grossed only $13.7 million so far and is no longer on the
leader board.
   In limited release, ``Shirley Valentine'' made its debut to
strong business, collecting $245,422 on eight screens.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Uncle Buck,'' Universal, $7.8 million, 1,832 screens, $4,270
per screen, $34.7 million, three weeks.
   2. ``Parenthood,'' Universal, $7.5 million, 1,390 screens, $5,395
per screen, $64.1 million, five weeks.
   3. ``The Abyss,'' 20th Century Fox, $5.5 million, 1,532 screens,
$3,611 per screen, $40.7 million, four weeks.
   4. ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' Warner Bros., $4.7 million, 1,613
screens, $2,889 per screen, $131.3 million, nine weeks.
   5. ``When Harry Met Sally...,'' Columbia, $4 million, 1,152
screens, $3,429 per screen, $66.6 million, eight weeks.
   6. ``Turner &amp; Hooch,'' Disney, $3.8 million, 1,536 screens,
$2,500 per screen, $57.2 million, six weeks.
   7. ``Batman,'' Warner Bros., $3.5 million, 1,344 screens, $2,634
per screen, $238.6 million, 11 weeks.
   8. ``sex, lies and videotape,'' Miramax, $3.4 million, 347
screens, $9,847 per screen, $8.1 million, five weeks.
   9. ``Relentless,'' New Line, $2.8 million, 835 screens, $3,399
per screen, $3.3 million, one week.
   10. ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids,'' Disney, $2.7 million, 1,257
screens, $2,179 per screen, $119.1 million, 10 weeks.
