<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1948EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DrugStrategy-Glance     09-05 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Strategy-Glance,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Drug War Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following outlines components of President
Bush's national drug strategy at a glance. The highlights of the
strategy include:
   _ $350 million for states and local governments for criminal
justice, law enforcement and prison systems.
   _ $1.2 billion for construction of federal prisons.
   _ Requiring federally acceptable drug prevention programs and
policies as a condition to receive federal funds for schools and
colleges.
   _ Withholding federal criminal justice funds from states that do
not have drug testing for prisoners, parolees and people arrested,
and consider test results when determining sentencing, bail and
parole.
   _ $261 million to help the Andean countries of Peru, Bolivia and
Colombia fight drug lords.
   _ More money for domestic eradication efforts.
   _ Tougher regulations for federal housing projects to expedite
evictions of drug dealers, and expand drug prevention programs for
resident associations.
   _ Urges greater use of employee drug testing in state and local
government and the private sector.
   _ Encourages stiffer penalties for drug users.
   _ More federal money for community drug prevention efforts.
   _ Increased money for treatment programs to expand the number of
people who can be treated, the range of treatment programs, and
emphasize treatment for pregnant women who use drugs.
   _ Making receipt of federal treatment funds contingent on state
and local compliance with federal standards for effective drug
treatment programs.
   _ Expanded research and information coordination to evaluate and
develop more effective treatments.
   _ Greater border interdiction emphasis on drug-detection dogs,
document fraud, container inspection and other methods.
   _ More emphasis on air interdiction, and catching drug couriers
and money launderers.
</TEXT>
