<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     09-05 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Attack Kills 7 Children, Woman in Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven children who had been playing in
the street and one woman were killed Tuesday when a rocket slammed
into the dirt road of a poor neighborhood in north Kabul, residents
said.
   They said at least five people were wounded by shrapnel from the
explosion. At least six rockets hit the Khair Khana area around 4
p.m., they added.
   The children ranged in age from 5 to 12 years, the residents said.
   Kabul has come under rocket attack almost daily since late June.
More than 300 people have been killed and more than 700 injured. A
heavy attack Saturday killed 16 people and wounded 52.
   The government blames the U.S-backed mujahedeen rebels based in
Pakistan for the attacks. The mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors,
accuse the Marxist government itself of firing the rockets.
   In Khair Khana, the spent rockets looked like crumpled tin cans
in the dust.
   The wailing of women came from over the mud brick garden walls as
neighbors scurried back and forth trying to comfort the bereaved.
   ``This is an American-Pakistani rocket,'' said a resident named
Aiamodin as he kicked with his toe a shell case embedded in the road.
   Nearby, on a street where the rocket shattered walls but did not
kill anyone, residents worked to clean up the mess.
   A young girl dumped a basketful of glass in a ditch while a
workman replaced the windows in the corner pharmacy.
   ``It's just a poor neighborhood, shopkeepers,'' said Mohammed, a
government employee.
