<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Drugs-Plan 2ndLd-Writethru a0675 09-05 1153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Plan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0675,1,090</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Plan Strikes at Casual Users As Well As Drug Traffickers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New details throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $7.9 billion national drug control strategy
announced Tuesday by the Bush administration recommends stripping
even casual drug users of their drivers licenses while mounting a
costly struggle against the drug lords of South America.
   ``Whatever the extent of their offense, if they use drugs they
should be held accountable,'' President Bush declared of the
millions of casual drug users in this country.
   For the most hardened drug traffickers in the United States, Bush
renewed his endorsement of the death penalty.
   For the war against the drug lords of South America, he
recommended $261 million in 1990 aid and the promise of $2 billion
more over the following five years for the governments of Colombia,
Peru and Bolivia _ nations that produce most of the cocaine that
crosses U.S. borders.
   For the casual drug users in the United States, he urged states
to suspend their drivers licenses, notify their employers, put them
in jail cells overnight or on weekends, evict them from public
housing or seize their cars. He also urged newspapers to publish the
names of drug offenders.
   The president called for ``a mix of sanctions'' against the
youthful offender, including school suspension, parental
notification, postponement of drivers license eligibility and
weekends of community service.
   The plan envisions military-style boot camps ``to bring a sense
of order and discipline to the lives of youthful, non-violent
first-time offenders and perhaps serve as a deterrent against future
crimes.''
   Among its other proposals: halfway houses and ``various house
arrest programs that keep an offender incapacitated at his own
expense.''
   The proposals include an increase in federal funds for treatment
of addicts and for prevention programs.
   But the main emphasis was on bringing the suppliers and users of
illegal drugs to justice.
   ``We should be tough on drugs _ much tougher than we are now,''
the president's 154-page report declared.
   ``Anyone who sells drugs _ and (to a great if poorly understood
extent) anyone who uses them _ is involved in an international
criminal enterprise that is killing thousands of Americans each
year,'' says the strategy which Bush unveiled in a nationally
televised address.
   National drug control policy director William J. Bennett summed
up a crucial element of the $7.9 billion anti-drug strategy: ``Drug
use, we say, is wrong.''
   ``There are lots of other things that are wrong _ money
laundering, crime, violence in the inner city _ but drug use itself
is wrong, and that means the strategy is aimed at reducing drug
use,'' Bennett said at a White House briefing shortly before Bush's
speech.
   The White House recommendations to the states are just that _
Bush rejected earlier plans to threaten states with the loss of
federal highway funds and criminal justice funds if they failed to
implement tough new sanctions.
   However, states must impose drug testing for arrestees,
prisoners, parolees and those out on bail to receive criminal
justice grants.
   Similar testing would be mandated for all federal arrestees, and
complete abstinence from drugs would be a condition for release on
bond, probation or parole.
   Bush plans to help cities enforce whatever anti-drug laws they
have on the books by pumping $350 million into law enforcement
grants, a $200 million increase over the current authorization.
Local governments can use some of the money to plan new jails, while
the federal government sets aside some $1.2 billion for construction
of new federal prisons.
   The federal prison system has a capacity of 31,000 inmates. The
strategy recommends expanding this by 77 percent.
   While the Bush strategy focuses on making those at all levels of
drug trafficking pay for their crimes, it also would provide help
for addicts, particularly those suffering from addiction to crack,
the relatively cheap cocaine derivative that is smoked.
   The Bush proposal calls for a 53 percent increase in federal
funds for drug abuse treatment, from $604 million authorized in the
current budget to $925 million in 1990. Programs would have to
demonstrate their success to receive funds.
   In addition, the strategy seeks $1.2 billion for prevention
efforts, 25 percent over the current authorization of $943 million.
   The strategy calls for $25 million in emergency drug education
grants for urban areas with major drug problems. That would be in
addition to the $350 million now spent to support school-based drug
education programs.
   It also requires schools, colleges and universities to impose
firm drive prevention programs and policies to receive any federal
funds.
   Overseas, the strategy takes into account the plight of the
governments of Colombia, Peru and Bolivia, the three main cocaine
producers, in their efforts to combat the drug trade while battling
insurgent groups and maintaining a legitimate economy.
   The recent flareup of violence in Colombia _ where the government
reinstituted its agreement to extradite alleged drug traffickers to
the United States to stand trial _ already has resulted in the
emergency dispatch of some $65 million in immediate military aid.
   For 1990, the strategy calls for $261 million to be spent in
military and law enforcement aid for these three South American
countries, more than a four-fold increase over the approximately $53
million in the current budget for anti-drug efforts. Total foreign
aid to those countries, including the anti-drug money, is almost
$163 million in 1989.
   Budget Director Richard Darman announced Tuesday that the
administration will seek $2 billion over the next five years in
economic aid to the three countries, much of it contingent on those
countries proving their willingness to fight drug traffickers.
   The strategy urges ``elevation of drugs as a bilateral foreign
policy issue'' and says that ``In the past, programs in this area
have been hampered by the lack of importance given by this country
to the drug issue as a foreign policy concern.''
   Meanwhile, the strategy also called for more widespread drug
testing in the public and private sectors, and encouraged employers
to identify employees who use drugs, including drug testing ``where
appropriate.''
   The numbers in the strategy reflect authorization figures, not
what actually will be spent or where that money will come from. For
example, one Senate staffer familiar with the drug issue noted that
prisons take a long time to build, and only a small portion of the
$1.2 billion for prisons will be spent in 1990.
   When Congress passed the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988, it called
for authorization of $2.8 billion above what was already being
spent. Faced with a staggering budget deficit, Congress agreed to
spend only $500 million in fiscal 1989 and up to $967 million by the
end of fiscal 1990.
   A bid by the House to spend $822 million in a supplementary
spending bill earlier this year was killed following a threat by
Darman. The supplementary spending on anti-drug efforts later was
lowered to about $75 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0143 </DOCNO>
