<FIRST>r a AM-Newspage-Evert     09-05 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspage-Evert,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chris Evert's Last Major Tournament Appearance Ends in Defeat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The illustrious pro tennis career of Chris Evert
came to an end Tuesday in the quarterfinals of the U.S. Open when
she was beaten by Zina Garrison, 7-6, 6-2.
   Evert's final shot at a major event was a forehand return of
serve into the net. She shook hands with Garrison and received a
standing ovation from the crowd.
   The 34-year-old Evert will represent the United States in the
Federation Cup at Tokyo next month, and might play in some other
tournaments, but she said this was her last appearance in a major
tournament.
   The classy master of the two-handed backhand, with peerless
baseline groundstrokes and a nearly stoic on-court demeanor, first
made her mark by reaching the semifinals at the U.S. Open in 1971,
when she was 16.
   ``I've had a lot of success here,'' Evert said. ``I've got
excellent memories of Forest Hills and Flushing Meadow. The crowds
were great all week and that's very special to me.''
   Earlier in the tournament, Evert became the first player with 100
victories in the Open.
