<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2044EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Soviet     09-05 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soviet,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Says Moscow Seeks `Truly Federal State'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a visiting Soviet delegation said
Tuesday that President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is trying to develop a
``truly federal state,'' but ruled out independence for Soviet
republics seeking greater autonomy.
   Breakaway independent states ``would not be in the interests of
either the Baltic republics themselves or the U.S.S.R,'' said
Yevgeny M. Primakov, chairman of the Soviet of the Union, one of two
houses of the Supreme Soviet legislature.
   ``What we are trying to achieve is a truly federal state and not
in name only, but in essence,'' he said, speaking through an
interpreter at the news conference at the Soviet Embassy. ``We would
like the republics to be as sovereign and independent as possible.''
   Primakov is in London for a meeting of the Inter-Parliamentary
Union, a gathering of lawmakers from around the world.
   Earlier, Moscow and London announced that British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher will visit Moscow for talks with Gorbachev on
Sept. 23 on her way home from a trip to Tokyo.
   It will be their first meeting since Britain expelled 11 Soviet
diplomats and journalists in May, charging they were spies, and the
Soviet Union retaliated by ordering out 11 Britons.
   Primakov said he hoped the visit would give a new impetus to arms
control negotiations and other East-West issues.
   ``We are not going to forget that the first meeting between
Mikhail Gorbachev and Margaret Thatcher was in a way a prelude to a
number of developments in the international arena which considerably
reduced tensions,'' said Primakov.
   He was referring to a 1984 meeting in London. Gorbachev and Mrs.
Thatcher appeared to strike up a particularly good personal
relationship and she described him as someone with whom she could
``do business.''
   However, relations cooled after the expulsions in May.
   Also Tuesday, the Foreign Office announced that Foreign Secretary
John Major will visit the United States next week.
   Major, who became foreign secretary in July, will spend Sunday
through Tuesday in Washington and meet with President Bush, Vice
President Dan Quayle and Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
</TEXT>
