<FIRST>u i AM-Non-Aligned     09-05 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Non-Aligned,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Calls U.S. Dollar `Devil Itself,' Seeks Resettling of Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi told
the non-aligned movement Tuesday in a rambling speech that the U.S.
dollar is ``the devil itself'' and Jews in Israel should be
resettled elsewhere.
   Gadhafi spoke without a prepared text for one hour and 25 minutes
on the second day of the four-day summit, ignoring the time limit of
20 minutes for each leader addressing the assembly.
   Some delegates said the speech was an embarrassment.
   Earlier, Cuban Vice President Raul Castro fired broadsides
against the United States, accusing it of nurturing subversion plans
against Cuba.
   In other speeches to the delegates from 102 nations:
   _Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi said, ``It is dominance by
economic pressure that is now emerging as the single most important
threat to the independence, freedom and stability of the non-aligned
nations. ... The central issue in the present international economic
order is the domination of the global economy by a few without
regard to the interests of the many.''
   _Nigerian President Ibrahim Badamosi Babangida demanded major
concessions from the West to ease the debt burden, as did other
African delegates earlier. He said official debts owed to creditor
countries should be abolished through ``outright cancellation by
creditor countries.'' He asked partial writeoffs of debts to
commercial banks and international financial institutions.
   _The Emir of Kuwait, Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmed al-Sabah proposed an
international meeting under U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de
Cuellar involving creditor countries, the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank on ways to resolve the debt crisis.
   Gadhafi's address, simultaneously translated on in-house
television at the Sava Hall conference center, was marked by
incomplete sentences and repetitive and often confusing statements.
   ``The dollar is one of the worst currencies, the devil itself, it
should be burned, it should not be of any real value at all,'' the
Libyan leader declared.
   He also said charging interest on credits was ``against the
religion of Islam'' and that Libya would stop demanding interest
from debtor countries.
   He said ``the Jews'' should be resettled ``from Palestine'' to
form a buffer state between France and Germany.
   Later he suggested that ``if the United States is sympathizing
with (the Jews) why doesn't it give them Alaska?''
   In an apparent attempt to underscore what he believes is an
absurdity of Jews settling in Israel, Gadhafi asked, ``Why don't we
Moslems go to New York?''
   A Yugoslav delegate grumbled, ``His speech is a mockery of the
world we live in and of the non-aligned movement.''
   An Arab delegate commented, ``There is certainly something mad
about him, but some of his ideas were not so bad.''
   Both delegates spoke on condition of not being identified.
   Raul Castro, brother of President Fidel Castro, made attacks on
the United States a main theme of his address to the conference,
which was attended by about 50 heads of state and about a dozen
prime ministers from the Middle East, Africa, Asia and Latin America.
   Castro accused Washington of ``aggression'' against Panama and
called it ``a crime we cannot tolerate,'' according to an English
version of his speech made available by Cuba's Prensa Latina news
agency.
   ``The United States, the major imperialist power, is behaving
today more arrogantly, threateningly and aggressively than ever
before.''
   He said Cuba is ``now being subjected to an unprecedented
defamation campaign and new plans for penetration and subversion''
by the United States.
   The United Nations' Perez de Cuellar was in Belgrade for the
summit and met Tuesday with Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz.
   In remarks later to reporters, Aziz charged that Iran rejects
peace talks with Iraq on settling the Persian Gulf war.
   Talks between Iran and Iraq, held under U.N. auspices, collapsed
last March.
   The two countries' 8-year border war ended inconclusively with a
cease-fire in August 1988.
   On Monday, de Cuellar met with Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati, who insisted Iran was willing to resume the talks.
</TEXT>
