<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Rebels 2ndLd-Writethru a0678 09-05 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Rebels, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0678,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Propose New Peace Talks, Cease-fire Announced</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to include fierce battle, 16 soldiers killed,
details. Picks up graf 4 pvs, `Col. Inocente ...' Minor editing thereafter
to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TALLI NAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran rebels said Tuesday they have
proposed talks with the new rightist government to end El Salvador's
civil war and that negotiations begin next week.
   There was no immediate response from the Salvadoran government,
but it did announce a 48-hour cease-fire.
   The announcements followed a fierce pre-dawn battle in
northeastern El Salvador in which at least 16 soldiers were killed.
   Armed Forces spokesmen reported the deaths after the fighting
outside Chilanga in Morazan province. They said the rebels also
suffered ``numerous casualties'' but gave no number.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, which represents
five left-wing guerrilla groups fighting El Salvador's U.S.-backed
government, called for talks to be held in Mexico starting sometime
between next Sunday and Thursday _ Sept. 10-Sept. 14.
   Col. Inocente Montano, the vice minister of defense, said Tuesday
the armed forces would observe a cease-fire Sept. 14-15 as part of
the celebration marking Central America's independence from Spain on
Sept. 15, 1821.
   Montano did not mention the rebels' proposal for peace talks but
told reporters the cease-fire ``is a positive initiative ... as long
as it is respected by the FMLN,'' the Spanish initials for the
guerrillas's front.
   A cease-fire for the independence festivities had been suggested
on Monday by the Permanent Committee of the National Debate for
Peace, an organization representing more than 70 church, union,
humanitarian and civic groups.
   It the government agrees to the proposed peace negotiations it
would be the first meeting between the two sides since President
Alfredo Cristiani of the conservative Republican Nationalist
Alliance suggested talks at his inauguration June 1. The guerrillas
agreed at that time but the effort snagged on the mechanics of
arranging the dialogue.
   ``We're taking away practically all obstacles,'' said Ana
Guadalupe Martinez, a rebel commander. ``We're making it the easiest
thing in the world.''
   In a significant softening of their previous conditions, she said
the front would bargain with any committee the government names.
   Before, the rebels had insisted that an army representative and
high-level officials be at the negotiating table. They rejected one
delegation the government considered on grounds its members would
not have the power to negotiate.
   The front suggested the dates and Mexico as a site for the talks
in a proposal sent Friday to Cristiani through Monsignor Arturo
Rivera Damas, the archbishop of San Salvador, Ms. Martinez told a
news conference in Mexico City.
   She added the front has not received a reply from the government.
   But she said the FMLN had received an unacceptable response to a
proposal that the government release all wounded rebel it is holding
as prisoners.
   Ms. Martinez said the proposal was made through Rivera Damas and
the government replied that it would release the wounded prisoners
if the rebels stopped sabotaging electrical installations and their
bans on transportation.
   ``That point was not negotiable,'' she said.
   Mario Lopez, another rebel commander, said new steps would be
announced Thursday.
   ``Commanders will make public a series of measures to create an
atmosphere of confidence for the negotiations,'' Lopez told
reporters.
   He did not elaborate but there was speculation the offers might
include a cease-fire.
   In the past the guerrillas have opposed a unilateral cease-fire,
saying a truce would have be to be negotiated at the bargaining
table.
   The FMLN, in its proposal for talks next week, again demanded
Rivera Damas be present during negotiations.
   Cristiani has said the archbishop should not be involved in the
talks.
   The FMLN also has insisted that delegates from the Organization
of American States and United Nations be present.
   Lopez said rebel representatives met Monday in Costa Rica with
OAS Secretary-General Joao Baena Soares and Francisco Bandrel, a
U.N. representative.
   Three rounds of talks with the government of former President
Jose Napoleon Duarte between 1984 and 1987 failed to make progress
toward ending the nearly 10-year-old war. Duarte headed a centrist
Christian Democrat government.
   An estimated 70,000 people, most of them civilians, have been
killed in the fighting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
