<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ChineseStudents     09-05 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Students,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>TV Images Subside but Chinese Reformists Continue Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Chinese students at U.S.
colleges this fall has dropped sharply, but those remaining still
feel the legacy of protest from this summer's quest for democracy at
Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   ``TV forgets you but people don't,'' Liu Yuan, president of The
China Information Center here, said Tuesday.
   ``Television needs a hot story, but actually that's not how
changing a system really works,'' Liu said. ``That's not how a
movement grows.''
   Students in the Boston area include Wu'er Kaixi of Harvard
University and Shen Tong of Brandeis University, exiled leaders of
the democracy movement who've been on the Chinese government's
most-wanted list since the student demonstrations in Tiananmen
Square in June.
   In the months following the crackdown on protesters, martial law
has been imposed, many demonstrators have been jailed or executed
and Western journalists in China have had a tough time getting
people to talk.
   But The China Information center, which was set up in this Boston
suburb, still receives more than 200 calls daily, and volunteers
still work around the clock relaying messages to and from contacts
in Western Europe, Japan and Australia.
   China Center volunteer David Blumental, who was one of the
protesters near Shanghai in June, said true reform would only come
by applying quiet, but constant, external pressure on the government.
   ``The focus has moved outside of China, as has the main
leadership,'' he said. ``The focus has moved to activities that will
promote the flow of the truth back and forth out of China.''
   Organizers here are planning a worldwide fast for Oct. 1, the
40th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China,
and conferences to debate the issues concerning the reform movement.
   Student activists in China went underground after the crackdown,
but many have returned to campuses there and face arrest.
   ``They're in a dangerous position,'' Liu said. ``We can't push
too much. The only way we can hurt the Chinese government is to tell
the truth.''
   The government has made it difficult for the story to get out. In
addition to the crackdown, the number of students granted visas for
study abroad has been dramatically reduced, U.S. State Department
officials said Tuesday.
   Chinese Embasssy and State Department officials in Washington
said they could not immediately pin down the number of visas issued
since June, but State Department spokesman Kenneth Bailes said it
had dropped.
   ``After the events in Tiananmen Square the government required
that those who had been previously issued such documents had to
apply for new ones,'' Bailes said. ``That in itself would cut down
on the number who actually got visas.''
   Bailes said that while no firm figures are available, the
impression persists that up to half the 40,000 Chinese who were
studying in the United States last year may not have returned.
   At Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government, only two of
the six Chinese students expected showed up for a summer fellowship
program. About half of the 80 students originally expected at the
University of California at Berkeley will attend this fall, said
Marvin Baron, director of the school's international office.
   ``I know a lot of people who were planning on coming, but only
know of one who got out,'' Blumental said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
