<FIRST>u a AM-DrugAgentSlain 1stLd-Writethru a0715 09-05 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Agent Slain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican National Questioned in Slaying of DEA Agent Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Zuno-Arce, 59...' to CORRECT brother to sister.
Picks up 5th graf, `U.S. District...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials blocked the
court-ordered release Tuesday of former Mexican President Luis
Echeverria's brother-in-law, who was being held in federal jail for
questioning in the 1985 slaying of a U.S. drug agent.
   The surprise turn of events came hours after a federal judge said
he did not believe Ruben Zuno Arce was a material witness to the
slaying of U.S. drug agent Enrique Camarena.
   Zuno-Arce, who had wept when the judge announced his finding, was
grim faced later as he was led out of court by U.S. Marshals for
transport to San Antonio, Texas, for an immigration hearing.
   Zuno-Arce, 59, whose sister is married to Echeverria, was held on
an immigration warrant alleging he is involved in drug trafficking.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie, who had ordered Zuno
released after 28 days in custody, said he was powerless to
interfere with INS.
   Zuno-Arce's attorney, Edward Medvene, denied the drug trafficking
allegations. At the earlier hearing, Medvene had argued that his
client had nothing to do with the slaying, but had the misfortune of
having a house that was ultimately sold to reputed drug lord Rafael
Caro Quintero, who allegedly masterminded the slaying of Camarena.
   The government had sought to keep Zuno-Arce in prison in order to
ensure his testimony at the upcoming trial of Juan Jose Bernabe
Ramirez, who is the latest defendant charged in the Camarena case.
His trial is scheduled for Oct. 3. Prosecutors argued to keep
Zuno-Arce in custody until then. The judge refused.
   Camarena and his Mexican pilot, Alfredo Zavala-Avelar, were
tortured and killed in Guadalajara, Mexico, in February 1985. Their
bodies were found four weeks later in a remote area of Michoacan
state.
   Zuno-Arce was not charged with any crime, but in mid-August
Rafeedie ordered him temporarily held without bail. The judge had
warned prosecutors he would not allow the indefinite imprisonment of
Zuno-Arce.
   Several members of the Mexican federal police force were linked
to the killings and one, Raul Lopez Alvarez, was convicted in Los
Angeles last year along with two drug traffickers.
   Caro-Quintero is in custody awaiting trial in Mexico City. Seven
more men are charged with murder and conspiracy in the case.
   Echeverria was president of Mexico from 1970 to 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
