<FIRST>u i AM-SovietTrawler 1stLd-Writethru a0707 09-05 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Trawler, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0707,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>14 Soviet Sailors Missing After Ship Collision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with new material and editing. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Finnish tanker and a Soviet trawler
collided in the Baltic early Wednesday and 14 of the trawler's 15
crew members were missing, the Tingstade Coastal radio station
reported.
   The one known survivor, the trawler's radio officer, was reported
badly hurt.
   Tingstade radio operator Richard Warff said the Swedish navy
reported finding four empty life rafts.
   The collision took place south of the Swedish island of Gotland
and the Soviet trawler Ladushkin sank soon after, the radio station
said.
   Rescue team leader Mats Jakobsson of the Swedish navy reported
that chances of finding anyone alive were ``dim. They are decreasing
every minute.''
   Jakobsson, speaking to Swedish radio three hours after the
collision, said the 6,000-ton tanker Tebo Star veered to avoid
hitting another Soviet trawler when Ladushkin suddenly appeared in
front of the tanker.
   The Russian trawler Matrosova picked up one survivor more than an
hour after the collision, which took place at 13 minutes after
Tuesday midnight, the Tingstade station said.
   Swedish navy units, including helicopters, were quickly on the
scene to help in the search. The navy had been holding maneuvers in
the area.
   The survivor was taken to a Swedish east coast hospital by
helicopter, Warff said.
   The Finnish tanker immediately sent a Mayday message following
the collision.
</TEXT>
