<DOCNO> AP890905-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Drugs-Reaction 2ndLd-Writethru a0686 09-05 0998</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Reaction, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0686,1000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 8 grafs after 4th graf with Bush saying no new taxes
and statements from DeConcini and Dole and local reaction; SUBS grafs 13-14
pvs with six new grafs with Biden, Kennedy, Rostenkowski react; pickup
15th graf pvs: Sen. Richard ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats led by House Speaker Thomas Foley
said Tuesday the Bush administration's drug plan will increase
pressure for a tax boost, while Republicans praised the plan and
vowed to find the money somehow.
   ``It's very difficult to assume we can, at least over the long
term, meet the cost of the drug war without some additional revenue
coming into the government,'' Foley said after President Bush met
with congressional leaders.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., emerged from the White House meeting
to tell reporters there would ``be some differences about where the
money comes from, but we can get the money.''
   Bush described a $7.9 billion program stressing tougher penalties
for drug users and more money for prisons, treatment programs,
education and prevention.
   In his nationally televised speech outlining the plan, Bush said
Tuesday night that the government ``can pay for this fight against
drugs without raising taxes or adding to the budget deficit.''
   ``We have submitted our plan to Congress that shows just how to
fund it within the limits of our bipartisan budget agreement,'' Bush
said.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., said, however, that Bush ``has
suggested only $716 million in offsets to finance a $2 billion
program. He has missed the mark there.'' He said much broader budget
offsets in programs such as the B2 bomber and foreign aid would be
needed to do the job.
   Meanwhile, Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., issued a
statement saying that ``what we don't need now is instant criticism
and nitpicking about what's wrong with the president's plan.''
   ``Congress helps spend about $1 trillion every year, so I feel
confident we can find enough funding to fuel our war on drugs,''
Dole said. ``I just don't believe we have to raise taxes to pay for
it. This is a war on drugs, not a war on the American taxpayer.''
   Initial reaction among local officials around the nation, notably
police chiefs, was welcoming _ but these officials said they could
not be optimistic about an easy victory.
   Baltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke, who last year called for legalizing
drugs, said it was too early to judge Bush's strategy.
   ``We ought to be a little bit careful because this is the third
time now cinse 1972 a president has launched an all-out war against
drugs,'' Schmoke said.
   Foley said Bush outlined $700 million in budget transfers to pay
for the plan and ``didn't seem to suggest any new taxes, I think
that's fair to say.''
   ``Over time, I think, some of us feel that in order to deal with
the entire functioning of government we're going to need some
additional revenues,'' Foley added.
   House Minority Leader Robert H. Michel, R-Ill., suggested that a
transfer of funds should work for the first year of the drug war
``and after that, we're going to have to take a look at it ...
because it's not going to be won in one year. And it will be a
costly venture when it's over.''
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., emerged from the session complaining
about plans to obtain the money through transfers. ``It just seems
unfair to me to be unfair to declare war and tell the Congress to
come back and pick up the money without talking about taxes or
without talking about waiving (the) Gramm-Rudman'' deficit reduction
law.
   ``To say that we've declared war and develop a domestic policy
and a foreign policy and then we have to go back and nickle and dime
from the different committees to raise $700 million, to me it just
doesn't seem as though we're sincere,'' Rangel said.
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del.,
delivering the Democratic response, said that the Bush plan ``is not
tough enough, bold enough or imaginative enough.'' He called for a
much broader attack, including an international team to hunt down
drug kingpins.
   ``There must be no safe haven for these narco-terrorists,'' Biden
said.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said: ``I commend President Bush
for the comprehensive strategy he has announced in the war on drugs
... the phony war of the past eight years is over.'' But he added:
   ``In my view, substantially more federal resources are needed ...
to make our national strategy more credible.''
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., said that ``unless the president
supports the tax increases that will be necessary to fight this war,
the drug dealers are going to win.''
   ``As despicable as drug dealers are, they understand economics,''
Rostenkowski said. ``If you want to play, you've got to pay.''
   Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., expressed ``strong support'' for
what he called ``a comprehensive plan and challenge to the nation.''
   ``Hopefully, an overwhelming majority of Americans are prepared
to reject totally the use of narcotics and to help relieve the
suffering of those previously addicted,'' he said. He also praised
Bush for offering aid to South American nations attempting to
curtail cocaine production.
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., said he was ``glad the president
has gone beyond sloganeering ... but the best kept secret in town is
how we pay for it.''
   ``It will take more than one speech,'' Leahy said. ``We need
presidential leadership along with the financial commitment to
finish the job.''
   In the House, Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., was critical of the
Bush blueprint, saying ``it isn't really a war on drugs. It's barely
a skirmish against drugs.''
   He called for a 1 percent surtax on individual and corporate
income taxes, saying there was no question that voters would support
it as a way to fight the drug war. ``People from one end of America
to the other will,'' he said, ``if they know where the money is
going.''
</TEXT>
