<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Iraq     09-05 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Iraq,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Up to 700 Dead in Blast at Iraqi Defense Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British newspaper reported Wednesday that up to
700 Iraqis and Egyptians died in an explosion Aug. 17 at a secret
Iraqi missile center near the capital of Baghdad.
   The Independent, quoting unidentified diplomats and Middle East
sources, said Iraq, with Egyptian assistance, is believed to be
developing missile technology at the center near Al Hillah, 40 miles
south of Baghdad.
   The report said the explosion caused a fire that took
firefighting planes nearly a week to extinguish. But it said no
reports of the disaster had appeared in the official Iraqi news
media.
   The London newspaper quoted U.S. diplomats as saying they had
received information from Iraqi sources of a major incident in the
second half of August in which the casualty toll numbered in the low
hundreds.
   But it quoted unspecified sources as saying that 700 bodies had
been recovered. It quoted the other sources as saying the blast
destroyed a third of the huge center, which contained workers'
housing as well as armament factories.
   The paper said there was no immediate suggestion of sabotage.
   ``The casualties appear to have included Egyptian military and
civilian engineers as well as Iraqi defense workers,'' The
Independent said. ``Sources in Cairo said that three Egyptian Air
Force transports flew from Iraq to the al-Mazha air base on 18
August, apparently carrying dead and injured from the explosion ...
   ``Egyptian sources said the Maadi military hospital in Cairo was
closed to civilian visitors from 19 August and doctors and nurses
specializing in skin grafts, respiratory disorders and burns were
drafted in.''
   The paper said Egyptian personnel have been based in Iraq for two
years.
   It reported: ``The joint Egyptian-Iraqi team succeeded in
producing a longer-range version of the Soviet-made Scud-B missile
by adding a North Korean-made supplementary fuel tank and reducing
the payload...
   ``The team also developed the Badr-2000, an improved version of
the Argentine Condor-2. By early 1988, the Egyptians managed to
increase the range of the missile to over 500 miles. But it has
proved notoriously inaccurate.''
</TEXT>
