<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-USVeterans     09-05 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US Veterans,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Vets Meet With Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven American veterans of the Vietnam
War met Tuesday with Gen. Manuel Antonio Notiega and one of them,
Phillip Jones, later told reporters they expressed ``a wish for
peace'' to the Panamanian leader.
   Also at the meeting was provisional President Francisco
Rodriguez, who took office Sept. 1. Rodriguez told the seven,
``Panama is a noble country, not an enemy of the American people,
but we want you to respect us.''
   Noriega, who was accompanied by five colonels, did not comment on
his talks with the veterans.
   The U.S. government does not recognize Rodriguez, viewing him as
a puppet of Noriega. The general, chief of Panama's Defense Forces,
has denied U.S. drug trafficking charges leveled against him last
year in Florida. Rodriguez took office to fill a vacuum created when
the government canceled May 7 elections, which foreign observers
said were won by the opposition.
   The veterans arrived Monday in Panama and are due to return
Wednesday to the United States. They were among foreign groups who
have expressed sympathy for Noriega's position.
</TEXT>
