<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv06   09-05 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 06,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, Sept. 06</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Should Broker-Client Conversations Be Taped? ^By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If brokers really want to improve their image
they might consider recording all conversations with their clients.
   To do so would provide a service to themselves and their clients,
says James B. Cloonan. It might protect each of them. It would tend
to limit deceit and even the mild puffery that can lead to
misunderstandings, he says.
   The idea is also likely to set off a backlash, especially from
sales people expert in the arts and nuances of enticing investors
into stocks they could do without. In effect, it would place every
conversation on the record.
   Cloonan, however, observes that the reputation of the industry,
battered in recent years by insider trading scandals, may be in need
of repairs to its image, and that electronic documentation can only
help.
   He has some experience in the field, being an adviser to the
Congressional Office of Technology Assessment, which has been
seeking ways to prevent fraud through legislation and electronic
surveillance.
   Most of that effort, however, has been involved with the major
insider trading scandals, and with indictments for fraud and various
securities law violations.
   Meanwhile, he says, another serious fraud persists. He calls it
``front-office fraud.'' It includes churning, unsuitable
recommendations, unauthorized trading and making unfulfillable
promises.''
   For various reasons, says Cloonan, who is president of the
110,000-member, Chicago-based American Association of Individual
Investors, these activities get much less attention from the legal
system and the media.
   ``While an individual involved in insider trading may go to
prison and pay a fine of millions of dollars, the broker who cheats
a retired person out of his life savings seems to get a short
suspension or a small fine,'' he says.
   Cloonan, a former professor, thinks so highly of the need for
recording broker conversations that he wrote an editorial on the
subject for the AAII Journal. Front-office fraud must be more
vigorously prosecuted, he says.
   He believes the reason prosecutions aren't as common in this area
is that so much boils down to a conversation involving only two
people. ``His word against hers, perhaps a misunderstanding _ who
knows?''
   As a consequence, criminal prosecution isn't likely, and civil
action or arbitration usually involves some kind of modest
settlement, and the punishments may be a temporary or permanent
suspension of broker privileges.
   ``I see reports of such behavior not only in boiler room
penny-stock operations, but in the better-known brokerage firms, as
well,'' he says. And, he adds, temptation may grow as retail brokers
incur profitability pressures.
   Of course, investors themselves could record conversations or
keep a journal. But, Cloonan believes, those individuals most likely
to be cheated are the least likely to do so. In his view, it should
be the broker's job.
   ``With today's technology I see no reason why conversations
shouldn't be recorded,'' he says. In fact, some discount stock and
commodity brokers already use such methods to record oral orders,
erasing the tapes after confirmation.
   The very existence of the recording would tend to place
constraints on exaggeration and fraud, and the recording would
provide evidence in cases where laws were violated. Customer and
sales person alike would benefit.
   ``It would be nice for investors to be able to prove what they
authorized,'' said Cloonan. ``And it would be nice for brokers to be
protected from unjust accusations from confused clients, when that
is the case.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed, Sept. 06</NOTE>
</DOC>
