<DOCNO> AP890905-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1508EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   09-05 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``The Big Picture''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Film opens wide Sept. 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Satire, George S. Kaufman once warned, ``is what closes on
Saturday night.'' That didn't stop him from collaborating with Moss
Hart on ``Once in a Lifetime,'' the biting spoof of early Hollywood.
   The New Hollywood with its buzz-phrases (``let's take a meeting
and do lunch'') and numbing vapidity and undercurrent of deceit
could certainly provide ample material for a biting satire. ``The
Big Picture'' isn't it. Christopher Guest and his collaborators are
not Kaufman and Hart, and their film proves annoyingly flat, like a
series of shaggy-dog stories without punchlines.
   More was expected of Guest, who contributed some of the funniest
sequences to ``Saturday Night Live'' as writer and actor. He also
co-wrote and appeared in Rob Reiner's clever send-up of the rock
world, ``This Is Spinal Tap.''
   Guest, who makes his feature debut as a director with ``The Big
Picture,'' co-wrote the story with Michael Varhol (who also
produced). They wrote the screenplay along with Michael McKean. They
obviously took delight in conveying ``inside'' jokes. Trouble is,
many of them are too inside for the layman.
   ``The Big Picture'' opens promisingly enough with an awards
program at the National Film Institute. Student films, most of them
grossly pretentious, are screened. The winner is Nick Chapman (Kevin
Bacon), an eager young filmmaker with high principles and a
supportive girlfriend (Emily Longstreth).
   Nick's award draws him into the Hollywood vortex. He is wooed by
a variety of smarmy agents and signs with an Oriental-looking loony
(Martin Short, who receives no billing).
   A big-talking studio chief (J.T. Walsh) hires Nick to direct his
original script. With dizzying speed, Nick betrays his principles,
dilutes his script, betrays his best friend (McKean) and abandons
his girlfriend for a starlet.
   Then one morning, Nick picks up the trade papers and finds the
studio boss has been fired. Nick's project is dropped, and he
becomes unemployable. After hitting bottom, he directs a music video
that makes him hot again. He is able to film his original script,
hire his best friend and reconcile with his girl.
   If Guest intended a Hollywood morality tale, it doesn't work. The
characters are standard cliches, and it's hard to believe that
Nick's dopey screenplay would get a second look at any studio. Kevin
Bacon does his best to breathe life into the weak-willed Nick, but
the character is hard to like or admire. Brief roles are played by
Eddie Albert, June Lockhart, John Cleese and Roddy McDowall.
   The Columbia release is rated PG-13, mostly for language. Running
time: 100 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1516EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   09-05 0975</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,1006</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Cousins'' (Paramount Home Video. VHS, Beta. Rated PG-13)
   
   ``Cousins'' carries no suggested retail price because it is
intended for the rental market. Good idea, because it's hardly worth
the celluloid on which it's filmed.
   ``Cousins'' is Joel Schumacher's graceless treatment of
Jean-Charles Tacchella's charming 1976 comedy, ``Cousin, Cousine.''
Schumacher makes the mistake of trying to closely follow the
original. Both open with a rousing family wedding scene in which the
husband and wife of different couples meet, run off for a little
sexual fling and leave their respective mates waiting at the
catering hall for their returns. The cuckholded spouses start up a
harmless flirtation and friendship and eventually have an affair of
their own.
   But where the original danced lightly with the passions and
eccentricities of French culture, the new version applies the thin,
moralistic veneer of an American TV sitcom with idiot level dialogue
and conviction. Simply put, the French have a different way of
viewing adultery.
   Ted Danson, as compelling in this role as a bottle of warm, flat
champagne, plays Larry Kozinski who is married to Tish, played with
airhead finesse by Sean Young. Isabella Rossellini, perhaps cast in
this movie to give it some sort of continental class and a little
sunshine, is Maria Hardy, an understanding wife and mother married
to a brutish bore named Tom (William Petersen) who sells Suburus but
who likes to say he sells BMWs.
   The truly comic moments (which were many in ``Cousin, Cousine'')
are diluted in ``Cousins'' by weighty and blunt situations: When Tom
realizes Maria and Larry are also having an affair, he confronts
Larry in typical Hollywood macho style with, ``If you go near my
wife again, I'll kill you.'' Petersen is more Fred Flintstone than
Valentino.
   What saves ``Cousins'' from utter and total oblivion is the
wonderful patter between Larry's father (Lloyd Bridges) and Larry's
son, Mitch (Keith Coogan). Grandpa and grandson have a bucolic
moment over some girlie magazines, and the scene in which Mitch
helps grandpa Vince prepare for a date with Maria's mother (Norma
Aleandro) is worth the rental.
   A totally unnecessary addition to ``Cousins'' is the subplot
involving the boy-girl problems Tom and Maria's daughter experiences
in pre-school. Who cares?
   Perhaps Hollywood will one day realize that some things get lost
in translation. One would think the lesson would have been learned
in 1983 when Jim McBride remade Jean-Luc Godard's classic 1960 film
``Breathless'' into a pathethic and misguided movie. It starred
Richard Gere, who was embarrassing as he attempted to take on the
role Jean-Paul Belmondo had created in the original.
   Something gets lost in the translation as Hollywood puts its neon
wand to French confections. If it ain't broke, don't fix it...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Tap'' (RCA-Columbia Pictures Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95.
Rated)
   
   Movie audiences have yearned for those splashy, joyous, romantic
musicals of the 1930s, '40s and '50s when boy met girl, boy lost
girl, boy got girl back and everybody lived happily everafter,
dancing all the way to the altar.
   Nick Castle, whose father choreographed many of those wonderful
Fred Astaire-Ginger Rogers vehicles, attempts to bring back those
golden dance movies with ``Tap,'' a love letter to hoofers great and
small.
   Starring Gregory Hines and some of the greatest tap kings living,
``Tap'' features excellent dancing and a splendid exuberance.
Unfortunately, the movie holds back; the dance sequences never seem
to totally reach their potential, and on the small screen they may
be lost altogether.
   One production number, in which Hines takes a club full of tap
fans out to Times Square to feel and hear the beat and rhythms of
the city (such as cars going over metal plates in the road or
construction crews thumping the pavement) and marks out a dance. The
number starts out well, luring the viewer to the rhythms and moves.
Then it fizzles.
   Another disappointment is the wistful roof-top soft shoe
performed by Hines and the lovely Suzzanne Douglas to ``Cheek to
Cheek.'' It's a romantic Fred and Ginger take-off that never really
gets off. How sad.
   The biggest problem with ``Tap'' is Castle's script and story
line. Max (Hines) is a genius dancer who unfortunately finds
second-story work more to his liking than hoofing. After a stint in
jail, he returns to New York where he hooks up with the hoods again.
At the same time, his mentor, Little Mo (Sammy Davis Jr.) encourages
him to resume his dancing and even tries to turn him on to a new tap
innovation _ amplified shoes.
   The plot, though, gets in the way of the dancing. It's not
compelling, poignant or interesting enough. The tap dancing,
however, is.
   Hines, perhaps the greatest contemporary tap stylist around these
days, is marvelous. His supporting cast includes Savion Glover, a
14-year-old hoofer who one day will make the same claim. There are
also Sandman Sims, Bunny Briggs, Harold Nicholas, Jimmy Slyde and
Steve Condos _ some of the dancers who helped define and perfect the
art and craft of tap in the 20th century.
   Forget the story. View ``Tap'' as a tribute to the great ones and
to appreciate what tap dancing was all about before Broadway and
Hollywood took away its snap and crackle.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
