<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   09-05 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The End of the Innocence'' (Geffen) _ Don Henley
   
   On the title cut of ``The End of the Innocence,'' Don Henley
interrupts his seduction of a woman to grouse about Ronald Reagan.
Best of my love, indeed.
   Henley sounds cranky on much of the rest of his new album, too.
And no wonder _ the guy is undergoing some serious transitions. On
Side 1 alone, he tells of a lover about to leave him (``I Will Not
Go Quietly''), another already in his past (``New York Minute'') and
a third that he hopes is in his future (``The Last Worthless
Evening'').
   Such emotional clutter would rob most folks of their sanity; it
robs Henley of his hooks. The tally for ``The End of the Innocence''
reads 53 minutes of music, no memorable melodies.
   Also absent is the keen social commentary that has marked the
ex-Eagle's best solo work. Here Henley stoops to attacking the most
obvious of targets, evangelists (``Little Tin God'').
   The supporting cast includes Bruce Hornsby, W. Axl Rose, Edie
Brickell, Take 6, Mike Campbell and Danny Kortchmar, so talent isn't
lacking. But inspiration is. Much of the record has the spark of a
demo tape.
   Henley had a hand in writing all 10 songs. He co-produced, played
the drums and sang all lead and some backup vocals. As the title cut
suggests, Henley might be trying to do too many things at once.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Piano Quintet in A, the ``Trout,'' by Franz Schubert; Piano
Quartet in G minor, by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart; Artur Schnabel and
the Pro Arte Quartet (EMI).
   
   Artur Schnabel, giant of 20th-century pianists and superlative
Beethoven interpreter, is reported to have said: ``I play Beethoven
to make my living; Schubert I play for love.'' His loving treatment
of the ``Trout'' can be heard on this EMI reissue of a 1935
recording, previously released on Arabesque.
   The interpretation may put off some listeners at first, but it
grows on you after a number of hearings. Schnabel's occasional
rhythmic flexing evokes an earlier romantic style, as do the string
players' tendency to slide between notes.
   The sound quality is not the greatest. The remastering from 78s
is uneven, the background noise considerable. But first violinst
Alphonse Ounnou's sweet tone and Schnabel's direct, lucid reading of
the notes shine through.
   The performance is brisk and muscular, but not so much that
Schubert's fleeting changes of color and mood are sacrificed. In the
first movement, phrases seem to build through their own natural
momentum. The cello and viola of the Pro Arte, a Belgian quartet
founded in 1912 and one of the most prominent before World War II,
sing beautifully in the Andante.
   The scherzo is the least successful of the movements, with a not
very appealing percussive, militaristic quality. The tempi in the
fourth movement variations never seem quite right, but that problem
is straightened out in the forceful finale.
   The wonderful Mozart G minor quartet was recorded a year earlier.
Schnabel and the Pro Arte members give a clean, square-cut
rendition. More than in the Schubert, the pianist's singing tone and
uncluttered phrasing come out.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
