<FIRST>r f PM-GenericDrugs     09-05 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Generic Drugs,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversy Yields No Evidence of Medical Harm, Says Consumer Advocate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also ran for AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The consumer groups who fought for acceptance
of generic drugs now find themselves defending an industry caught up
in charges of fraud and mismanagement. Despite the controversy, one
gadfly emphasizes there is no evidence generic drugs have caused any
medical harm.
   Moreover, pharmacists report few customers are switching to
generally more expensive brandname products.
   In the years since Congress approved marketing the brandname
clones, generic drugs have become a staple of the pharmaceutical
menu, accounting for about a third of all prescriptions filled in
the United States.
   The renewed attention to generics stems from disclosures of
improprieties that so far have been confined to a few generic drug
makers and Food and Drug Administration employees but that some fear
could be more widespread.
   ``At this point, there is no evidence that generic drugs have
resulted in any harm,'' reminds Dr. Sidney Wolfe, a physician and
head of the Public Citizen Health Research Group, a Ralph
Nader-founded consumer group that fought hard for generic drugs.
   Consumer reaction has been quiet.
   Although pharmacists say customers have been asking more
questions about the drugs they're getting, few have insisted on
switching to brandname products.
   ``We're surprised we're getting such a small response,'' said
John McHugh, president of the American Association of Retired
Persons Pharmacy Service, whose 12 pharmacies nationwide fill 30,000
prescriptions a day.
   AARP also worked hard to win acceptance of generic drugs, which
they say save consumers money since generics usually cost less than
the brandname drugs they mimic. And AARP officials say they continue
to support generic drugs.
   ``I don't see anything yet that would require us to backtrack,''
said John Rother, director of legislation, research and public
policy for AARP. ``So far, it appears to be a fairly isolated type
of malfeasance in the industry and within the FDA. It doesn't seem
to be something that can't be dealt with fairly quickly.''
   As evidence of its confidence, AARP last week was continuing to
fill prescriptions with Bolar Pharmaceutical Co. Inc.'s generic
version of the widely prescribed hypertension brandname drug Dyazide.
   The FDA wants to remove Bolar's drug _ the last remaining generic
of Dyazide and the company's leading seller _ from the market
because of questions about sample testing when it was approved for
marketing in 1987.
   Earlier this summer, Vitarine Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Springfield
Gardens, N.Y., withdrew its generic version of Dyazide from the
market after admitting it had substituted the brandname drug for its
own in tests conducted as part of the FDA approval process.
   Besides Bolar and Vitarine, nine other generic drug makers are
under investigation by the FDA for suspicion of improprieties
ranging from mismanagement to fraud, including sample switching.
   An additional 20 generic drug companies are under scrutiny by the
agency, and the FDA is sampling all versions of the 30
most-prescribed generic drugs on the market.
   Recently, three former employees of the FDA's generic drug
division have pleaded guilty to charges that they accepted illegal
gratuities from drug makers.
   To win approval, generic drug makers must prove to the FDA that
their product has the same potency _ that it is absorbed into the
blood at a comparable rate _ as the brandname version.
   The FDA allows about 20 percent variability in potency, which
some doctors say can be a problem for some patients with certain
illnesses and conditions.
   This has been raised by a committee of the American Academy of
Family Physicians, which is recommending that the academy go on
record this month as opposing use of generic drugs in certain
patients, including those who are 75 years and older, and those with
diabetes mellitus, congestive heart failure, cardiac problems,
psychoses, depression and asthma.
   But Wolfe and other generic drug supporters say potency
variability is no greater than the variability seen in prescribed
dosages. Doctors usually prescribe the same dose of medication for a
125-pound adult as they do for a 250-pound adult, Wolfe said.
   The brandname manufacturers, which have been defending their
products against competing generics for years, have been silent for
the most part during the controversy.
   ``The research-based drug companies could not have purchased
better advertising questioning the merits of generic drugs than
they're getting right now,'' Nordmann said. ``They don't have to say
anything. They're looking at the generic industry shoot itself in
the foot.''
   Even though those mainstream companies emphasize developing new
drugs _ and winning exclusive marketing rights during a multi-year
patent period _ they also produce roughly three-fourths of all
generic drugs sold to remain competitive with the companies that
deal solely in generic drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0825EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ForecastingTurbulence     09-05 0895</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forecasting Turbulence,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Gurus Blame Bad Data for Wrong Predictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also ran for AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peering into the future and predicting where
the $5 trillion U.S. economy is headed has never been an easy job,
but it has gotten a lot tougher lately.
   Chagrined economists have watched in horror as the government
last month made revision after revision in data on past performance
that they use for coming up with their prognostications.
   The net result was that the U.S. economy was not nearly as weak
during the spring as first believed. Consumers spent at double the
pace first reported, employment growth was much stronger and the
overall economy, rather than limping along at an anemic annual
growth rate of 1.7 percent from April through June, actually grew at
a healthy 2.7 percent rate.
   As a consequence of all the revisions, the gloom-and-doom
forecasts of a month a go that a recession was imminent have been
tossed out the window. Replacing them is the new upbeat assessment
that the economy will continue cruising ahead at a healthy clip for
the rest of the year.
   While there are plenty of red faces accompanying the sudden
turn-about in forecasts, a lot more is at stake than the reputations
of high-paid analysts employed by major banks and investment houses.
   Government officials from the White House to the Federal Reserve
depend on accurate economic data in setting economic policy. Wrong
statistics can produce policies that throw tens of thousands of
people out of work needlessly or kick the economy into an
inflationary spiral.
   Many private economists say the problem lies in major budget
cutbacks in the statistic gathering agencies during the Reagan years.
   ``The problem with the statistics has gotten worse because they
don't have enough money to do a proper job,'' said Michael Evans,
who heads a Washington economic consulting firm. ``Some day, policy
mistakes based on bad statistics will end up sending the country
into a recession.''
   Some economists believe the country may face a resurgence of
inflation six months down the road because because of decisions that
the Federal Reserve made in June and July based on the bad
statistics.
   Viewing the extremely weak original reports on consumer spending
and employment growth, Fed policymakers decided to lower interest
rates to jumpstart a sluggish economy and avert a recession. The
revised data show that the economy, far from being sluggish, was
actually growing at a healthy rate last spring.
   ``I believe if the Fed knew then what they know now, they would
not have eased,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the Boston
Co., an investment house. ``They helped to propel a basically strong
economy even more and thus they now run the risk of losing the
battle on inflation down the road.''
   Sinai and other economists worry that by spurring growth when a
stimulus wasn't really necessary, the Fed will end up making
inflationary pressures worse next year.
   They maintain that when prices start rising faster then, the Fed
will have to clamp down so hard on growth that it could topple the
country into the first economic downturn since the 1981-82 recession.
   The government's reports on factory orders and retail sales have
been notoriously unreliable at times in the past and analysts have
grown accustomed to looking at the figures with skepticism.
   What has economists most in a tizzy now is that the Labor
Department's monthly employment report _ generally considered one of
the most accurate economic measurements _ veered so far off the mark
earlier this year. Almost half the actual job growth in April, May
and June was missed in the original reports.
   Lois Plunkett, an official with the department's Bureau of Labor
Statistics, said three consecutive monthly revisions of such
magnitude is unusual. The average upward monthly revision in job
growth for the three months was just under 90,000, compared with
revisions averaging 47,000 jobs monthly over the past five years.
   ``We have been getting better over the years but we feel we could
improve further'' with additional resources, Ms. Plunkett said.
   Michael Boskin, President Bush's chief economic adviser, has
called the quality of government statistics a ``serious problem.''
And an interagency task force assigned to recommend changes is now
reviewing the situation.
   Former Commerce Undersecretary Robert Ortner, who was in charge
of many of the economic reports during the Reagan administration,
said the answer does not lie simply in providing more money to
collect and analyze the data.
   Some surveys that now rely on business providing data voluntarily
may have to be made mandatory to insure adequate responses, Ortner
said. For other reports the solution may be as simple as delaying
them a few more days while more data is gathered, he said.
   The Commerce Department did just that last year with its
merchandise trade reports after problems with collecting data
produced wildly unreliable figures on the nation's monthly trade
deficits.
   But Ortner failed in getting another report on new orders to
factories for durable goods delayed for one week in order to get
better information. When he suggested the idea, Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan strongly objected, Ortner said.
   ``Greenspan wanted to have as much information as he could as
early as possible for the conduct of monetary policy,'' Ortner said.
``You always face the trade-off between timeliness and accuracy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 0843EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ward'sClothing     09-05 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ward's Clothing,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Montgomery Ward Aims for Share of Clothing Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montgomery Ward &amp; Co., which fought its way back
from collapse four years ago on the strength of electronics and
appliances, is preparing to battle for a share of the lucrative
retail clothing market.
   Next month, the Chicago-based retailer will unveil a new west
suburban store on the Niles-Skokie border containing what it hopes
will be a successful formula for men and women's casual and career
clothing.
   The push comes at a time when general retailers like Sears,
Roebuck and Co. see a downturn in consumer spending for durable
goods like refrigerators and color televisions, and are trying to
reclaim customers in the soft-goods arena.
   ``I think I can say for the first time since I've been here I
really have a high level of confidence that we are on the brink of a
strategic rollout of apparel,'' said Ward chairman Bernard Brennan
in a recent interview.
   ``I think where we are now is in a position where apparel can be
a very significant factor in our growth.''
   Brennan, who took Ward through a $3.8 billion leveraged buyout a
year ago, says Ward has little choice but to make the high-margin
clothing business a winner if the retailer wants to keep growing.
   ``Apparel may be 30 percent of (Ward's) business now, but it
drives in all the traffic. We're also reaching an economic period
where there's pressure on big-ticket merchandise, so if we're
accepted in apparel, we'll drive more traffic into the stores.''
   Much of the success of Ward's brand-name, low-price strategy has
been in such areas as Electric Avenue for electronics and
appliances, Home Ideas for home accessories, Gold 'N Gems for
jewelry, and Auto Express, its auto parts aftermarket business.
   Whatever growth Ward has seen in clothing has been in the Kid's
Store, the brand-name children's apparel concept launched last year.
   Now it's the grownups' turn. The effort has been an arduous one,
Brennan says. The company has been working for more than three years
to find the right mix of moderate goods and has gone through several
top executives over that time trying to accomplish its goal.
   The company's new apparel buying office now is run by Dan Levy,
former head of Home Ideas, who also was an executive at Gimbel's and
Kaufman's department stores.
   The casual clothing line for men and women will be similar to
merchandise sold at the Gap, where everything is coordinated by
color and fabric, Brennan says.
   And the company also will sell casual career clothing for men and
women, but no tailored suits or jackets. Ward will carry such brand
names as Gitano, Jordache, Von Furstenburg, Sag Harbor, Lee and
Wrangler, and add more over time.
   Brennan also said Ward will come out with a new private-label
brand ``very soon,'' bearing the name of a celebrity.
   Even with the revamp in apparel, Ward isn't straying from its
main customer base, families with household incomes varying from
$30,000 to $50,000 a year, men and women between the ages of 25 and
45.
   Ward also is in the midst of an aggressive expansion plan for its
department stores and free-standing specialty stores. The company
has said it expects to build four new full-line stores and 22 of its
specialty stores between this year and 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     09-05 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0267</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices opened slightly lower today, the
first day of trading following the long Labor Day weekend.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was down 0.38 at
2,751.71 at 10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Among broader market barometers, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 0.17 to 196.20. On the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 0.11 to 383.85.
   Declining NYSE issues led advances slightly after the first 30
minutes of trading, with 519 down, 450 up and 485 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 19.86 million shares.
   Last week, the Dow average soared to new highs amid an upbeat
attitude about the nation's economy. Several reports showed
continued economic strength, including the August employment report,
which buoyed market sentiment.
   The news indicated that the economy isn't slowing as much as
expected, which has raised fears that the Federal Reserve may raise
interest rates instead of lowering them.
   On Friday, the Dow industrials rose 14.82 to a new high of
2,752.09, surpassing the previous peak of 2,743.36 reached a week
ago and bringing its gain for last week to 19.73 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones Friday by about 9 to
5, with 897 up, 498 down and 561 unchanged. Volume on the floor of
the Big Board came to 133.30 million shares, down from 143.42
million on Thursday.
   The nation's financial markets were closed on Monday for the
Labor Day holiday.
