<DOCNO> AP890905-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1120EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Saab 1stLd-Writethru   09-05 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Saab, 1st Ld-Writethru,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Plunges, Saab Confirms Talks With Ford</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-7 to show stock exchange urged release of Saab
statement and trading of Saab shares.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporting plunging profits in its
carmaking division, Sweden's Saab-Scania AB has confirmed it is in
negotiations with Ford Motor Co. about a possible collaboration.
   Reports have said that the automotive and aircraft giant may sell
a major stake in its carmaking operation to Ford. Ford has declined
to comment.
   Georg Karnsund, Saab's president and chief executive officer,
refused to disclose details of the talks Monday, saying Saab signed
an agreement of confidentiality with Ford.
   ``Discussions are taking place between the two companies. The
purpose of these discussions is to explore whether there are any
possibilities of closer cooperation in various areas of the
automotive business,'' Karnsund said in a statement cleared with
Ford.
   The statement, released at the urging of the Stockholm stock
exchange, said the talks were ``still at an early stage.''
   Karnsund said no further information would be released until the
talks were concluded. He said Saab also was talking with other
carmakers, but declined to identify them.
   Prices of Saab shares, meanwhile, rose slighly on the Stockholm
market Tuesday following Saab's announcement.
   Sales in the United States, once Saab's most profitable market,
dropped 15 percent in the first six months of the year, the company
said. The U.S. troubles dragged down the profit of the car division
by 30 percent to the equivalent of $139 million in the period, it
said.
   Karnsund said Saab needed to increase volume to overcome the
crisis, and ``this applies regardless of whether we go it alone or
start to collaborate with another car manufacturer.''
   The Saab-Scania group could carry the ailing car division, but
``we would achieve bigger volumes faster through collaboration with
a suitable partner,'' he said.
   A six-month report showed that despite setbacks in passenger
cars, Saab-Scania remained one of Sweden's most successful
companies, with sales of $3.5 billion, up 12 percent over the same
period in 1988.
   Its backlog of orders for commercial aircraft totaled $1.8
billion, compared with $1.2 billion this time last year, the report
said.
   Rumors have ciruclated for months that Saab might sell off its
problematic car division.
   A deal with Ford that includes the profitable Scania truck
division would give the American company a European foothold in
heavy vehicles to compete with General Motors Corp., which signed a
cooperation agreement two years ago with AB Volvo, Sweden's leading
automaker.
   Swedish newspapers reported last week that Saab was negotiating
to sell Ford a 20 percent to 40 percent share of the car division.
Ford reportedly was bidding for a majority share.
   Jan-Erik Larsson, head of the car division, said last week that
Saab ``will remain a Swedish automaking company,'' indicating that a
buyout was not being considered.
   Karnsund denied speculation that Saab might sell the division to
Volvo.
   The company president blamed declining U.S. sales on a slump in
the industry, making 1989 the worst year since 1981. Cars built to
U.S. specifications could not be diverted elsewhere when the market
sagged. He said about 3,000 unsold cars were sitting on U.S. lots.
   Karnsund also attributed the drop in profits to a steep rise in
costs, including a heavy investment in U.S. marketing.
   The company report said half-year sales by the car division rose
2.4 percent to $1.3 billion, despite a drop in the number of cars
sold to 58,700 from 61,400 worldwide.
   The group also is considering selling some of its component
plants and plans to cut up to 2,000 workers over two years.
Saab-Scania employs 50,653 after adding more than 600 this year,
Karnsund said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
