<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-05 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Turn Mixed After Lower Opening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade with new export
demand offsetting the bearish implications of last week's good
growing weather in the Midwest.
   After a lower opening, the wheat market got a boost from
indications China bought 200,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat over the
weekend, an unexpected purchase.
   Corn and soybeans received early support from signs that Mexico
was in the market for U.S. corn and from forecasts for below-normal
temperatures next week in the Midwest.
   Fears of frost damage to the corn and soybean crops lingered in
the markets this morning, although prospects for a freeze in the
Corn Belt were considered dim.
   ``There was none over the weekend and there's not going to be any
this week,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``There's a chance for frost next week but
I wouldn't count on it.''
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents lower to 4 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.95 a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1 cent lower with September at $2.32\ a bushel; oats were }
cent lower to 2} cents higher with September at $1.36 a bushel;
soybeans were 4\ cents lower to { cent higher with September at
$5.81 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle futures were .10 cent to .55 cent lower with October
at 72.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .62 cent
lower with October at 81 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent to
.73 cent lower with October at 39.45 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .42 cent to .70 cent lower with February at 43.45 cents
a pound.
   Livestock futures settled lower on Friday while pork bellies
advanced.
</TEXT>
