<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-05 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Sharply In Europe, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose sharply against most major
currencies in European trading Tuesday despite reports of
central-bank intervention.
   Gold prices declined.
   Foreign-exchange dealers said the dollar rose on confidence that
U.S. interest rates would remain firm for some time and could even
move higher.
   After the Bank of Japan intervened against the dollar's rise, 11
other central banks sold dollars for West German marks or their own
currencies. But their effort was almost fruitless.
   Some dealers said the dollar could rise to 2 West German marks
this week, a level it last reached on June 15.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 146.65 Japanese yen, up from 146.13. In London
the dollar closed higher at 147.00 yen.
   One British pound cost $1.5385 late Tuesday in London, cheaper
than $1.5532 Monday.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Monday's
late rates: 1.9895 West German marks, up from 1.9780; 1.7170 Swiss
francs, up from 1.7085; 6.7055 French francs, up from 6.6725; 2.2415
Dutch guilders, up from 2.2282; 1.1811 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1815; and 1,425.50 Italian lire, up from 1,417.50.
   Gold bullion closed in London at $358.25 a troy ounce, down from
$359 late Monday. The late Zurich bid price was $358.30 an ounce,
off 70 cents.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $359.35 an ounce, up from
$358.45.
   Silver bullion rose in London to $5.07 a troy ounce, up from
$5.05.
</TEXT>
