<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1438EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RigCount     09-05 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rig Count,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rig Count Increases by 27 to 936</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of working oil and gas rigs in the
country jumped by 27 to 936 last week, fueled by double-digit
increases in Texas and Oklahoma, a widely-followed index of drilling
activity said Tuesday.
   A year ago, the count stood at 933. The index had risen by six
the previous week and by 45 two weeks earlier.
   The Baker Hughes rig count reflects the number of rigs actively
exploring for oil as of last Friday, but not those actively
producing oil.
   Houston-based Hughes Tool Co., an oil toolmaker company that
merged with Baker International Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept
track of the rig count since 1940.
   In December 1981, at the height of the oil boom, the rig count
reached a peak of 4,500. But oil prices plunged to less than $10 per
42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, prompting a collapse in the
rig count that bottomed out at 663 _ the lowest since Hughes began
compiling figures.
   Texas, which dropped by 14 a week ago, showed a 20-rig gain in
the most recent count, while Oklahoma was up by 16.
   Among other major oil producing states, Colorado and Wyoming each
were up by three, while Kansas increased by two. Louisiana lost 11
rigs, while California, New Mexico and North Dakota each were down
by two and Ohio and Pennsylvania each dropped one. Michigan was
unchanged.
</TEXT>
