<FIRST>r f AM-Philippines-Economy     09-05 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Economy,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippine Economic Growth Slows Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Tuesday that
the pace of growth in the Philippine economy slowed during the first
half of the year as prices continued to rise.
   The government's National Statistical Coordinating Board made the
announcement in a report submitted to President Corazon Aquino.
   The Board said the gross national product, which measures the
value of goods and services, grew 5.33 percent during the first six
months of this year, down from the 6.54 percent rate during the same
period in 1988.
   The government had predicted the economy would grow at an average
of 6.5 percent this year.
   The Board also said prices of good and services in August rose
11.7 percent, higher than the 10.3 percent rise in July.
</TEXT>
