<FIRST>r f AM-HiringSurvey     09-05 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hiring Survey,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Employment Outlook Dimmed By Softness In Northeast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer U.S. companies plan to increase hiring in
the final quarter of 1989 than the previous year, due largely to
softness in the Northeast, a survey of U.S. firms released Tuesday
found.
   The survey, conducted by Manpower Inc., a temporary employment
agency, found that 26 percent of nearly 14,000 employers questioned
by telephone planned to increase hiring from October through
December, down from 28 percent in 1988.
   Companies located in the Northeast had the least ambitious hiring
plans, with 22 percent saying they would add to their staff, a
seven-year low, vs. 27 percent last year.
   Nationally, 9 percent of the firms surveyed planned staff
reductions, compared with 8 percent last year. In the Northeast, 11
percent said they would cut staff, up from 8 percent in 1988.
   Manpower President Mitchell S. Fromstein said the softness in the
Northeast was particularly evident in the manufacturing sectors,
where hiring plans were substantially below those of other regions.
   Overall, retailers had the most optimistic hiring plans,
reflecting the upcoming lucrative holiday season, Fromstein said.
   On Friday, the Labor Department reported that August unemployment
held steady at 5.2 percent with the creation of more than 200,000
non-farm jobs, excluding the effects of phone strikes.
   The respondents to Manpower's quarterly survey included private
companies and government agencies in 437 cities.
</TEXT>
