<FIRST>u f AM-TreasuryBills     09-05 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Treasury Bills,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Bills Fall in Tuesday's Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in Tuesday's auction to the lowest level in several
weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 7.88 percent, down from 7.94 percent
last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 7.87 percent, down from 7.88 percent last
week.
   The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 7.65
percent on July 31 and six-month bills averaged 7.85 percent on Aug
21.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.15 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,800.80 and 8.31 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,602.10.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Tuesday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 8.32
percent last week, down from 8.36 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
