<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2125EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Europe'92-USTV Adv10-2Takes   09-05 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Europe '92-US TV, Adv 10-2 Takes,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, Sept. 10, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Europe '92: Future of U.S. TV Shows in Doubt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RTL-TVi is correct 12th graf, ``Last year ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
looking ahead to Western Europe in 1992, when the 12 nations of the
European Economic Community remove their trade barriers and
interlock their policies and goals.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Once Upon a Time in America'' was one
of the first movies a new European network showed when it went on
the air this year.
   In fact, American shows are increasingly what the 320 million
viewers in the 12 nations of the European Economic Community see
almost every time they turn on their television sets.
   Be it the original ``Batman'' series, the ``Odd Couple,'' ``Star
Trek'' or ``Dallas,'' U.S. programs pervade the airwaves and
European politicians and artists are rallying against them.
   After years of waffling, the EEC member nations will try to
decide in October whether to stem the flood of U.S. programming
through quotas.
   The United States is crying foul, complaining about protectionism
and fearing a loss of millions of dollars in trade.
   But defenders of quotas here say European culture is at stake,
calling for protection as the EEC prepares turn the community into a
single trading bloc by the end of 1992.
   Writing to key members of the EEC-affiliated European Parliament
recently, Carla Hills, the special U.S. trade representative, said
quotas would be ``blatantly discriminatory, patently unjustifiable,
and would almost certainly have a disastrous effect on the U.S.
industry's substantial European earnings.''
   Experts said more homegrown productions may not improve the
overall quality of European television and doubted whether Europe
can produce enough to replace U.S. shows kept out by quotas.
   This decade, many European nations deregulated their television
industries, more than doubling air time, which could be filled only
with more U.S. programs.
   As early as 1982, Culture Minister Jack Lang of France called for
``a real crusade against _ let's call things by their name _ this
financial and intellectual imperialism that no longer grabs
territory, or rarely, but grabs consciousness, ways of thinking,
ways of living.''
   He said he counted more than 200 hours of American shows in one
week on the six French channels.
   Last year, on Belgium's RTL-TVi, a commercial network, 65 percent
of the movies, 83 percent of the series and 70 percent of the
cartoons were American-made, according to parliamentary records.
   Quotas would hit the U.S. television industry hard as it is
increasingly using international sales to offset huge production
costs.
   George Gerbner of the Annenberg School of Communications in
Philadelphia said in an interview that U.S. producers had ``only
three major buyers in the United States,'' meaning the three big
networks.
   ``And they put the price so low that the domestic market only
takes care of the cost. For a profit they are forced onto the world
market. So there is a strong drive to get into as many markets as
possible.''
   A decade ago, the Western European market for U.S. television
consisted of only a handful of state networks, but more stations
have since gone on the air and the competition for top shows has
driven prices up.
   Lorimar Telepictures Corp., which produces ``Dallas,'' has been
seeing its international revenues rise by about 25 percent annually.
The series, which sold for $12,000 an episode in 1986, yielded four
times as much in 1988.
   Today, Walt Disney Studios gets more than half its overseas
television revenue from EEC countries. The community's business for
U.S. producers swelled to more than $650 million last year from $100
million in 1980.
   The European public continues to gobble up American TV with great
cheer, despite pleas that they should not yield to ``cultural
imperialism.''
   But American programs gave been on European TV screens for a long
time, chiefly because there was little else to chose from.
   As long ago as the 1950s ``there was a void in TV schedules and
only the U.S. producers could work on such a massive scale,'' said
Professor Cees Hamelink of the International Association of Mass
Communication Research in The Hague, Netherlands.
   The process was self-fulfilling. Larry Gross, also of the
Annenberg School, said U.S. television forces audiences to expect a
level of production that Europeans can't match.
   ``To meet them, you have to join them,'' he said in an interview.
   Western Europe's new commercial networks do just that. It is
cheaper to show reruns of ``Taxi,'' ``Alf,'' ``Benson'' and
``Hogan's Heroes'' than to make their own programs or buy more
expensive European series. In any case, major European series are
not likely to be available in sufficient quantities for some time.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Europe'92-USTV Adv10-1stadd   09-05 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Europe '92-US TV, Adv 10-1st add,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, Sept. 10, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>BRUSSELS: some time.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Discussing possible EEC quotas, Jack Valenti, President of the
Motion Picture Association of America, raised the question at a
congressional hearing in Washington earlier this year whether
European producers can ever satisfy European viewers' demands after
so much American television.
   Yet the EEC is moving ahead with plans to protect European
television.
   If not, said Jacques Delors, president of the EEC Commission,
``all televisions will be made in Japan and all programs will be
American.''
   As early as 1984, the EEC suggested a local-content quota of 60
percent. This year, this was watered down to a majority of European
programs ``where practicable.''
   But the European Parliament wanted precise figures and that has
led to a stalemate. The EEC nations will reopen the debate in
October.
   Meanwhile, U.S. television remains a political issue for the left
and, more recently, the extreme right.
   Franz Schoenhuber, leader of the West German Republicans, rang
the theme during election campaigns this year, assailing ``Dallas''
and other U.S. shows on West German television.
   ``We don't want the American way of life,'' he said.
   The French film director Claude Autant-Lara, reflecting the views
of many of his European colleagues, talked about the ``terrifying''
threat to European culture from across the Atlantic.
   Comparing the best in Europe's cultural heritage with American
mass consumerism, Claude Brule, president of France's Union of
Playwrights and Composers, begged Europeans ``not to turn the
grandchildren of Moliere into those of Coca-Cola.''
   ``The Americans are seen as crude and rude and it is a continuing
process,'' said Gross of the Annenberg School.
   ``It is a defensible argument to impose quotas on other cultures,
but the context and the reason have to be different than to think
domestic is good and foreign is bad.''
   The culture split can even get blurred.
   ``Once Upon a Time in America,'' which the Belgian commercial
station VTM showed on its opening weekend last winter, is a U.S.
movie, featuring lots of blood and gore. However, it was directed by
Sergio Leone, an Italian.
   Not all U.S. television gets a bad rap in Europe. Nor does ``Made
in Europe'' guarantee unrivaled quality.
   ``On the day that the British and the continental Europeans can
make programs as good as `Hill Street Blues' they may be in a
position to talk about holding back American cultural imperialism,''
wrote TV critic Christopher Dunkley in Britain's Financial Times
early this year.
   Europeans have produced such successful programs as the British
series ``Jewel in the Crown'' and ``Brideshead Revisited'' and the
quality West German production ``Berlin Alexanderplatz.''
   But they are not the norm.
   Italy's 250 or so mostly local stations lure viewers with endless
jewelry sales, game shows, beauty contests and entertainment
programs where culture is as sparse as clothing.
   Some experts see no European television style, merely a spinoff
of the U.S. style. They point to ``Chateauvallon,'' a French series
titled after a fictive town, or West Germany's ``Das Erbe des
Guldenburgs'' (The Guldenburg Inheritance), which match the family
feuds and romantic escapades of ``Dallas.''
   They doubt whether quotas can change this, since local programs
would have to be mass produced to meet the new demand.
   ``Only the European media giants stand to win when quotas are
introduced,'' said Jean Claude Burgelman, director of Brussels'
Center for the Study of New Media and Information Technology.
   These winners could be Italy's Silvio Berlusconi, the West German
Leo Kirch and Britain's Robert Maxwell, he said in an interview.
``And they have no history of producing television art,'' Burgelman
added.
   ``They will want to make heaps of money and will produce works
for the largest common denominator,'' said Hamelink of The Hague
research group. ``You will get the typical series you get in the
United States: a bit of violence, a bit of mild sex.''
   Said Burgelman: ``Instead of American pulp we will have European
pulp.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
