<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-05 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firmer, Gold Softer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained sharply against most foreign
currencies in active trading Tuesday despite a reported wave of
selling by central banks.
   Gold prices softened. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery settled at $359.60 a troy ounce, down
$1 from Friday. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid
for gold of $358.60 an ounce, off 65 cents from Friday.
   U.S. financial markets were closed Monday for the Labor Day
holiday.
   Currency dealers said the dollar started out strong on continued
confidence that U.S. interest rates would remain firm and could even
move higher. But the dollar ended off its highs of the day largely
due to profit-taking, they said.
   ``There's some pretty good demand out there,'' said Robert Ryan,
a senior trader for Irving Trust Co. ``The market likes the dollar
but it thinks it's slightly overbought.''
   Traders said the market had little reaction to reported efforts
by about a dozen major central banks to drive down the dollar's
value, including the Federal Reserve, which was said to have
intervened three times.
   A recent chain of positive economic data has helped support the
dollar by making U.S. securities more attractive to foreign
investors, thereby increasing the need to convert overseas
currencies into dollars.
   Some dealers say the dollar is poised to move higher because the
economy's apparent strength might prompt the Fed to raise interest
rates to quell inflationary pressures.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 146.65 Japanese yen, up from 146.13. It closed
at 147.00 yen in London, and 146.75 yen in New York, up from 145.945.
   The dollar was stronger against the British pound. Each pound
cost $1.5385 late Tuesday in London, cheaper than $1.5532 Monday.
Sterling fetched $1.5385 in New York, down from $1.55325 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Friday, included: 1.9875 West German marks, up from 1.9780; 1.7150
Swiss francs, up from 1.7085; 6.7000 French francs, up from 6.6725;
1.18065 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1815; and 1,424.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,417.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Monday's late rates
included: 1.9895 West German marks, up from 1.9780; 1.7170 Swiss
francs, up from 1.7085; 6.7055 French francs, up from 6.6725; 2.2415
Dutch guilders, up from 2.2282; 1.1811 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1815; and 1,425.50 Italian lire, up from 1,417.50.
   Gold bullion closed in London at $358.25 an ounce, down from $359
Monday. The late Zurich bid was $358.30 an ounce, off 70 cents.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed up 90 cents at $359.35 an
ounce.
   Silver prices turned mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $5.063 a troy ounce, down from
$5.076 Friday. Silver rose in London to $5.07 an ounce from $5.05.
</TEXT>
