<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-05 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose Tuesday, paced by an
advance in wholesale home heating oil and gasoline.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for October
delivery of No.2 heating oil gained 0.60 cent to 54.57 cents a
gallon. Contracts for more distant months posted similar increases.
The October contract had fallen 0.31 cent on Friday, the previous
trading session.
   Unleaded gasoline for October delivery moved 0.44 cent higher to
53.76 cents a gallon after falling 0.21 cent Friday. The November,
December and January contracts also rose.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, settled at $19.05 per 42-gallon barrel, up
20 cents from Friday, when the contract added 2 cents. Other
delivery months also increased.
   Prices for refined petroleum products benefited from projections
of a pickup in worldwide demand and expectations of a temporary drop
in supply, which normally occurs at the beginning of autumn when
refiners shift part of their capacity to output of heating oil from
gasoline, analysts said.
   Andrew Lebow at E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc. said the
energy market was generally quiet, with crude taking a cue from the
products.
   ``While the crude fundamentals don't look as promising as for the
products ... there is some reluctance to sell the market off in the
face of strong product demand,'' Lebow said.
</TEXT>
