<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 1730EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ForeignAirlines Bjt   09-05 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Airlines, Bjt,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airborne Invasion: Foreign Carriers Snapping Up Pieces of U.S. Rivals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like modern-day conquistadors, foreign airlines
are descending on the New World to buy up pieces of U.S. carriers.
   Major U.S. airlines have become hot properties, stalked by
big-time investors, unions and rival carriers. Foreign airlines are
keen to get in on the action, and the Americans are eager to get the
infusions of capital from abroad.
   More importantly, though, the foreigners are taking equity stakes
in order to help them gain access to the booming U.S. air travel
market, which can augment their passenger traffic.
   Foreign airlines aren't allowed under U.S. law to own domestic
airlines or carry passengers within the United States, so many are
linking up with American partners in special marketing agreements.
As big stockholders, the foreigners can exert even more influence on
the strategies of U.S. carriers.
   ``They're using it to get a toehold in the U.S. market,'' said
Andrew Geller, an airline analyst at Provident National Bank in
Philadelphia.
   British Airways, Scandinavian Airlines System, KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines, Swissair, Japan Air Lines and Australia's Ansett Transport
Industries Ltd. all have snapped up, or are seeking, equity stakes
in U.S. carriers.
   The attraction is especially strong for European airlines, which
have been seeking ways of positioning themselves to exploit the era
of Common Market deregulation that is set to begin in 1992.
   SAS, the first foreign carrier to buy a stake in a U.S. major,
signed a $50 million cooperation agreement with Texas Air Corp. last
October and holds 9.9 percent of the Houston-based company. SAS
recently has been in talks to buy a stake in struggling Continental
Airlines, one of Texas Air's main subsidiaries.
   ``We had a very limited number of U.S. gateways,'' said Nils Flo,
an SAS spokesman in New York, explaining why the airline entered the
agreement that gave it a ``feeder'' network in the United States.
   A new pilots-and-management proposal to buy United Airlines
parent UAL Corp. for $6.75 billion would include a 15 percent share
for British Airways, which has agreed in principal to invest $750
million. Speculation was rife Tuesday that billionaire oilman Marvin
Davis, who previously made a lower bid, may seek help from another
foreign airline to top the group's offer.
   British Airways' role in the UAL bid is similar to that played by
KLM, which is the foreign partner in the investor group that
recently paid $3.65 billion for Northwest Airlines parent NWA Inc.
in a leveraged buyout.
   Under U.S. law, foreign airlines may not own more than 25 percent
of a domestic carrier, and the Department of Transportation can
object to smaller stakes if it believes the foreign company is
trying to exert control.
   Assistant Transportation Secretary Jeffrey N. Shane said last
week that the department is reluctant to approve such foreign
purchases, partly because there still are many questions about U.S.
airlines' access to European markets after the Common Market's
planned unification in 1992.
   UAL and British Airways, two of the biggest airlines, started
with a marketing agreement back in December 1987 that includes
sharing airport facilities and coordinating schedules.
   A British Airways passenger in London, for example, can book a
flight through to Chicago on one ticket; the British airline would
take him from London to New York, where he could connect to United
for the second leg.
   The venture has been so successful it has increased both
airlines' passenger traffic by around 30 percent, according to Sir
Colin Marshall, British Airways' chief executive officer.
   British Airways ``has methodically extended its presence in
several bold strokes that should improve the company's
already-potent position as international airline markets are
gradually deregulated,'' Michael Armellino and Glenn Engel, analysts
for Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., wrote in a report.
   Another international alliance was struck mainly for defensive
reasons, rather than expansive designs. Delta Air Lines, fearing it
could be a takeover target, recently agreed to sell a 5 percent
share to Swissair. The two also have a marketing agreement, signed
earlier.
   Lufthansa German Airlines disclosed Friday that it is in talks
with AMR Corp., parent of American Airlines, about a possible stake
in American's Sabre computer reservations system.
   Ansett, an Australian conglomerate owned 50-50 by media tycoon
Rupert Murdoch and transportation company TNT Ltd., in August 1987
bought a 20 percent stake in America West Airlines, an aggressive
regional carrier. The two do not have a cooperative agreement, but
America West leases and purchases some of its aircraft from Ansett.
   ``We have a lot in common,'' said Daphne Dicino, an America West
spokeswoman in Tempe, Ariz. ``Basically it's a very positive
experience.''
   HAL Inc., the parent of Hawaiian Airlines, is about 20 percent
owned by Japan Air Lines. A subsidiary of the Japanese carrier plans
to build several hotels in the Hawaiian islands.
   Last week, HAL signed a definitive agreement for its sale for
around $22 million to an investment group that includes former
baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth.
</TEXT>
