<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined Tuesday in quiet
post-holiday trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 7.41 to
2,744.68, still the second highest close ever behind the record high
of 2,752.09 set Friday. The market was closed Monday in observance
of Labor Day.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
826 down, 618 up and 528 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 145.18 million
shares, up from 130.30 million in Friday's session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 175.46 million shares.
   Analysts said there was little activity as many traders did not
return from the long Labor Day weekend. Some program trading and a
selloff to gain profits sent stocks lower after an up-and-down
morning session, traders said.
   Takeover-related buying in the airline and hotel sectors
attracted the most interest, sending prices up there. The Dow
transportation index climbed 5.69 to 1,532.01, another new high.
   ``Takeover names and transportation continue to be the only
things that get any play,'' said Thomas R. Walsh, head of equity
trading for Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
   UAL, parent of United Airlines, rose 3} to 290} amid speculation
that investor Marvin Davis would top a management-led buyout offer
of $300 a share. Other potential takeover targets in the industry
also moved higher. AMR, parent of American Airlines, gained { to 90\
and Delta rose 1] to 81].
   Among hotel stocks, Holiday Corp., owner of Holiday Inn, gained
1] to 81] in reaction to rumors the company turned down a takeover
offer valued at $105 a share. Hilton Hotels, which recently put
itself up for sale, gained 2| to 108}.
   Oil stocks were mostly higher. Mobil was up { to 55|, Chevron
increased ~ to 57~, Arco gained | to 105\. Amoco fell [ to 48\ and
Exxon was down [ to 43~.
   Philip Morris was a leading issue among blue chips, rising 2] to
166~. Other active stocks included Bristol-Myers up } to 50~, IBM up
] to 117}, General Motors unchanged at 50 and Chrysler unchanged at
27.
   Losers on the day included Teledyne, down 3} to 372, Coca Cola,
down 1] to 65|, and three technology companies _ Hewlett-Packard,
which fell 1] to 51}, Honeywell, down 1\ to 87}, and Cray Research,
off 1[ to 43.
   Ford, which is holding talks with the Swedish automaker and
aerospace company Saab-Scania, lost | at 53|.
   Last week, the Dow average soared on a wave of optimism about the
nation's economy. Several reports showed continued economic
strength, including the August employment report that buoyed market
sentiment.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market on Tuesday lost $6.79 billion, or
0.20 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.53 to 195.84.
