<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-BAT     09-05 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-BAT,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders Caught In Takeover Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a booklet sent to BAT Industries PLC
shareholders, hostile raider Sir James Goldsmith has accused the
company's board of attempting to frustrate the $21.6 billion
takeover bid, a published report Tuesday said.
   The Financial Times reported that the 23-page booklet from
Goldsmith's Hoylake Investments Ltd. consortium also attacked the
performance of BAT, a tobacco, retailing and insurance concern.
   Securities and Exchange Commission regulations prohibit Hoylake
from promoting its bid in the United States so the full text of the
booklet was not made available to American journalists.
   BAT shareholders received documents in the mail Tuesday from both
sides in the takeover battle.
   Hoylake sent its booklet on Saturday. BAT on Sunday responded by
describing the Hoylake document as ``highly selective and
misleading.''
   Hoylake has accused BAT of trying to frustrate the offer in U.S.
courts. In its latest document, BAT countered the criticism by
quoting statements made by U.S. officials, including California
Attorney General John Van de Kamp, that support BAT's position.
   ``Goldsmith has tried repeatedly to uncover evidence that BAT has
not performed for shareholders,'' the statement said. ``No feats of
statistical manipulation can disguise the consistent strength of
BAT's outstanding record.''
   The three-page letter called on shareholders to reject the bid
``as decisively as they have done so far by doing absolutely
nothing.''
