<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-05 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Plummet On Producer Sales, Strong Dollar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices tumbled to life-of-contract lows Tuesday on
New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange following a selloff Monday
on the London market that analysts attributed to signs that supplies
will remain abundant.
   On other markets, coffee and cattle futures fell sharply; energy
and wheat futures advanced; and precious metals retreated.
   Cocoa futures settled $75 to $78 lower with the contract for
delivery in September at $1,045 a ton.
   Analysts cited a variety of bearish fundamental and technical
factors behind the market's decline, including rumors that a large
purchase of Ivory Coast cocoa was in danger of falling through, and
reports that Cameroon, another major cocoa producer, had followed
the Ivory Coast's lead in lowering its minimum guaranteed price to
farmers.
   ``There's an implication there that they might be aggressive in
selling cocoa in the future,'' said Arthur Stevenson, an analyst in
New York with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The sell-off occurred on the eve of a meeting of some of the
world's largest cocoa producers to discuss a strategy for restoring
stability to the cocoa market through a strengthening of the
International Cocoa Association cartel.
   But analysts noted that Malaysia, the world's fourth-largest
cocoa producer, was not joining the cartel, so there is little
chance for an effective international agreement.
   Coffee futures fell amid profit-taking in New York after posting
strong gains last week.
   Green, unroasted coffee settled 2.7 cents to 5 cents lower with
September at 84.30 cents a pound.
   Live cattle futures plummeted on signs that an expected drop in
cattle marketings was not materializing.
   Many traders had been convinced that supplies of fattened cattle
would dry up in late summer and early fall due to a drop in
first-and second-quarter feedlot placements.
   But many feedlot operators saw the same pattern developing and
delayed marketing of cattle off of feedlots, hoping to sell them a
little later at higher prices.
   Because so many feedlot operators delayed marketings, the
expected drop in supplies never developed, said Chuck Levitt, senior
livestock analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``Anticipation was the name of the game and everyone responded to
it,'' he said.
   Live cattle settled .13 cent to 1.25 cents lower with October at
72.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .50 cent lower
with October at 81.12 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent to .88
cent lower with October at 39.27 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .45 cent to 1.05 cents lower with February at 43.37 cents a
pound.
   Energy futures prices rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
paced by an advance in wholesale home heating oil and gasoline due
to stronger worldwide demand and expectations for a temporary drop
in supply.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 13 cents to 20 cents
higher with October at $19.05 a barrel; heating oil was .53 cent to
.60 cent higher with October at 54.57 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .45 cent to .68 cent higher with October at 53.76 cents
a gallon.
   Wheat futures posted solid gains on the Chicago Board of Trade in
reaction to improved foreign demand for U.S. wheat while corn and
soybean futures prices retreated in lackluster trading.
   The wheat market was supported by last week's sale of 200,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat to China and indications the Chinese may
have purchased another large shipment over the weekend, analysts
said.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department announced it had
targeted the Philippines for sales of 600,000 metric tons of U.S.
wheat at subsidized prices.
   Wheat settled } cent lower to 5} cents higher with September at
$3.97\ a bushel; corn was { cent to 1} cents lower with September at
$2.32\ a bushel; oats were 2\ cents lower to 1 cent higher with
September at $1.34} a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents lower to } cent
higher with September at $5.81\ a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures retreated slightly in quiet trading on
New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled $1 lower across the board with October at $361.40 a
troy ounce; silver was 1.3 cents to 1.5 cents lower with September
at $5.063 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
