<FIRST>r f AM-PanAm-Florida     09-05 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Am-Florida,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am to Expand Florida Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. announced plans Tuesday to increase its
Florida service by nearly 50 percent as Miami-based Eastern Airlines
enters the seventh month of its leaner, post-strike schedule.
   The expansion, scheduled to begin next month, will increase the
average number of daily Pan Am flights operating in Florida during
the mid-winter from 48 to 70.
   Pan Am acknowledged that the expansion was aimed, at least in
part, at filling the void left by rival Eastern.
   ``It's a big part of it,'' said Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon
in New York.
   On Oct. 1, Pan Am will begin operating three daily flights
between Miami International Airport and Nassau, Bahamas.
   The next phase of expansion will start Oct. 29 with service from
Miami to Philadelphia, Boston, Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and Charlotte,
N.C. Also that day, daily flights to St. Maarten and Antigua from
Miami are scheduled to begin.
   The New York-based carrier will resume service to San Juan,
Puerto Rico, on Dec. 15 with four flights daily from Miami. The
airline stopped flying to San Juan in 1983.
   Other flights planned from Miami include a fifth daily flight to
New York's LaGuardia Airport and a third daily flight to Washington,
D.C.
   New service between New York's Kennedy International Airport and
Ft. Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport in Florida also will
be included in the expansion.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell declined to comment on Pan Am's
plans.
</TEXT>
