<FIRST>u f AM-UAL 2ndLd-Writethru   09-05 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Skeptical of Pilots' Bid For United</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, UAL closed ... to CORRECT closing stock price.
Picks up 10th graf pvs, The market ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unionized machinists and ground crews expressed
doubt Tuesday that a pilot-led takeover attempt worth $6.75 billion
for the parent of United Airlines could succeed because it would
require enormous new debt.
   The Machinists' stance seemed to strengthen the chances that
California investor Marvin Davis could succeed in his rival bid for
UAL Corp.
   Cooperation of by all of the company's workers is seen by some
industry analysts as crucial to the pilot-led offer, which would be
undertaken with management and make UAL the biggest employee-owned
company in the country.
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers
said in a statement that UAL was worth about $2 billion less than
the labor-management offer, which was announced Friday.
   ``We are very skeptical that United Airlines could survive in
today's marketplace with the additional debt that would be placed on
the carrier under this proposal as we understand it, particularly
since the proposed purchase price far exceeds the value of the
airline,'' said John Peterpaul, general vice president of the
Machinists union.
   He said the Machinists had not been invited to participate in any
discussions regarding the labor-management proposal disclosed Friday.
   Hank Krakowski, a spokesman for the United chapter of the Air
Line Pilots Association, said he had not seen the Machinists'
statement and could not comment on it. But, he said, ``it is our
strong desire to have all employees on board this proposal.''
   Meanwhile, UAL's stock price climbed Tuesday amid speculation
that Davis would top the pilot-management offer for UAL of $300 a
share, possibly with help from a foreign carrier.
   UAL closed at $290.75 a share in nationwide New York Stock
Exchange trading, up $3.75 from Friday's close.
   ``The market thinks something else is going to happen,'' said
Andrew Geller, an airline industry analyst with Provident National
Bank in Philadelphia. ``I think there's a fair chance he'll come
back with another bid.''
   Analyst Edward Starkman of PaineWebber Inc. interpreted the
market action as investor caution.
   ``The offer on the table ... is going to be tough to beat,'' he
said.
   Davis, a California billionaire who put UAL in play last month
with a $240-a-share offer that he later sweetened to $275, was
reportedly seeking the help of foreign airlines in an attempt to
outbid the insider group.
   The New York Times quoted an unidentified source in the Davis
camp as saying Davis was talking with European and non-European
carriers.
   The Davis group did not return telephone calls seeking
confirmation of the report.
   Davis previously indicated he might increase his bid to acquire
United, the nation's second-largest airline.
   The bid by the labor-management alliance has financial backing
from British Airways PLC.
   If successful, the labor-management group's plan would result in
75 percent employee ownership, making UAL the country's largest
worker-owned company. British Airways would own 15 percent of the
company and UAL's management, led by Chairman Stephen Wolf, would
hold 10 percent.
   Federal aviation regulators reportedly are concerned with the
involvement of foreign entities in takeovers of U.S. airlines.
Government authorities are expected to closely examine proposed
acquisitions that include non-U.S. backers.
   The 6,300-member United chapter of the pilots union helped devise
the labor-management offer and is the only UAL employee group
committed to participating in a buyout.
   United's 12,700 flight attendants have indicated a willingness to
discuss participation. The Machinists, which represent the company's
mechanics and ground crews, haven't ruled it out but the union's
statement Tuesday strongly suggested they wouldn't participate.
   The pilots have indicated their bid may be partly financed with
pension money. But Brian Freeman, a financial adviser to the
Machinists, has said it is ``inconceivable'' that his group,
representing 25,000 of United's 70,000 workers, would invest pension
funds in UAL.
   Starkman said the pilots would have a difficult time running UAL
without strong support from the other unions.
   ``What really makes this deal go or not is the cooperation of
labor,'' he said.
   UAL has said its board of directors will form a committee to
review the bids for the company.
</TEXT>
