<TEXT>
   Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the credit-rating
agency, said a proposed accounting rule for retirees' medical
benefits would be prone to large errors and distort corporate
balance sheets.
   The proposed rule discussed Tuesday would make companies face up
to reality by listing the future cost of retirees' medical benefits
as a liability on their books.
   Rough estimates of the new liabilities range from $400 billion to
$2 trillion for all U.S. companies.
