<FIRST>u f BC-SaraLeeDesserts 3rdLd-Writethru f0260 09-05 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sara Lee Desserts, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0260,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Says Settlement Reached with Sara Lee</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `In Chicago ...,' to CORRECT spelling of ``mousse''
and to fix typos. Picks up 7th graf, ``The word ... ''.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everybody doesn't like something, but nobody
likes being told a ``light'' cheesecake has fewer calories than the
regular version when it really doesn't, Attorney General Jim Mattox
says.
   Announcing a settlement Tuesday with the Sara Lee Corp., Mattox
said the Chicago-based Sara Lee Corp. will stop advertising that its
``light'' cheesecake and pound cake snacks have fewer calories than
its regular cakes.
   Mattox said that Sara Lee's Light Classics cheesecakes and its
All Butter Pound Cake Snack have more calories and fat than the
original Creme Cheesecake and Original All Butter Pound Cake,
respectively.
   The advertisements for the ``light'' cheesecake and pound cake
were misleading, Mattox said.
   ``Those of us who are weight-watchers and connoisseurs of
desserts need as much help as we can get,'' Mattox said.
``Mislabeling a dessert is unfair to consumers.''
   In Chicago, Sara Lee said the agreement involved the use of the
words ``Light Classics'' on the packaging and advertising of its
French Cheesecake, Strawberry French Cheesecake, Chocolate Mousse
and Strawberry Mousse desserts.
   ``The word `light' appeared in small print and referred to the
desserts' texture,'' said T. Patrick Costello, president of Sara Lee
Bakery's Retail division. ``These products were formulated to
respond to consumers who prefer authentic whipped French-style
cheesecakes and mousses.''
   He said while Sara Lee felt the objection ``has no merit in
fact,'' the company decided to settle the dispute ``because it will
save us additional, costly legal expenses.''
   Under the settlement, reached with Mattox and the attorneys
general of eight other states, Sara Lee agreed to stop the
advertising, to display the per-serving calorie content of its
products, and said any product labeled ``light'' will contain no
more than two-thirds of the calories of the product to which it is
being compared, Mattox said.
   The company also will pay each state $10,000 in investigative
costs, Mattox said. The other states involved in the settlement are
California, Illinois, Iowa, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Missouri, New
York and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Shrimpers-Turtles 1stLd-Writethru f0246 09-05 0959</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shrimpers-Turtles, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0246,0982</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Orders ``Trap Doors'' In Shrimp Nets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd graf pvs to UPDATE with shrimper comment;
INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf pvs, ``There is ...,'' to ADD that decision
takes effect Friday and to elaborate on penalty and grace period; picks
up 9th graf pvs, `Knauss said ...'. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department ordered shrimp
fishermen Tuesday to install ``trap door'' devices in their nets to
protect endangered sea turtles.
   The decision came after months of controversy during which Gulf
Coast shrimpers argued the requirement would threaten their
livlihood.
   Shrimpers immediately denounced the government order and
suggested some fishermen may not comply with the regulation, despite
a maximum $20,000 fine per violation.
   ``It's going to drive a lot of people out of business,''
maintained Jimmy Russell, president of the 200-boat Brownsville-Port
Isabel Shrimp Producers Association on the Texas coast. ``I wouldn't
be surprised if they have a lot of people tell them they're not
going to do it.''
   The government directive came under a court order requiring the
Commerce Department take action to protect the turtles, thousands of
which drown yearly when caught in the nets of shrimp fishermen,
primarily in the Gulf of Mexico.
   The question of how to protect the turtles prompted lawsuits by a
half dozen environmental groups seeking to protect the turtles and
charges from shrimp fishermen groups that the use of the trap door
devices will cause them to lose a significant part of their daily
catch.
   Last July, Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher suspended
enforcement of a regulation requiring the devices after angry Gulf
Coast shrimpers blockaded shipping channels along the Texas coast
and threatened violence against law officers and the Coast Guard if
the requirement were enforced.
   Among the species to be protected by the so-called ``turtle
excluder devices'' _ or TEDs _ are the Kemp's ridley, leatherneck
and hawksbill, all of which are listed as endangered species, and
the loggerhead and green se turtles which are listed as being
threatened.
   In making the announcement, John A. Knauss, undersecretary of
commerce, said that under the federal Endangered Species Act ``the
only way to ensure protection of these vanishing species is through
the use of TEDs.''
   ``There is no other choice,'' Knauss said in a statement.
   The decision takes effect Friday.
   Commerce spokesman Brian Gorman said violators could be fined as
much as $20,000 per violation, although penalties likely will be in
the $8,000 range in most cases. Fishermen will have a grace period
until Oct. 15 where all or some of the fine would be suspended if
the violator installed the required net equipment.
   Knauss said attempts to protect the turtles by limiting the
length of time that shrimpers' nets are in the water _ an approach
that has been tried in recent months _ was insufficient to protect
the turtles.
   The decision immediately was hailed by environmental group which
had filed suit seeking the government to require that the trap door
devices be used by Gulf Coast shrimpers. Many shrimpers off the
south Atlantic coast already use the devices.
   ``The decision is certainly what we had hoped for,'' said Michael
Weber, vice president of the Center for Marine Conservation. He
added, however, that he expects possible legal attemps by shrimpers
to get the decision reversed or pressure in Congress to have the
regulation changed.
   ``Basically we're pleased, but we're sorry it took so long and we
had to jump through so many legal hoops,'' said Charles Miller, a
spokesman for the National Wildlife Federation. ``At this point the
turtles are going to have fighting chance.''
   The controversy over the use of the so-called TEDs has dominated
this year's Gulf Coast shrimping season.
   Last May, the Commerce Department directed that the trap-door
devices be installed by shrimp fishermen in the Gulf Coast where an
estimated 11,000 sea turtles are reportedly drown annually when
caught in the nets.
   But the shrimpers loudly protested use of the TEDs, an
oval-shaped metal grate about four feet in diameter that is place
inside the funnel-like shrimp nets to allow large animals such as
turtles to be diverted and escape through a special trap door.
   The shrimpers argued that the devices also cause them to lose
large amounts of shrimp _ as much as 40 percent of the catch,
according to some fishermen. Environmentalists have argued that such
assertions are wrong and that at worst only about 2 percent of the
shrimp catch is affected, and possibly less if the TEDs are used
properly.
   Because of economic concerns, Mosbacher ordered a two-month delay
in enforcing the federal requirement for the devices. In July, after
sometimes violent protests erupted among some Gulf Coast shrimp
fishermen over the use of TEDs, Mosbacher gave the shrimpers a
choice of using the devices or limiting their thrawl times.
   The federal courts, however, ordered a final rule to be issued by
Sept. 8, prompting the Commerce Department decision Tuesday to
return to requiring the use of the trap door devices.
   Environmentalists warn that several of the sea turtle species _
especially the Kemp's ridley _ may be doomed to extinction in the
coming decades if they are not protected from shrimpers nets. The
number of female Kemp's ridley sea turtles nesting each year has
declined from some 42,000 in the 1940s to no more than 700 today,
according to James Ross, an expert on sea turtles.
   Ross said that from 600 to 1,600 Kemp's ridely turtles are killed
each year often after the young turtles get in the way of the
shrimping nets. The decline of the species is estimated at about 3
percent a year, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890905-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2151EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MCA-Azoff 1stLd-Writethru f0248 09-05 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MCA-Azoff, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0248,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azoff Quits as Chairman of MCA's Music Unit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 1st graf pvs to UPDATE with Azoff comment;
DELETES 10th graf pvs, `Azoff ``has ... ,' as outdated. Picks up 11th graf,
`The trade ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Azoff, who in six years
resurrected MCA Records from a sleepy also-ran to the No. 2 pop
music label, quit Tuesday to form his own entertainment company.
   ``What I want to do is a broad-based company, the cornerstone of
which will be a record company,'' he said in a telephone interview.
``Basically, I intend to start the first major independent of the
'90s with major funding.''
   Azoff said he was evaluating an offer from MCA to fund the
venture. Asked if there had been other offers, he said, ``The phones
always ring.''
   Before joining MCA, Azoff achieved prominence by his deft
handling of the careers of such rock superstars as the Eagles, Boz
Scaggs and Steely Dan. Many thought him crazy when he decided in
April 1983 to join the company he once characterized as the ``Music
Cemetery of America.''
   ``The roster I inherited was uniquely interesting,'' Azoff said
in a letter to MCA employees Tuesday. ``Could we ever forget The
Catholic Girls, MCA's answer to the Go-Go's; Zoom, the black
heavy-metal band; and Helen Reddy, best remembered as a nun in
`Airport '75.'''
   After he joined MCA, the company dropped 41 of its 46 acts and
started rebuilding, often resurrecting the careers of other labels'
discards.
   Most significantly, Azoff broadened the label's base beyond rock
and jazz into black music, by signing such acts as Klymaxx,
Stephanie Mills, Patti LaBelle and Gladys Knight, and contemporary
country, with artists such as The Judds, Lyle Lovett, George Strait
and Reba McEntire.
   ``Today our roster boasts some of the most impressive names in
contemporary including ... Bobby Brown, Elton John, Boston, Tiffany,
Jody Watley, New Edition, Pebbles and Fine Young Cannibals,'' Azoff
said.
   A proxy statement shows Azoff was paid about $5 million in salary
and stock last year. Also in 1988, Billboard magazine reported MCA
had become the No. 2 pop label behind CBS Records. MCA was ranked
12th in 1983, the year Azoff signed on.
   In a statement, MCA said Azoff resigned as an MCA Inc. vice
president and as chairman of its Music Entertainment Group, and was
working on his future plans, including possible business ventures
with MCA.
   Reports had circulated for several months that Azoff wanted to
run his own company along the lines of David Geffen, who controls
the powerful music and movie company named after him.
   The trade newspaper Daily Variety said Azoff had been variously
reported to be negotiating with Polygram, Warner Communications and
Boston Ventures, the investment firm with which MCA teamed last year
to buy Motown Records, as well as MCA itself.
   MCA president and chief operating officer Sid Sheinberg referred
to those talks in a news release.
   ``We are very hopeful that negotiations for us to continue to be
involved with Irving in exciting new music entertainment
undertakings will come to a successful and mutually beneficial
conclusion,'' he said.
   Azoff will be succeeded as chairman of MCA Music by Al Teller, a
former CBS Records president who joined MCA last year as a corporate
vice president and president and chief operating officer of MCA
Records.
   Statistics for MCA's Music and Entertainment Group help convey
how Azoff converted MCA into a challenger to such recording giants
as CBS Records and Warner Bros. Records.
   For the 1982 fiscal year, MCA's recording and music-publishing
operations grossed $141.7 million; for fiscal 1988, the Music
Entertainment Group, which includes home-video revenues, grossed
$661 million.
   During his career at MCA, Azoff was plagued by allegations of
conflict of interest because of his partial ownership of three
outside companies that did business with MCA.
   In May 1986, MCA bought the companies: Front Line Management,
which handled Don Henley, Stevie Nicks, Jimmy Buffett and Heart;
Full Moon Records, a small label whose artists included Dan
Fogelberg and Chicago; and Facilities Merchandising Inc., which
handles vending of T-shirts, caps and other novelties at more than
40 arenas nationwide.
   Under Azoff, MCA Records boycotted an industry move in 1985 to
put warning stickers on records that contain ``obscene'' material.
   Besides the record company, the Music Entertainment Group
includes MCA's music-publishing business; its records and home video
distribution unit; the Universal Amphitheater in Universal City and
amphitheaters in Atlanta, Dallas and Denver; and several other
businesses.
   Azoff will continue to act as a consultant for the facilities
merchandising unit, which Azoff founded before joining MCA.
</TEXT>
