<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FirstJersey     09-05 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-First Jersey,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second First Jersey Broker Admits Money Laundering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former First Jersey Securities Inc. broker
on Tuesday admitted helping launder $450,000 of his clients' money,
partly at the direction of a branch manager who also was identified
as a top-ranking member of the troubled firm.
   Kevin O'Donohue, 32, was the second employee of First Jersey's
Cherry Hill office to admit to charges in a federal money laundering
probe.
   At his plea, Donohue named three other Cherry Hill employees not
previously said to be involved in the scheme, bringing to seven the
number of First Jersey brokers implicated.
   First Jersey sold its retail network in February 1987. Donohue's
admissions concerned money laundering from February 1984 to October
1985.
   A call for comment to the company's headquarters in New York was
not returned.
   Under a plea agreement with prosecutors, O'Donohue admitted a
conspiracy charge and will cooperate with the investigation. In
exchange, eight other counts will be dropped.
   O'Donohue faces five years in prison and a $250,000 fine when he
is sentenced, which U.S. District Judge John Bissell scheduled for
Nov. 9.
   He admitted helping to hide a couple's funds from the Internal
Revenue Service by taking large amounts of cash, breaking them into
cashiers checks smaller than $10,000 and depositing the checks in
the couple's brokerage account. First Jersey records also were
falsified, he said.
   By law, transactions involving more than $10,000 must be reported
to the government.
   The couple, identified in the indictment as Theodore and Barbara
Schallenhammer, used the funds to buy stock. Assistant U.S. Attorney
Andrew Rossner said they were not charged. Their attorney, Morris
Pinsky, did not immediately return a phone message.
   Donohue said branch manager Jack Mondel directed him and another
broker to translate the Schallenhammer's money into cashiers checks.
Rossner said Mondel was a regional vice president of First Jersey.
   Mondel could not be reached for comment and Rossner did not know
his whereabouts or lawyer's name.
   Paul Fau of Mount Laurel, a former branch manager in Cherry Hill,
pleaded guilty in June to money laundering. Former Cherry Hill
broker Arthur Basmajian of Pittsburgh awaits trial, as does Dominic
Padula of Paterson.
   Padula was accused of helping launder $430,000 for one customer's
account between August 1983 and November 1985. Donohue said two
other brokers who have not been charged were involved in the money
laundering.
   First Jersey, founded by high-flying financier Robert E. Brennan,
and some of its employees have been the subject of investigations by
federal prosecutors and the Securities and Exchange Commission for
15 years.
   Charges include stock manipulation, illegal campaign
contributions, excessive markups and perjury. Brennan has denied
improprieties.
   The firm settled allegations of fraudulent securities practices
with the SEC in 1984.
</TEXT>
