<FIRST>r f BC-UAW-Japan     09-05 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UAW-Japan,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Creates Department To Deal With Non-U.S. Carmakers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers union on Tuesday announced
the creation of a new department to deal with automakers other than
the Big Three.
   The department, called the Transnational and Joint Ventures
Department, will be directed by UAW President Owen Bieber. It will
coordinate the union's activities at U.S. auto plants owned by
overseas-based companies and joint ventures.
   Currently, Honda Motor Co., Mazda Motor Corp., Nissan Motor Corp.
and Toyota Motor Corp., all based in Japan, operate their own
automaking plants in the United States.
   There are two joint ventures in operation, involving General
Motors Corp. and Toyota, and Chrysler Corp. and Mitsubishi Motors
Corp. Ford and Mazda have a production agreement involving Mazda's
plant in Flat Rock, Mich.
   The UAW recently lost a representation election at Nissan's
Smyrna, Tenn., plant.
</TEXT>
