<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Cliff'sNotes     09-05 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cliff's Notes,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Clears Distribution of Parody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spy, the irreverant New York humor magazine, can
distribute its spoof of Cliff's Notes, the long-established study
guide to the classics, a federal appeals panel ruled Tuesday.
   Three judges of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals vacated a
lower court's injunction that banned the distribution of Spy Notes,
a parody that used the Cliff's Notes format to also poke fun at what
Spy Co-Editor Kurt Andersen called the ``hip urban novel.''
   The one-page ruling did not give the reasons for the decision.
The judges said a full opinion would follow.
   ``It is a happy day for us and the First Amendment,'' Andersen
said.
   As a result of the ruling, Spy Notes is expected to be on sale at
bookstores around the country by the week of Sept. 18, said
Jacqueline Deval, a spokeswoman for the parody's publisher, Bantum
Doubleday Dell Publishing Group Inc.
   Spy Notes gives humorous plot summaries, commentary and questions
for review on contemporary novels like ``Bright Lights, Big City''
by Jay McInerney and ``Slaves of New York'' by Tama Janowitz.
   It also includes the Novel-O-Matic, a slide rule-like device that
Andersen says allows readers to create their own 1980s novel.
   Cliff's Notes Inc. sued the publishing concern because it claimed
the parody, whose cover has Cliff's Notes distinctive
yellow-and-black stripes, looked too much like the real thing and
would confuse consumers.
   U.S. District Judge Shirley Wohl Kram granted Cliff's Notes a
preliminary injunction on Aug. 2 and Doubleday immediately appealed.
   ``Needless to say, we're sorely disappointed by the ruling,''
said Cliff's Notes attorney William Hart. He said he could not
comment further until the appeals panel issued a full opinion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
