<FILEID>AP-NR-09-05-89 2304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-France-TakeoverBid     09-05 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-France-Takeover Bid,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suez Appears To Have Won France's Biggest Takeover Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compagnie Financiere de Suez on Tuesday appeared to
have won France's largest takeover battle after it sweetened its bid
for Compagnie Industrielle and its insurance unit and reached a
truce with dissident shareholders.
   Analysts said the accord and sweetened tender offer, valued at
$4.1 billion, means Suez, a financial holding company, should have
no difficulty winning control of Industrielle and Compagnie
Financiere du Groupe Victoire, France's second-largest insurer.
   Suez announced it was raising its offer from the equivalent of
about $1,940 a share to about $2,208, a share for Industrielle
stock. It will boost its bid for common stock in Groupe Victoire
from $298 to $340 and increase its offer for the non-voting stock
from $149 to $170.
   The initial tender offer valued Industrielle and Groupe Victoire
at about $3.5 billion.
   A spokesman for Industrielle confirmed that such an agreement had
been reached.
   As part of the accord, Industrielle President Jean-Marc Vernes
has agreed to tender the 25 percent stake in Industrielle which is
held by Societe Centrale d'Investissement, the announcement said.
Vernes holds 34 percent of Societe Centrale d'Investissement stock.
   Suez already controls about 30 percent of Groupe Victoire, and 18
percent of Industrielle. Gaining control of Industrielle would
automatically give it a majority stake in Group Victoire.
   Industrielle currently has about 40 percent in its insurance unit.
   The move follows allegations last week by Vernes that Suez had
offered him 3,000 francs, or about $478, per share above its public
stock offer. Suez denied the charges but negotiated the agreement
with Vernes, who until now had adamently opposed the offer.
   Trading in shares of Industrielle and Victoire stock, suspended
last month, resumed Monday but was suspended again Tuesday when word
of the agreement was made public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
